                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Binary search is the canonical O(log n) technique. Every FAANG interview expects it on sorted arrays, rotated arrays, and — critically — on the answer space itself (binary search on value, not index).</div>
                    <div class="core-box"><strong>Core Idea:</strong> Maintain invariant: answer is always in [lo, hi]. Choose mid; decide which half to discard based on a monotone predicate. Template: lo=0, hi=n-1; while(lo≤hi); always shrink the search space.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants</div>
                    <div class="pill-grid">
                        <span class="pill">Classic sorted array</span><span class="pill">Leftmost / first occurrence</span><span class="pill">Rightmost / last occurrence</span><span class="pill">Rotated sorted array</span><span class="pill">Rotated with duplicates</span><span class="pill">BS on answer space (minimize)</span><span class="pill">BS on answer space (maximize)</span><span class="pill">BS on floating point</span><span class="pill">2D matrix search</span><span class="pill">Peak finding</span><span class="pill">BS + greedy validation</span><span class="pill">Exponential search</span><span class="pill">Unbounded/infinite array</span><span class="pill">K-th element (two arrays)</span>
                    </div>

