            <div class="topic-card" id="tp5">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">05</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">Kadane's Algorithm</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Algorithms</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Technique · DP</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">28 problems · max subarray, circular, product, deletion, 2D, tree variants</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Kadane's Algorithm is a linear-time DP technique that finds the maximum-sum contiguous subarray by maintaining one invariant: at each index i, compute the best subarray sum ending exactly at i — either extend the previous best or start fresh. The recurrence <code>maxEndingHere = max(nums[i], maxEndingHere + nums[i])</code> is deceptively simple, yet it underpins problems spanning circular arrays, products, 2D matrices, absolute values, and DP-on-tree variants. It appears consistently in top-tier interviews because (a) naive O(n²) is trivially wrong, (b) the optimal is O(n), and (c) extensions like circular arrays and product subarrays test whether a candidate truly understands the invariant or has merely memorised the code.</div>
                    <div class="core-box"><strong>Core Invariant:</strong> <code>maxEndingHere = max(nums[i], maxEndingHere + nums[i])</code> — start fresh when maxEndingHere &lt; 0 because a negative prefix can never help. Global answer = max over all maxEndingHere values.<br><br><strong>State:</strong> dp[i] = max subarray sum ending at i &nbsp;·&nbsp; <strong>Recurrence:</strong> dp[i] = max(nums[i], dp[i−1] + nums[i]) &nbsp;·&nbsp; <strong>Preferred:</strong> Bottom-up, O(1) space with rolling variables (maxEndingHere, maxSoFar). Top-down adds call-stack overhead for zero benefit.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="pill-grid">
                        <span class="pill">Standard max-sum subarray</span>
