                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Linguistic Triggers (keywords in problem statement):</strong><br>
                        • "merge all overlapping intervals" → Classic merge; sort by start, greedy extend<br>
                        • "minimum number of rooms / machines / conference halls" → Count max simultaneous active intervals; sweep-line or min-heap<br>
                        • "non-overlapping" or "no two intervals overlap" → Either removal (greedy) or weighted selection (DP)<br>
                        • "free time / available slots / gaps" → Merge first, enumerate gaps between merged blocks<br>
                        • "insert … into sorted list of intervals" → Three-phase walk (before, overlap, after)
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Structural Triggers (shape of input/output):</strong><br>
                        • Input is <code>int[][] intervals</code> or <code>List&lt;List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt;</code> of [start, end] pairs → Almost always an interval problem<br>
                        • Output is a list of intervals → Almost certainly merge or insert variant<br>
                        • Output is a single integer count where input is intervals → Sweep-line / difference array
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Constraint Triggers (N and value ranges):</strong><br>
                        • N ≤ 10⁵ and values up to 10⁹ → Coordinate compression required; cannot use plain array for difference array<br>
                        • N ≤ 10⁵ and online queries → TreeMap / sorted set, not re-sort every time
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;font-size:.88em;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.55">
<strong>Q1:</strong> Does the problem involve ranges/intervals [start, end] on a linear axis?
  → NO:  Not an interval problem. Stop.
  → YES: Continue.

<strong>Q2:</strong> Are intervals given all at once (offline) or arrive one-by-one (online)?
  → OFFLINE: Continue to Q3.
  → ONLINE:  Go to Q8.

<strong>Q3:</strong> Do you need to COMBINE/COLLAPSE intervals?
  → YES: Q4.    → NO:  Q5.

<strong>Q4:</strong> Do the intervals carry values/profits?
  → NO:  Classic Merge (#1) or Insert (#2).
  → YES: Weighted Job Scheduling DP (#17).

<strong>Q5:</strong> Do you need to COUNT something (rooms, overlaps, groups)?
  → YES: Sweep-line with +1/−1 events OR min-heap of end-times (#6, #13).
  → NO:  Q6.

<strong>Q6:</strong> Do you need to REMOVE intervals (minimise overlaps)?
  → YES: Greedy Activity Selection — sort by end (#3, #7).
  → NO:  Q7.

<strong>Q7:</strong> Do you need COVERAGE (cover a target range with fewest intervals)?
  → YES: Greedy interval covering — sort by start, extend reach (#33).
  → NO:  GAPS? → Gap detection (#11, #12).
         INTERSECTION of two lists? → Two-pointer (#4).
         SUBTRACTION? → Fragment scan (#9).

<strong>Q8 (Online):</strong> Do you need only INSERT and QUERY overlap?
  → YES: TreeMap / SortedList BST (#19, #20).
  → NO:  Q9.

<strong>Q9 (Online):</strong> Do you need INSERT + REMOVE + QUERY?
  → YES: Range Module / sorted map of disjoint intervals (#25).
  → NO:  Q10.

<strong>Q10 (Online):</strong> Do you need RANGE UPDATE + RANGE MAX QUERY?
  → YES: Segment Tree with lazy propagation (#24, #23).
  → NO:  SKYLINE / HEIGHT tracking? → Sorted multiset (#22).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Intervals have weights and you want maximum total value</strong> — Greedy merge selects wrong intervals. Use Weighted Job Scheduling DP (binary search + DP sorted by end-time).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Intervals arrive online with O(log n) per-op requirement</strong> — Static sort-and-merge is O(n) rebuild per insert. Use TreeMap / SortedList for O(log n) predecessor/successor lookup.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Axis is huge (up to 10⁹) and you need a difference array</strong> — Plain array of size 10⁹ causes MLE. Use coordinate compression or a Fenwick tree on compressed coordinates.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Circular/modular intervals</strong> — Sort-by-start fails at wrap-around. Split circular intervals at 0/M boundary, run linear merge, then restitch.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Intervals are 2-D (rectangles)</strong> — 1-D merge gives wrong area. Use sweep-line on x-axis + 1-D interval merge/segment tree on y-axis.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Containment detection (is A fully inside B?)</strong> — Standard overlap check c ≤ b catches containment AND partial overlap — you need the stricter check a ≤ c AND d ≤ b. Classic merge logic silently gives wrong answer here.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>"Burst Balloons" style problems</strong> — The intervals represent DP sub-problems, not ranges to merge. Use Interval DP (dp[i][j]), not sweep-line.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Streaming with hard memory limits</strong> — Storing all intervals for offline sort is impossible. Use reservoir-style online merge or accept approximate answers with a bounded-error sketch.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>1. Classic Greedy Merge (#1)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> The sort + single-pass algorithm produces the unique minimum set of disjoint intervals covering the same union.<br>
                        <em>Invariant:</em> After processing the first k intervals (sorted by start), <code>result</code> contains the correct merged intervals for those k intervals.<br>
                        <em>Inductive step:</em> At interval k+1 with start s and end e: if s &gt; result.last.end, no previously processed interval reaches s (since all starts ≤ s by sort), so k+1 is disjoint → append. If s ≤ result.last.end, they overlap; <code>max(result.last.end, e)</code> is the correct merged end because no future interval (start ≥ s) can "fill" a gap inside [result.last.start, s−1].<br>
                        <em>Uniqueness:</em> The merged output is unique because the union set is fixed and the greedy produces the coarsest partition.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>2. Activity Selection / Non-overlapping Removal (#3)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> Greedy "keep the interval with earliest end-time" maximises the number of kept non-overlapping intervals.<br>
                        <em>Exchange argument:</em> Let G = greedy solution, O = any optimal, both sorted by end-time. If they agree on the first k intervals but differ at k+1 — G picks g, O picks o with end(g) ≤ end(o) (greedy choice). Swap o for g in O: g doesn't overlap with O's (k+2)-th interval (since end(g) ≤ end(o) and O was valid). Count doesn't decrease.<br>
                        <em>Conclusion:</em> G can be transformed into O without reducing count → G is optimal.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>3. Weighted Job Scheduling DP (#17)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> <code>dp[i] = max(dp[i−1], profit[i] + dp[p(i)])</code> where p(i) = latest job ending before start[i] gives maximum profit.<br>
                        <em>Observation:</em> For job i, either it is NOT included (best = dp[i−1]) or it IS included (best = profit[i] + best using only jobs ending before start[i] = dp[p(i)]). These two cases are exhaustive and disjoint, so dp[i] is correct.<br>
                        <em>Complexity:</em> p(i) found via binary search on end-times in O(log n), giving O(n log n) total.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 1 — Forgetting to append the final in-progress interval</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG (running variables variant)
start, end = intervals[0]
for cur in intervals[1:]:
    if cur[0] &lt;= end:
        end = max(end, cur[1])
    else:
        result.append([start, end])
        start, end = cur
# FIX: append the last interval AFTER the loop
result.append([start, end])</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 2 — Wrong overlap condition (strict vs non-strict)</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: misses touching intervals like [1,3],[3,5]
if cur[0] &lt; end:   # should be &lt;=
# FIX:
if cur[0] &lt;= end:</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 3 — Sorting by wrong key (start vs end)</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG for Activity Selection (Non-overlapping Intervals)
intervals.sort(key=lambda x: x[0])  # sort by START — wrong for greedy removal
# FIX: sort by END
intervals.sort(key=lambda x: x[1])</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 4 — Mutating input array in-place (breaks caller)</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG
intervals.sort()  # mutates original
# FIX
intervals = sorted(intervals, key=lambda x: x[0])</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 5 — Meeting Rooms II: push without popping (room not reused)</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: allocates new room even when one is free
for start, end in intervals:
    heapq.heappush(heap, end)
# FIX: pop if earliest-ending room is free
for start, end in intervals:
    if heap and heap[0] &lt;= start:
        heapq.heapreplace(heap, end)
    else:
        heapq.heappush(heap, end)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 6 — Insert Interval: off-by-one in overlap check</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># CORRECT non-overlap:
if new[0] &gt; interval[1] or new[1] &lt; interval[0]:
# BUG variant (excludes touching):
if new[0] &gt;= interval[1] or new[1] &lt;= interval[0]:</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 7 — Difference array: applying −1 at r instead of r+1</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG
diff[l] += val
diff[r] -= val    # should be r+1
# FIX
diff[l] += val
diff[r + 1] -= val</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 8 — Weighted Job Scheduling: binary searching wrong array</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: binary searching on start times
idx = bisect_right(starts, jobs[i][0]) - 1
# FIX: binary search on END times to find last job ending before current start
idx = bisect_right(ends, jobs[i][0]) - 1</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 9 — Integer overflow in rectangle area</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// BUG: int * int for large coordinates
int area = width * height;          // overflows if width, height &gt; 46340
// FIX
long area = (long) width * height;</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 10 — My Calendar I: checking only one neighbour</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: only checks predecessor
prev = tree.floor(start)
if prev and prev.end &gt; start: return False
# FIX: must also check successor
nxt = tree.ceiling(start)
if nxt and nxt.start &lt; end: return False</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Applying greedy merge to weighted intervals</strong> — Classic merge has no notion of value — it merges all overlapping intervals regardless. If any interval carries a weight and you need to SELECT a subset, you must use Weighted Job Scheduling DP. This is the single most common wrong approach at the Hard level.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Confusing "overlap" with "containment"</strong> — [1,10] and [3,5] overlap AND contain each other. Problems asking to remove covered intervals (LC 1288) require checking a ≤ c AND d ≤ b, not just c ≤ b. Using the overlap check here silently over-counts removals.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Forgetting the heap pop in Meeting Rooms II</strong> — Not popping before pushing means you never reuse a freed room, inflating the answer. Always check heap[0] ≤ cur.start before deciding to push vs. heapreplace.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Online vs offline conflation</strong> — Collecting all intervals and sorting at the end is wrong for streaming problems (My Calendar, Range Module). It breaks the online contract and will fail any follow-up that asks "what if intervals arrive in real time?"</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Difference array with values up to 10⁹</strong> — Allocating <code>diff = [0] * (10**9 + 1)</code> causes MLE. Coordinate-compress the endpoints first, then build the difference array on compressed indices only.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Not handling the empty input or single-interval edge cases</strong> — Many interval bugs surface only when len(intervals) == 0 or == 1. Always handle these before the loop.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Circular interval wraparound</strong> — Treating [22, 3] on a 24-hour clock as a normal interval with start &gt; end causes incorrect sort ordering and false non-overlap conclusions. Always split first.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Follow-Up Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>"What's the time complexity? Can you do better than O(n log n)?"</td><td>Sort is the bottleneck; O(n log n) is optimal in comparison-based model (proven by sort lower bound). If input is already sorted, O(n).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>"What if intervals are given as a stream — you can't store all of them?"</td><td>Use a balanced BST (TreeMap); insert each interval and merge with neighbours in O(log n). Memory = O(k) where k = current distinct merged intervals.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>"What if N = 10⁹ intervals?"</td><td>Can't store; need a streaming/summarisation approach. If intervals are uniform random, reservoir sampling. If structured (e.g. monotone starts), sliding window. Discuss trade-off between exactness and memory.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>"How would you parallelise this for a distributed system?"</td><td>Partition intervals by coordinate ranges across machines; each machine merges its partition; a coordinator merges boundary intervals between adjacent partitions. O(n/k) per machine, O(k) merge at coordinator.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>"What if intervals can be added AND removed dynamically?"</td><td>Range Module (#25): sorted map of disjoint intervals. Each add/remove is O(log n + k) where k = number of intervals affected.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>"For every point x, how many intervals contain x?"</td><td>Offline: difference array + coordinate compression, O((n+q) log n). Online per-query: Fenwick tree / segment tree on compressed coordinates.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>"What if endpoints are floating point?"</td><td>Algorithm is identical — float comparison works the same. Beware epsilon issues; use exact rational arithmetic or a problem-specific epsilon if needed.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>"Prove your greedy is correct for Activity Selection."</td><td>Exchange argument: any optimal solution can have its choices swapped one-by-one with greedy's choices without reducing the count (see Proof section).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>"How would you handle 2-D intervals (rectangles)?"</td><td>Sweep line on x-axis; maintain active y-intervals in a segment tree; compute y-coverage via interval merge on segment tree after each x-event. O(n log n).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>"What if the problem asks for the MEDIAN overlap count at any point, not the max?"</td><td>Sweep-line with sorted multiset of depths; at each event record the depth; find median of all recorded depths. Or offline: sort events, track depth array, find median via order statistics.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>

                    <div class="sec-title">3-Phase Mastery Plan</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Phase 1 — Solve (Build Core Intuition):</strong><br>
                        Order: #1 → #2 → #3 → #7 → #4 → #6 → #13 → #14 → #8 → #12 → #17 → #19 → #20 → #24 → #25 → #22 → #28<br>
