                    <div class="sec-title">Graduation Test</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        These three problems are NOT in the table above. Solving all three cold (no hints, no editorial, 45 minutes each) certifies full mastery.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 1 — LeetCode 1851: Minimum Interval to Include Each Query.</strong> Why valid: requires simultaneously sorting intervals by SIZE (not start), sorting queries offline, using a min-heap to track active intervals, and answering each query at the right moment. Tests offline sorting, sweep + heap, and query answering fused into one problem in a non-obvious way. A candidate who has only memorised solutions will not recognise the approach.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 2 — Codeforces 1000C: Covered Points Count.</strong> Why valid: endpoints up to 10¹⁸ — far beyond any array. Requires coordinate compression, difference array, prefix sum, and careful output of (point, depth) pairs for all points with depth ≥ 2. Pure sweep-line problem disguised as geometry. The 10¹⁸ constraint eliminates any candidate who hasn't internalised coordinate compression as mandatory.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 3 — USACO Gold (2019 February): Springboards.</strong> Why valid: interval problem fused with DP and 2-D coordinate queries. You must find, for each springboard, the best previous springboard whose interval "dominates" it, combining sweep-line with a Fenwick tree for 2-D range minimum queries. Highest-difficulty fusion of interval thinking with advanced data structures — the exact ceiling of what Google/Meta Hard interviews reach. Solving it cold demonstrates that your mastery is not just interview-deep but competition-deep.
                    </div>
                </div></div>
            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
                 TOPIC 7 — PREFIX SUMS (MASTERY)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp7">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">07</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">Prefix Sums</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Algorithms</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Pre-computation · Hash Map · Difference Array · 2D · BIT</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">30 problems · 5 stages · range queries, difference arrays, prefix XOR, 2D, dynamic BIT</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Prefix Sums is the foundational pre-computation primitive of competitive programming. The core invariant is: <code>sum(i, j) = prefix[j+1] − prefix[i]</code> — any contiguous subarray sum reduces to a single O(1) subtraction after O(n) preprocessing. This single identity unlocks an enormous class of problems: range sum queries, subarray count problems, 2D rectangle queries, difference arrays for range updates, and hash-map-augmented subarray problems. It appears in virtually every Google/Meta interview round because it tests whether a candidate instinctively pre-computes rather than recomputes — a fundamental signal of algorithmic maturity. At the ICPC/IOI level, prefix sums compose with segment trees, sparse tables, and Fenwick trees to form the backbone of nearly all range query algorithms.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>A prefix sum array is a "running water level"</strong> — <code>prefix[i]</code> is the total water accumulated up to position i. The water between two banks i and j is simply the level at j minus the level at i. You measure the river once; you answer every query in one subtraction.<br><br>
                        <strong>How the mental model scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 1:</strong> <code>prefix[j+1] − prefix[i] = sum of arr[i..j]</code>. One array, one subtraction.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2:</strong> The "water" is not integers but modular residues, XORs, or parities. The subtraction becomes a modular operation or XOR — same shape, different algebra.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3:</strong> The river becomes a 2D lake. <code>prefix[r][c]</code> = total water in the rectangle from (0,0) to (r,c). Inclusion-exclusion replaces the single subtraction.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 4:</strong> The problem never says "subarray sum." You must recognise that a condition like <code>sum(i,j) = k</code> is secretly <code>prefix[j] − prefix[i] = k → prefix[i] = prefix[j] − k</code>. The water level is hidden inside a counting or existence question.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 5:</strong> There are 10⁹ positions but only 10⁵ updates. The river is sparse. A Fenwick tree or segment tree replaces the static array — the identity <code>prefix[j] − prefix[i]</code> still holds, but each level query is now O(log n).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant &amp; Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> For a 1-indexed array <em>a</em>, define <code>prefix[0] = 0</code> and <code>prefix[i] = a[1] + a[2] + ... + a[i]</code>. Then for any 0 ≤ i ≤ j ≤ n:<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<code>sum(i+1, j) = prefix[j] − prefix[i]</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (by telescoping):</strong> By definition, <code>prefix[j] = a[1] + ... + a[j]</code> and <code>prefix[i] = a[1] + ... + a[i]</code>. Subtracting: <code>prefix[j] − prefix[i] = a[i+1] + ... + a[j]</code> — the shared prefix <code>a[1..i]</code> cancels exactly.<br><br>
                        <strong>Generalisation:</strong> This telescoping works for any associative operation with an inverse: addition (subtraction), XOR (XOR again), multiplication (division if non-zero). It does NOT work for max/min because there is no inverse — this is the fundamental limitation.<br><br>
                        <strong>2D corollary:</strong> <code>rect(r1,c1,r2,c2) = prefix[r2][c2] − prefix[r1−1][c2] − prefix[r2][c1−1] + prefix[r1−1][c1−1]</code> by inclusion-exclusion on the same telescoping identity applied twice.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master (15 total)</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>1. 1D range sum query</strong> — Stage 1 · O(n) build, O(1) query · static array · <em>New idea:</em> prefix array definition; telescoping subtraction<br>
                        <strong>2. 1D range sum with modular/XOR algebra</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n) build, O(1) query · static array · <em>New idea:</em> the "subtraction" changes algebra (XOR is its own inverse; mod requires careful handling)<br>
                        <strong>3. Subarray sum equals K (count)</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n) · hash map on prefix values · <em>New idea:</em> count pairs (i,j) where prefix[j] − prefix[i] = k → frequency map of prefix values<br>
                        <strong>4. Subarray sum divisible by K (modular)</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n) · hash map on prefix mod K · <em>New idea:</em> (prefix[j] − prefix[i]) % K = 0 → same prefix mod → group by remainder<br>
                        <strong>5. 2D rectangle sum query</strong> — Stage 3 · O(nm) build, O(1) query · 2D prefix array · <em>New idea:</em> inclusion-exclusion on four corners; prefix is now 2-indexed<br>
                        <strong>6. 2D rectangle sum count / submatrix target</strong> — Stage 3 · O(n²m) with hash map · 2D prefix + hash map · <em>New idea:</em> fix two rows, reduce to 1D subarray-sum-equals-K on column sums<br>
                        <strong>7. Difference array (range add, point query)</strong> — Stage 3 · O(n+q) · difference array + prefix sum · <em>New idea:</em> prefix sum's INVERSE operation — store differences, recover values via prefix sum<br>
                        <strong>8. Difference array 2D (rectangle add, point query)</strong> — Stage 3 · O(nm+q) · 2D difference array · <em>New idea:</em> 2D inclusion-exclusion on the difference array<br>
                        <strong>9. Prefix sum on transformed values (sqrt, log, boolean)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n) · static array · <em>New idea:</em> the array being summed is not the raw input — requires a transformation first<br>
                        <strong>10. Prefix XOR (subarray XOR queries)</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n) build, O(1) query · static array · <em>New idea:</em> XOR is its own inverse, so xor(i,j) = prefix_xor[j] ^ prefix_xor[i−1]<br>
                        <strong>11. Prefix XOR + hash map (count subarray XOR = k)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n) · hash map · <em>New idea:</em> same shape as subarray-sum-equals-K but with XOR algebra; requires recognising the reduction<br>
                        <strong>12. Sparse prefix sum (dynamic updates + queries)</strong> — Stage 5 · O(log n) per op · Fenwick tree / segment tree · <em>New idea:</em> prefix array is no longer static; each update requires partial reconstruction<br>
                        <strong>13. Prefix sum on a tree (path sum queries)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n) DFS build, O(1) query with LCA · Euler tour + static prefix · <em>New idea:</em> "prefix" runs down a root-to-node path; sum(u,v) = depth[u] + depth[v] − 2·depth[LCA]<br>
                        <strong>14. Sliding window prefix (fixed or variable length)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n) · prefix array + two pointers · <em>New idea:</em> prefix enables O(1) window sum; two-pointer finds the valid window bounds<br>
                        <strong>15. Circular prefix sum</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n) · prefix array with modular indexing · <em>New idea:</em> wrap-around subarray splits into two segments; handle via total_sum − complement
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Complexity Staircase</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Sub-Variant</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>What Changed from Previous</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1D range sum query</td><td>O(n) build + O(1)/query</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Baseline</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Modular / XOR algebra</td><td>O(n) + O(1)/query</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Algebra of "subtraction" changes</td></tr>
