                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statements</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>🔧 #13 — 2D Range Add, Point Query:</strong> Given an N×M grid initialised to all zeros, process Q operations. Each operation is (r1, c1, r2, c2, v): add v to every cell (r, c) where r1 ≤ r ≤ r2 and c1 ≤ c ≤ c2. After all operations, answer P point queries: what is the value at cell (r, c)?<br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 ≤ N, M ≤ 1000, 1 ≤ Q, P ≤ 10⁵, 1 ≤ v ≤ 100.<br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> N=3, M=3; ops=[(1,1,2,2,5), (2,2,3,3,3)]; queries=[(1,1),(2,2),(3,3)] → [5, 8, 3].<br>
                        <strong>Intended solution:</strong> Maintain 2D difference array <code>diff[N+2][M+2]</code>. For each op (r1,c1,r2,c2,v):<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;<code>diff[r1][c1] += v; diff[r1][c2+1] −= v; diff[r2+1][c1] −= v; diff[r2+1][c2+1] += v</code><br>
                        After all ops, compute 2D prefix sum of diff to recover the grid. O(NM + Q) total.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • "sum of elements between index i and j" → Stage 1 — direct range query; build prefix array<br>
                        • "number of subarrays with sum equal to k" → Stage 2 — prefix[j] − prefix[i] = k; hash map on prefix values<br>
                        • "add v to all elements in range [l,r], then query point" → Stage 3 — difference array (inverse prefix)<br>
                        • "submatrix sum" or "rectangle sum" → Stage 3 — 2D prefix with inclusion-exclusion<br>
                        • "count subarrays where [some property of sum holds]" → Stage 4 — transform property into prefix condition; check what algebra applies
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • Input is an array + multiple (l, r) range queries with no updates → Stage 1/2, static prefix array<br>
                        • Input is an array + multiple (l, r, v) range updates + point queries → Stage 3, difference array<br>
                        • Input is a 2D grid + rectangle queries or updates → Stage 3, 2D prefix or 2D difference array
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • N ≤ 10⁵ with Q ≤ 10⁵ queries AND updates → Stage 5; static prefix rebuild is O(n) per update → use Fenwick tree<br>
                        • Values up to 10⁹ and N ≤ 10⁵ with no updates → Stage 1–4; static prefix is fine
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Anti-Triggers (when NOT to use prefix sums):</strong><br>
                        🚩 "maximum subarray" or "maximum of subarray [i..j]" → NOT prefix sum (max has no inverse) → Kadane's algorithm or sparse table (static) or segment tree (dynamic)<br>
                        🚩 "number of subarrays with sum ≥ k" → NOT hash-map prefix (inequality ≠ equality) → Monotone deque on prefix (LC 862) or binary search + BIT<br>
                        🚩 "sum of all subsets" → NOT prefix sum; it's a bitmask/combinatorics problem counting each element's contribution across 2ⁿ subsets
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;font-size:.88em;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.55">
<strong>Q1:</strong> Does the problem ask about a contiguous range (subarray,
    submatrix, path segment) of an array/grid?
  → NO:  Not a prefix sum problem. Stop.
  → YES: Continue.

<strong>Q2:</strong> Are there UPDATES to array values between queries?
  → YES: Go to Q8 (dynamic prefix — Stage 5).
  → NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q3:</strong> Is the query asking for RANGE SUM (or equivalent: XOR,
    product, count of property)?
  → NO:  Go to Q7.
  → YES: Continue.

<strong>Q4:</strong> Is the answer a single range sum value?
  → YES: Stage 1 — build prefix array, answer = prefix[j+1] − prefix[i].
         Expected complexity: O(n) build + O(1)/query.
  → NO:  Continue (you need to count pairs or find a target).

<strong>Q5:</strong> Is the condition an EQUALITY (sum = k, sum % k = 0, XOR = k)?
  → YES: Stage 2 — hash map on prefix values.
         Key: transform "sum(i,j) = k" → "prefix[j] − k exists in map".
         Expected complexity: O(n).
  → NO:  Go to Q6.

<strong>Q6:</strong> Is the condition an INEQUALITY (sum ≥ k, sum in [lo, hi])?
  → YES: ⚠️ Hash map BREAKS here.
         Stage 5 — monotone deque (if sliding window) or
         merge sort / BIT with coordinate compression (if arbitrary).
         Expected complexity: O(n log n).
  → NO:  Recheck problem statement.

<strong>Q7:</strong> Are you applying RANGE UPDATES (add v to [l,r]) and then
    reading point values?
  → YES: Stage 3 — difference array.
         diff[l] += v, diff[r+1] −= v; final values = prefix sum of diff.
         Expected complexity: O(n + q).
  → NO:  Is the input 2D?
         → YES: Stage 3 — 2D prefix or 2D difference array.
         → NO:  Does the problem have a hidden linear structure?
                → YES: Stage 4 — identify the transformation first.

<strong>Q8 (Dynamic):</strong> Do you need POINT UPDATES + PREFIX QUERIES?
  → YES: Stage 5 — Fenwick tree (BIT). O(log n) per op.
  → NO:  Do you need RANGE UPDATES + RANGE QUERIES?
         → YES: Stage 5 — Segment tree with lazy propagation.
                Expected complexity: O(log n) per op.

<strong>Stage identification summary:</strong>
  Q4 YES → Stage 1. O(n) build, O(1) query.
  Q5 YES → Stage 2. O(n) total.
  Q7 YES → Stage 3. O(n+q).
  Hidden transform needed → Stage 4. O(n) after transform.
  Updates present → Stage 5. O(log n) per op.
  If your solution is slower than these bounds, look for the
  Stage 5 data structure optimisation.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Range MAX or MIN queries (no inverse exists)</strong> — max(i..j) cannot be expressed as f(prefix[j]) − f(prefix[i]) because max has no inverse operation. [Stage 1–2 mistake] → Sparse Table (O(1), static) or Segment Tree (O(log n), dynamic).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Inequality conditions on subarray sums (≥ k, ≤ k, ∈ [lo,hi])</strong> — Hash map lookup requires exact equality. [Stage 2 mistake] → Monotone Deque for contiguous window variants; Merge Sort on Prefix Array / BIT with coordinate compression for arbitrary ranges.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Dynamic updates to the array (online, streaming)</strong> — Rebuilding the entire prefix array after each update is O(n) per update = O(nq) total. [Stage 5 mistake] → Fenwick Tree (BIT) for point updates + prefix queries; Segment Tree for range updates + range queries.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Non-associative operations (e.g. GCD, LCM of a range)</strong> — GCD has no simple inverse (gcd(a,b) − gcd(a,c) ≠ gcd(b,c)). [Stage 1 mistake] → Sparse Table for static GCD/LCM range queries in O(1).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>2D difference array with overlapping boundaries</strong> — A common Stage 3 mistake is applying 1D logic to 2D — forgetting the +v at (r2+1, c2+1) (inclusion-exclusion term). [Stage 3 mistake] → Always derive the 2D formula from first principles: four corners, alternating signs.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Circular/wrap-around subarrays</strong> — prefix[j] − prefix[i] breaks when the subarray wraps around index 0. [Stage 2 mistake] → Handle as total_sum − (non-wrapping complement), or double the array and apply standard prefix on arr + arr.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Very large axis (up to 10⁹) with sparse updates</strong> — A static array of size 10⁹ causes MLE. [Stage 5 mistake] → Coordinate-compress endpoints to O(q) distinct values, then apply difference array or BIT on compressed indices.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 1 — 1D Range Sum (Telescoping Invariant)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> prefix[j] − prefix[i] = a[i+1] + ... + a[j] for all 0 ≤ i ≤ j.<br>
                        <em>Proof by definition and telescoping:</em> Define prefix[0] = 0; prefix[k] = prefix[k−1] + a[k] for k ≥ 1. Then prefix[j] − prefix[i] = (a[1]+...+a[j]) − (a[1]+...+a[i]) = a[i+1]+...+a[j]. □<br>
                        <em>Note:</em> Correctness is unconditional — no edge cases beyond index bounds.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 2 — Subarray Sum Equals K (Hash Map Correctness)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> The running hash-map algorithm counts exactly the number of pairs (i,j) with i &lt; j and sum(i+1..j) = k.<br>
                        <em>Proof by invariant maintenance:</em><br>
                        • Invariant: at step j, freq[v] = number of indices i ≤ j with prefix[i] = v.<br>
                        • At each step, we query freq[prefix[j] − k] = number of i &lt; j with prefix[i] = prefix[j] − k = number of valid left endpoints for subarrays ending at j.<br>
                        • We initialise freq[0] = 1 (empty prefix at i=0), ensuring subarrays starting from index 1 are counted.<br>
                        • We update freq[prefix[j]] AFTER querying, preventing i = j from being counted. □
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 3 — Difference Array (Inverse Correctness)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> After applying all (l, r, v) operations to diff, computing prefix_sum(diff) recovers the final array value at every index.<br>
                        <em>Proof by linearity:</em> Each operation contributes v to every index in [l, r]. Encoding as diff[l] += v, diff[r+1] −= v means prefix_sum(diff)[i] = Σ v over all operations where l ≤ i ≤ r. This holds because for operation (l, r, v), prefix sum accumulates v starting at l (where it was added) and stops at r+1 (where it was subtracted). The contribution to index i is v iff l ≤ i ≤ r. □
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 1 (Stage 1) — Off-by-one: 0-indexed vs 1-indexed prefix array</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: prefix has same length as arr; prefix[0] = arr[0], not 0
prefix = [0] * n
for i in range(n): prefix[i] = prefix[i-1] + arr[i]  # prefix[-1] wraps!
# FIX: use n+1 length with sentinel
prefix = [0] * (n + 1)
for i in range(n): prefix[i+1] = prefix[i] + arr[i]
# query sum(i,j): prefix[j+1] - prefix[i]</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 2 (Stage 2) — Subarray sum = K: updating map BEFORE querying</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: counts i==j (empty subarray matching k=0 incorrectly)
for j in range(n):
    freq[prefix[j]] += 1           # update first
    count += freq[prefix[j] - k]   # then query — counts prefix[j] itself
# FIX: query first, then update
for j in range(n):
    count += freq[prefix[j] - k]
    freq[prefix[j]] += 1</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 3 (Stage 2) — Modular prefix: negative modulo in Java/C++</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// BUG in Java: (-1) % 5 = -1, not 4
int rem = prefix % k;
// FIX: normalise remainder
int rem = ((prefix % k) + k) % k;</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 4 (Stage 2) — Circular subarray: using prefix directly without complement</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: prefix[j]-prefix[i] doesn't handle wrap-around
# FIX: max subarray sum in circular array
max_wrap = total - min_subarray_sum(arr)   # complement approach
answer = max(max_linear, max_wrap)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 5 (Stage 3) — 2D prefix: wrong query formula (missing −1 on boundaries)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG
query = prefix[r2][c2] - prefix[r1][c2] - prefix[r2][c1] + prefix[r1][c1]
# FIX (1-indexed prefix with sentinel row/col of zeros)
query = prefix[r2][c2] - prefix[r1-1][c2] - prefix[r2][c1-1] + prefix[r1-1][c1-1]</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 6 (Stage 3) — Difference array: applying −v at r instead of r+1</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG
diff[l] += v
diff[r] -= v      # wrong: subtracts one position too early
# FIX
diff[r + 1] -= v</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 7 (Stage 3) — 2D difference array: missing the (+v) at (r2+1, c2+1)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: only three of the four corners updated
diff[r1][c1]     += v
diff[r1][c2+1]   -= v
diff[r2+1][c1]   -= v
# MISSING: diff[r2+1][c2+1] += v  ← inclusion-exclusion demands this
# FIX: all four corners
diff[r2+1][c2+1] += v</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 8 (Stage 4) — Prefix XOR: using subtraction instead of XOR for range query</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG
xor_range = prefix_xor[j] - prefix_xor[i-1]   # subtraction is wrong for XOR
# FIX: XOR is its own inverse
xor_range = prefix_xor[j] ^ prefix_xor[i-1]</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 9 (Stage 5) — Fenwick tree: querying prefix sum instead of range sum</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: range sum query returns prefix[r] - prefix[l] (should be prefix[l-1])
def range_sum(l, r):
    return query(r) - query(l)       # off by one: excludes a[l]
# FIX
    return query(r) - query(l - 1)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 10 (Stage 5) — Fenwick tree: 0-indexed array with 1-indexed BIT (index shift)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: updating BIT at index 0 causes infinite loop in lowbit walk
bit = [0] * (n + 1)
def update(i, delta):
    while i &lt;= n:            # if i starts at 0, loop never executes
        bit[i] += delta
        i += i &amp; (-i)
# FIX: always 1-index the BIT; shift all input indices by +1
update(i + 1, delta)
query(i + 1)</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 1] Initialising prefix array of size n instead of n+1</strong> — Without the sentinel prefix[0] = 0, you cannot represent the subarray starting at index 0. Every range query is off by one. <em>Correct model:</em> "prefix[i] = sum of first i elements; prefix[0] = 0 always."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 2] Using hash map for inequality conditions (≥ k, ≤ k)</strong> — Hash maps only resolve exact equality. <em>Correct model:</em> "Inequality requires a sorted structure — deque, BIT, or merge sort."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 2] Not initialising freq[0] = 1 before the loop</strong> — This misses subarrays that start from index 0. A subarray [0..j] has sum = prefix[j] − 0 = prefix[j]. <em>Correct model:</em> "The empty prefix (before index 0) is a valid left boundary."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] Confusing difference array direction</strong> — Applying diff[l]+=v, diff[r]-=v (forgetting the +1 on r) when the interval is inclusive [l,r] subtracts one position too early, corrupting index r. <em>Correct model:</em> "Subtract at the position AFTER the endpoint — prefix sum must carry the value through r."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 4] Trying to apply prefix sums to MAX/MIN queries</strong> — A candidate drilled on prefix sums will attempt prefix_max[j] − prefix_max[i] for range max. Algebraically unsound. <em>Correct model:</em> "Only operations with an inverse (+, XOR, ×) support the prefix trick. Max/min have no inverse."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] Rebuilding static prefix after each update (O(n) per update)</strong> — For n=10⁵ and q=10⁵ updates, this is 10¹⁰ ops. <em>Correct model:</em> "Any update invalidates all subsequent prefix values — you need a data structure designed for dynamic prefixes."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] Computing 2D prefix sum in wrong order (column before row)</strong> — Building prefix[i][j] requires prefix[i-1][j], prefix[i][j-1], prefix[i-1][j-1] all finalised. <em>Correct model:</em> "Always iterate rows outer, columns inner — or verify all dependencies are filled before use."</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 2 Follow-Ups (Constraint Mutations)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
