                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 4 Follow-Ups (Hidden Reductions)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>"The array has only 0s and 1s. Count subarrays with equal 0s and 1s."</td><td>Transform: 0→−1, 1→+1. Count subarrays with sum=0. Now it's a Stage 2 problem.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>"Count subarrays where XOR of all elements equals k."</td><td>Prefix XOR: xor(i..j) = prefix_xor[j] ^ prefix_xor[i−1]. Hash map on prefix XOR values. Same shape as Stage 2, different algebra.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 5 Follow-Ups (Optimisation Pressure)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>"Now the array is updated with point changes between queries. What changes?"</td><td>Static prefix is O(n) rebuild per update. Use Fenwick Tree: O(log n) update + O(log n) prefix query.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>"What if you need both range-update AND range-sum queries dynamically?"</td><td>Fenwick tree alone is insufficient. Use two BITs (the classic BIT range-update trick) or a segment tree with lazy propagation.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Beyond Stage 5 (Distributed / Adversarial)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>"The array is distributed across 100 machines. How do you answer range sum queries?"</td><td>Each machine stores a prefix sum of its local shard. Query the boundary machine and combine. Global prefix = sum of all shard totals up to the relevant machine.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>"An adversary is adding elements in real time; maintain the count of subarrays with sum=k at all times."</td><td>Each new element a[n] extends the prefix by one value. Count new pairs: freq[prefix[n]−k] where freq is the running hash map. O(1) per new element — the online extension of LC 560.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>

