                    <div class="sec-title">Graduation Test</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        These three problems are NOT in the table above. Solving all three cold (no hints, no editorial, 45 min each) certifies full mastery.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 1 — LC 1508: Range Sum of Sorted Subarray Sums</strong> (Stage 3 + 4)<br>
                        <em>Why valid:</em> The candidate must first compute all subarray sums using prefix arrays, then binary search on a "how many subarray sums ≤ x" predicate using prefix sums again inside the binary search. Prefix sums are used TWICE at different levels of abstraction. A candidate who only knows Stage 1 will produce an O(n² log n) sort-based solution; Stage 4 mastery yields O(n log(sum) · n) with binary search.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 2 — Codeforces 1398C: Good Subarrays</strong> (Stage 2 + 4)<br>
                        <em>Why valid:</em> The problem states a condition on subarrays that does not obviously involve sums. The candidate must derive that the condition implies a constraint on prefix values, then apply the counting technique. Solving cold means the candidate recognises prefix-sum applicability when it is not stated.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 3 — LC 2281: Sum of Total Strength of Wizards</strong> (Stage 4 + 5)<br>
                        <em>Why valid:</em> Requires prefix sum of prefix sums (second-order accumulation) combined with a monotone stack — two advanced techniques fused without any hint from the problem statement. Passing cold demonstrates that the prefix-sum mental model scales to non-obvious compositions — the highest bar for mastery.
