                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statement</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>🔧 Bridge Problem — Backtracking with Constraint Propagation (Stage 4→5 bridge):</strong> You are given an N×N grid. Place exactly K non-attacking rooks such that no two rooks share a row or column, AND each rook must be placed in a white cell (cells are 0 = black or 1 = white). Return the count of valid placements.<br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 ≤ N ≤ 8, 1 ≤ K ≤ N.<br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> N=3, K=2, grid=[[1,0,1],[0,1,0],[1,1,1]] → 6.<br>
                        <strong>Intended solution:</strong> Backtrack row by row. At row r, try each column c where grid[r][c]==1 and col_used[c]==False. Mark col_used[c]=True, recurse to r+1, unmark. Base case: placed K rooks → count++. Pruning: if remaining_rows &lt; K − placed, return (can't place enough). Bridges Stage 3 (N-Queens structure) into Stage 4 (recognising applicability in a new domain) with Stage 5 entry-level pruning.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • "generate all / enumerate all / find all possible" → Stage 1/2 — exhaustive enumeration of a decision tree<br>
                        • "partition into groups / segments / subsets satisfying [constraint]" → Stage 3/4 — partitioning backtracking; each decision splits the input<br>
                        • "place N pieces on a board such that no two [conflict]" → Stage 3 — placement backtracking with conflict sets<br>
                        • "is it possible to [reach / form / achieve] using [limited resources]" → Stage 4 — feasibility search; decision tree over resource allocation<br>
                        • "restore / reconstruct / decode all valid [strings/sequences]" → Stage 4 — reconstruction backtracking; validity check gates each branch
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • Output is <code>List[List[...]]</code> (all combinations, all partitions) → backtracking with path collection at base case<br>
                        • Output is a single boolean ("is it possible?") with no polynomial algorithm obvious → backtracking with early-exit on first valid solution<br>
                        • Input is a small N (≤ 20) with exponential search space but no DP state definition → backtracking with pruning
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • N ≤ 20 with output as a count or existence → backtracking (possibly with bitmask DP if overlapping subproblems detected)<br>
                        • N ≤ 9 for board-filling problems (Sudoku, N-Queens) → backtracking with constraint sets; O(9^N) feasible
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Anti-Triggers (when NOT to use backtracking):</strong><br>
                        🚩 "minimum number of operations to reach target" → NOT backtracking (exponential) → BFS (unweighted) or Dijkstra (weighted)<br>
                        🚩 "count the number of ways to [fill / partition]" where N &gt; 20 → NOT plain backtracking → DP with memoisation; count is too large to enumerate<br>
                        🚩 "find the shortest path / minimum cost path" → NOT backtracking → BFS / Dijkstra / Bellman-Ford; backtracking has no shortest-path guarantee
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;font-size:.88em;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.55">
<strong>Q1:</strong> Does the problem ask to ENUMERATE, CONSTRUCT, or CHECK
    EXISTENCE of solutions in a combinatorial space?
  → NO:  Not a backtracking problem. Stop.
  → YES: Continue.

<strong>Q2:</strong> Is N ≤ ~20 (making exponential search feasible)?
  → NO (N &gt; 20): Backtracking will TLE. Go to Q9 (DP/BFS alternative).
  → YES: Continue.

<strong>Q3:</strong> Does the problem ask for ALL solutions or ONE solution?
  → ALL: Full enumeration backtracking — collect at base case.
  → ONE: Backtracking with EARLY EXIT on first valid solution.

<strong>Q4:</strong> Is the choice at each step drawn from a SET (subsets/combinations)
    or a SEQUENCE (permutations/orderings)?
  → SET (order doesn't matter): Use START-INDEX to avoid revisiting.
    → Reusable? YES → pass same i. NO → pass i+1.
    → Duplicates? YES → sort + same-level skip.
    → Stage 1/2. O(2ⁿ) to O(n!).
  → SEQUENCE (order matters): Use VISITED ARRAY.
    → Duplicates? YES → sort + skip if nums[i]==nums[i-1] and not used[i-1].
    → Stage 1/2. O(n!).

<strong>Q5:</strong> Does the state involve a 2D GRID or BOARD?
  → YES: Grid backtracking. Use 2D visited array or in-place marking.
    → Fixed depth (N-Queens, Sudoku)? Use constraint SETS for O(1) checks.
    → Variable path (Word Search)? Use DFS with visited marking.
    → Stage 3. O(n!) to O(9^m).
  → NO: Continue.

<strong>Q6:</strong> Is there a CONSTRAINT determining valid choices
    (not just "not visited")?
  → YES: Constraint-guided backtracking.
    → Can you PROPAGATE forward before recursing?
       YES → Forward checking / constraint propagation (Stage 5).
       NO  → Check at each node (Stage 3/4).
  → NO: Pure enumeration (Stage 1/2).

<strong>Q7:</strong> Does the problem require tracking RUNNING STATE
    across decisions (e.g., running sum, current expression value)?
  → YES: Stage 4 — pass running state as parameter; undo on backtrack.
         Watch for operator-precedence traps (Expression Add Operators).
  → NO: Continue.

<strong>Q8:</strong> Are there OVERLAPPING SUBPROBLEMS in the search tree
    (same partial state reached via different paths)?
  → YES: Stage 5 — add memoisation on the state (bitmask or tuple).
         This converts backtracking to bitmask DP.
         Expected: O(2ⁿ · n).
  → NO: Pure backtracking without memo.

<strong>Q9 (N too large):</strong> Can the problem be solved with DP, BFS, or greedy?
  → DP: Overlapping subproblems with optimal substructure.
  → BFS: Shortest path / minimum steps in state space.
  → Greedy: Local optimal = global optimal (exchange argument holds).

<strong>Stage identification summary:</strong>
  Q4 (set/sequence, no grid) → Stage 1/2. O(2ⁿ) to O(n!).
  Q5 (grid/board) → Stage 3. O(n!) to O(9^m).
  Q7 (running state, disguised) → Stage 4. Exponential with pruning.
  Q8 (overlapping subproblems) → Stage 5. O(2ⁿ · n).
  If your solution is slower than O(2ⁿ · n) for N ≤ 20,
  look for the Stage 5 memoisation or pruning optimisation.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 1] N &gt; 20 for enumeration problems</strong> — O(2²⁰) ≈ 10⁶ is feasible; O(2³⁰) ≈ 10⁹ is not. → Use bitmask DP if overlapping subproblems, or meet-in-the-middle (split into two halves of size n/2, enumerate each, combine).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 2] Counting problems with large N</strong> — Backtracking counts by enumerating every solution — O(result size), can be astronomical. Use DP where the count is accumulated without enumeration.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] Shortest-path or minimum-cost problems on a graph</strong> — Backtracking finds valid solutions but not minimum-cost ones efficiently. Use BFS (unweighted minimum steps) or Dijkstra (weighted).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 4] Polynomial solutions disguised as search</strong> — Some "NP-hard-looking" problems have greedy or DP solutions. Always check: optimal substructure (→ DP), exchange argument (→ greedy) before reaching for backtracking.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] Backtracking without memoisation on repeated states</strong> — If same (remaining, constraint-state) is reached via multiple paths, pure backtracking recomputes it. Convert to memoised recursion / bitmask DP. Classic symptom: TLE on N ≈ 15–20.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] Sudoku-style without constraint propagation</strong> — Bare backtracking Sudoku is O(9^81) worst case. Without "only try digits missing from row/col/box," TLE on hard puzzles. Forward checking is mandatory at this stage.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] Undo bugs making state corrupted</strong> — If undo is incomplete (global variable modified in one branch, not restored), subsequent branches see corrupted state. Symptom: wrong answers that are hard to reproduce. Every mutation in the choose step must be explicitly reversed in unchoose.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 1 — Subset Enumeration (Invariant Maintenance)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> <code>backtrack(i, path)</code> adds to result exactly all subsets of nums[i:] that extend path.<br>
                        <em>Proof by strong induction on n − i:</em><br>
                        • <em>Base case</em> (i = n): No elements remain; path itself is the only valid extension → add path to result. ✓<br>
                        • <em>Inductive step:</em> Assume correct for all calls with i' &gt; i. At index i, we make two recursive calls: <em>include</em> — backtrack(i+1, path+[nums[i]]) correctly enumerates all subsets of nums[i+1:] extended by path+[nums[i]] by induction; <em>exclude</em> — backtrack(i+1, path) correctly enumerates all subsets of nums[i+1:] extended by path. Together they cover all subsets of nums[i:] extended by path. ✓<br>
                        • <em>Completeness:</em> every include/exclude combination is tried. <em>No duplicates:</em> each path corresponds to a unique include/exclude sequence. □
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 3 — N-Queens (Constraint-Set Invariant)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> The algorithm places exactly one queen per row such that no two queens share a column, diagonal, or anti-diagonal.<br>
                        <em>Proof by invariant maintenance:</em><br>
                        • <em>Invariant:</em> Before placing queen in row r, sets cols, diag (r−c), anti_diag (r+c) contain exactly the columns/diagonals attacked by queens in rows 0..r−1.<br>
                        • <em>Placement:</em> we only place at column c if c ∉ cols, (r−c) ∉ diag, (r+c) ∉ anti_diag — ensuring no conflict.<br>
                        • <em>Update:</em> add c, r−c, r+c to the three sets, maintaining invariant for row r+1.<br>
                        • <em>Undo:</em> after recursion, remove c, r−c, r+c, restoring invariant for trying next column in row r. ✓<br>
                        • <em>Completeness:</em> all columns 0..n−1 are tried for each row. No valid placement is skipped. □
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 5 — Memoised Backtracking (Overlapping Subproblem Collapse)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> Adding memoisation on (index, state) to backtracking produces the same result as without memoisation.<br>
                        <em>Proof by substitution:</em> If <code>backtrack(i, state)</code> is called twice with identical arguments, both operate on identical remaining choices and constraints. By the Stage 1 inductive proof, both produce identical results. Therefore storing and returning the cached result is correct. ✓<br>
                        <em>Complexity improvement:</em> Without memo, the same (i, state) subtree may be recomputed exponentially many times. With memo, each unique (i, state) is computed once → O(states · branching factor) total.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 1 (Stage 1) — Not copying the path when adding to results (reference bug)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: all entries in result point to the same list object
result.append(path)     # path is mutated later → all results become identical
# FIX: always append a copy
result.append(path[:])  # or list(path) or path.copy()</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 2 (Stage 2) — Duplicate skipping: wrong condition (across-levels instead of same-level)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: skips valid elements when previous sibling was used at a DIFFERENT level
if i &gt; 0 and nums[i] == nums[i-1]:
    continue
# FIX: skip only at same recursion level
if i &gt; start and nums[i] == nums[i-1]:
    continue</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 3 (Stage 2) — Permutations with duplicates: wrong used-array condition</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: skips too aggressively — misses valid permutations
if i &gt; 0 and nums[i] == nums[i-1] and used[i-1]:
    continue
# FIX: skip if previous equal element is NOT used (same-level duplicate)
if i &gt; 0 and nums[i] == nums[i-1] and not used[i-1]:
    continue</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 4 (Stage 2) — Combination sum: no termination on negative remaining</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: recurses indefinitely when remaining &lt; 0
def backtrack(start, remaining):
    for i in range(start, len(candidates)):
        path.append(candidates[i])
        backtrack(i, remaining - candidates[i])  # no base case for negative!
# FIX: add early termination
    if remaining &lt; 0: return
    if remaining == 0: result.append(path[:]); return</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 5 (Stage 3) — Grid backtracking: forgetting to unmark visited cell</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: cells remain marked, blocking future valid paths
visited[r][c] = True
for dr, dc in directions:
    backtrack(r+dr, c+dc, idx+1)
# visited[r][c] = False  ← MISSING
# FIX: always restore
visited[r][c] = False</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 6 (Stage 3) — N-Queens: wrong diagonal encoding</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: (row, col) tuple is not the diagonal invariant
diag.add((row, col))
# FIX: use scalar invariants
diag.add(row - col)        # same r-c = same diagonal
anti_diag.add(row + col)   # same r+c = same anti-diagonal</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 7 (Stage 3) — Sudoku: box index formula off</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: wrong box grouping
box_id = row * 3 + col            # mixes rows and columns
# FIX
box_id = (row // 3) * 3 + (col // 3)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 8 (Stage 4) — Expression Add Operators: multiply without adjusting last term</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: multiply applied to cumulative sum, not just the last term
backtrack(pos+length, cur * num, num)  # cur is wrong base for multiply
# FIX: track `last` (the last operand added) separately
# cur - last + last * num  →  removes last addition, replaces with multiplication
backtrack(pos+length, cur - last + last * num, last * num)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 9 (Stage 5) — Memoisation with mutable path in state key</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: tuple(path) includes accumulation which varies — wrong key
memo[tuple(path)] = result
# FIX: key should be the REMAINING state, not the accumulated path
memo[(index, frozenset(used))] = result</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 10 (Stage 5) — Bitmask: using OR to "undo" instead of XOR or AND-NOT</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: OR cannot undo a set bit
mask |= (1 &lt;&lt; i)  # set bit
# ... recurse ...
mask |= (1 &lt;&lt; i)  # BUG: OR again does nothing to undo
# FIX: use XOR (only works if bit was set) or AND-NOT
mask ^= (1 &lt;&lt; i)        # toggles bit back off
mask &amp;= ~(1 &lt;&lt; i)       # unconditionally clears the bit (safer)</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 1] Appending path reference instead of path copy</strong> — <code>result.append(path)</code> stores a reference to a list that will be mutated. All results become identical. <em>Correct model:</em> "I'm storing a snapshot — always path[:]."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 2] Skipping duplicates with i &gt; 0 instead of i &gt; start</strong> — Using i &gt; 0 skips elements at the beginning of deeper recursion levels, silently dropping valid combinations. <em>Correct model:</em> "Skip a duplicate only if it's at the SAME level — i &gt; start enforces same-level scope."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] Missing the undo step for grid problems</strong> — Marking visited=True but forgetting =False means cells remain blocked for sibling branches. Symptom: fewer results than expected. <em>Correct model:</em> "Every mutation before a recursive call must be reversed after it — no exceptions."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 4] Treating a counting problem as enumeration</strong> — "How many valid arrangements exist?" can sometimes be solved via DP without enumeration. Backtracking counts by generating every solution — exponential. <em>Correct model:</em> "If N &gt; 15, check for DP before backtracking."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 4] Not recognising a game-theory problem as backtracking</strong> — "Can player 1 guarantee a win?" is a minimax tree. Candidates try BFS or greedy. <em>Correct model:</em> "Optimal play = exhaustive game-tree search. A position is winning iff any child is losing for the opponent."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] Running backtracking without pruning on constraint problems</strong> — Unconstrained Sudoku is O(9^81) — effectively infinite. <em>Correct model:</em> "Constraint propagation is mandatory, not optional. Always narrow the choice set before recursing."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] Confusing "backtracking with memo" with DP</strong> — When you memoise backtrack(index, state), you have written top-down DP. Not recognising this signals incomplete mastery. <em>Correct model:</em> "Memoised backtracking IS DP. Name it correctly and explain the state definition."</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 2 Follow-Ups (Constraint Mutations)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>"What if elements can be reused? What changes in your code?"</td><td>Change <code>backtrack(i+1, ...)</code> to <code>backtrack(i, ...)</code> — one-character change; explain why termination is still guaranteed (remaining decreases monotonically).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>"The input has duplicates. How do you avoid duplicate results without using a set?"</td><td>Sort the input; at each level skip nums[i] if nums[i]==nums[i−1] and i &gt; start; explain WHY i &gt; start (not i &gt; 0).</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 3 Follow-Ups (State Expansion)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>"Extend Word Search to return ALL paths that spell the word, not just one."</td><td>Remove early-exit (return True); collect all valid paths; deep-copy path at base case; complexity becomes O(n·m·4^L·results).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>"Solve N-Queens for N=100 — clearly backtracking won't work. What changes?"</td><td>Use mathematical constructions (explicit queen placement formulas exist for all N ≥ 4); backtracking is infeasible beyond N ≈ 15.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 4 Follow-Ups (Hidden Reductions)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>"How would you solve Sudoku faster than pure backtracking?"</td><td>Constraint propagation (AC-3 / arc consistency): after placing a digit, propagate to all related cells; reduces branching factor from 9 to ~2–3 on average.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>"Can you model this as an exact cover problem? What does that give you?"</td><td>Exact cover reduces to binary matrix; Knuth's Algorithm X (Dancing Links) solves with efficient undo (O(1) cover/uncover); DLX is the fastest known Sudoku solver.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 5 Follow-Ups (Optimisation Pressure)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>"Your backtracking is O(n!). Can memoisation help here?"</td><td>Only if overlapping subproblems exist — same remaining set reached via different orderings. If state = bitmask of used elements, memo table has 2ⁿ entries; total O(2ⁿ · n).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>"N = 20 and your bitmask DP is O(2²⁰ · 20) ≈ 2×10⁷. What if N = 40?"</td><td>Meet in the middle: enumerate subsets of first 20 (2²⁰) and last 20 (2²⁰), then combine. Still exponential but halved exponent: O(2^(n/2)).</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Beyond Stage 5 (Adversarial / Distributed)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>"You're solving Sudoku puzzles submitted by users in real time. How do you scale this?"</td><td>Each puzzle is independent — embarrassingly parallel. Worker pool; each worker runs constraint propagation + backtracking. Hardest puzzles can be solved in &lt; 1 ms with DLX.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>"An adversary constructs the worst-case input for your N-Queens solver. What does it look like; how do you defend?"</td><td>Worst case: no pruning fires until the last placement. Defence: forward checking; worst-case N-Queens is still O(n!) but average case drops dramatically; for N &gt; 20, use explicit construction formulas.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>

                    <div class="sec-title">3-Phase Mastery Plan</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Phase 1 — Solve (strictly by Stage across all sub-variants):</strong><br>
                        <em>Stage 1 first:</em> S.No 1 (78 Subsets) → S.No 2 (77 Combinations) → S.No 3 (46 Permutations). Write all three from the SAME template: <code>backtrack(start_or_index, path)</code>. The only difference should be 2–3 lines. If implementations look very different, you haven't internalised the template.<br>
                        <em>Stage 2 next:</em> S.No 4 → 5 → 6 → 7 (all duplicate/reuse variants). You should derive each from the previous with one change. Then S.No 8 (Phone), 9 (Palindrome), 10 (IP).<br>
                        <em>Stage 3 next:</em> S.No 11 (Word Search) → 12 (Unique Paths III) → 13 (N-Queens) → 15 (Sudoku). Grid problems introduce 2D state; N-Queens introduces constraint sets.<br>
                        <em>Stage 4 next:</em> S.No 16 (Expressions) → 17 (Word Break II) → 18 (Flip Game) → 19 (Word Pattern II) → 21 (Android Unlock). Hardest recognition problems. Time yourself; if &gt; 40 min, review the pattern before continuing.<br>
                        <em>Stage 5 last:</em> S.No 23 (Squareful Arrays) → 24 (Tiling Rectangle) → 26 (Word Search II with Trie). Implement each optimisation explicitly — do not look up the Trie integration.<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 2 — Drill (speed and recognition):</strong><br>
                        Stage 1: under 10 min. Stage 2: under 15 min. Stage 3: under 25 min (N-Queens: under 20). Stage 4: under 35 min. <em>Template drill:</em> write the complete backtracking template (choose/recurse/unchoose) from memory in under 2 minutes, daily for 1 week. <em>Recognition drill:</em> given only the title, identify (a) sub-variant, (b) Stage, (c) key pruning needed. Target 90% before Phase 3. <em>Undo drill:</em> for every problem, explicitly write "What exactly do I undo?" as a comment before coding.<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 3 — Validate (unseen sources per Stage):</strong><br>
                        Stage 1/2: AtCoder ABC tagged "brute-force + backtracking" — any 3 unseen. Stage 3: USACO Silver grid-placement problems from recent years. Stage 4: Codeforces Div 2 D/E tagged "backtracking + implementation" — 3 problems. Stage 5: Google Kickstart archives — "arrangement" or "placement" problems requiring pruned search.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Graduation Test</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        These three problems are NOT in the table above. Solving all three cold (no hints, no editorial, 45 min each) certifies full mastery.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 1 — LC 1659: Maximize Grid Happiness</strong> (Stage 3 + Stage 5)<br>
                        <em>Why valid:</em> Naïve backtracking (place each person, check all neighbours) is O(3^(m·n)) — TLE. The correct solution uses bitmask DP on the current row state, treating the previous row as a bitmask. A candidate who reaches Stage 5 naturally arrives at this — solving it cold proves they can identify when backtracking needs to become DP.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 2 — CF 1097F: Alex and a TV Show</strong> (Stage 4 + Stage 5)<br>
                        <em>Why valid:</em> Looks like a set-cover backtracking problem but is solved via Möbius inversion on a bitset. The candidate must first recognise exact-cover structure (Stage 4), then apply the bitset optimisation (Stage 5). Highest-level "backtracking to combinatorics" reduction tested at Codeforces Div 1 D level.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 3 — LC 489: Robot Room Cleaner</strong> (Stage 3 + Stage 4)<br>
                        <em>Why valid:</em> A backtracking problem where the state (grid layout) is hidden. The candidate must track relative position manually, simulate the grid in memory, and implement the undo step as a physical robot movement sequence. Tests that the mental model is robust enough when state is not directly accessible — the hardest form of Stage 4 recognition, analogous to implicit-graph problems.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
                 TOPIC 9 — GREEDY (MASTERY)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp9">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">09</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">Greedy</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Algorithms</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Exchange Argument · Sort Key · Heap · Regret · Matroid</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">32 problems · 5 stages · activity selection, heap greedy, regret, matroid, greedy + binary search</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Greedy algorithms make the locally optimal choice at each step — the proof that local optimality cascades into global optimality is an <em>exchange argument</em>: any optimal solution can be transformed into the greedy solution by swapping choices one at a time without worsening the result. Greedy is the most dangerous topic in competitive programming because it is simultaneously the easiest to apply and the easiest to apply wrongly — a greedy that looks correct on examples can fail on a single adversarial case. It appears in every Google interview because it tests mathematical reasoning (can you prove your greedy?), not just implementation. At ICPC/IOI, the hardest greedy problems require recognising that a problem with no obvious greedy structure reduces to a canonical greedy form (scheduling, matroid, exchange-argument) after a non-obvious transformation.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Greedy is a vending machine that always dispenses the "best available" item.</strong> The key question is never "which item is best?" — it's "what does 'best' mean in this problem, and does picking it now guarantee we never regret it later?"<br><br>
                        <strong>How the mental model scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 1:</strong> "Best" is obvious — largest value, smallest cost, earliest deadline. Pick greedily in sorted order. No regret possible.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2:</strong> "Best" changes based on one flipped constraint — earliest end instead of largest value, or smallest ratio instead of smallest absolute value. The sort key changes; the algorithm skeleton is identical.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3:</strong> Two competing greedy criteria must be balanced simultaneously. The state tracks two quantities; the sort key is a composite function of both.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 4:</strong> The problem doesn't look like a greedy problem. You must first transform the input or reframe the objective before the "best available" principle becomes visible.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 5:</strong> The greedy choice requires knowing the current minimum/maximum of a dynamic set — a data structure (heap, segment tree, sorted set) makes each greedy step O(log n) instead of O(n).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant &amp; Proof Sketch — The Exchange Argument</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> Let G = greedy solution, O = any optimal solution. We show G is at least as good as O.<br><br>
                        <strong>3-step template applicable to ANY greedy problem:</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Step 1 (Align):</strong> Order both solutions by the greedy sort key. Find the first position k where G and O differ — G chose element g, O chose element o, with greedy_key(g) ≤ greedy_key(o) (G chose "better" by its criterion).<br>
                        • <strong>Step 2 (Exchange):</strong> Swap o for g in O at position k. Show that after the swap, O' is still a valid solution AND cost(O') ≤ cost(O) (or value(O') ≥ value(O)). The entire proof lives here.<br>
                        • <strong>Step 3 (Iterate):</strong> Repeat until O has been transformed into G. Since each swap didn't worsen O, cost(G) ≤ cost(O). Since O was optimal, G is also optimal. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Why this matters:</strong> If you cannot execute Step 2, your greedy is wrong. The exchange argument IS the proof. Every greedy problem at Google requires you to sketch this argument when asked "how do you know this is correct?"
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master (15 total)</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>1. Sort + linear scan (activity selection)</strong> — Stage 1 · O(n log n) · sort array · <em>New idea:</em> sort by end time; keep if start ≥ last end<br>
                        <strong>2. Sort by ratio / composite key (fractional knapsack)</strong> — Stage 1 · O(n log n) · sort by value/weight · <em>New idea:</em> sort key is a ratio, not a raw value<br>
                        <strong>3. Two-pointer greedy (matching min to max)</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n log n) · two pointers on sorted array · <em>New idea:</em> optimal pairing uses two sorted ends simultaneously<br>
                        <strong>4. Greedy with constraint flip (earliest deadline first)</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n log n) · sort by deadline · <em>New idea:</em> sort key changes from value to deadline; same skeleton, different comparator<br>
                        <strong>5. Prefix-greedy (always extend current reach)</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n) · linear scan with reach variable · <em>New idea:</em> maintain max_reach greedily; answer is steps taken when reach is exhausted<br>
                        <strong>6. Stack-based greedy (remove to optimise)</strong> — Stage 3 · O(n) · monotone stack · <em>New idea:</em> greedy removal uses a stack to maintain order; each element compared to stack top<br>
                        <strong>7. Heap-based greedy (always process best available)</strong> — Stage 3 · O(n log n) · min/max heap · <em>New idea:</em> "best available" is dynamic — heap maintains sorted order across insertions<br>
                        <strong>8. Two-heap greedy (balance two populations)</strong> — Stage 3 · O(n log n) · two heaps · <em>New idea:</em> two competing criteria; median or balance point maintained via dual heaps<br>
                        <strong>9. Greedy on sorted events (sweep line)</strong> — Stage 3 · O(n log n) · sort events + active set · <em>New idea:</em> process start/end events in order; greedy assigns resources at each event<br>
                        <strong>10. Greedy with exchange argument on strings</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · custom comparator sort · <em>New idea:</em> comparator derived from exchange argument, not natural order (e.g., ab &lt; ba iff a+b &lt; b+a)<br>
                        <strong>11. Regret-based greedy (undo a previous choice)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · heap + virtual undo · <em>New idea:</em> make a greedy choice, then "undo" it by adding a negative-weight virtual item; enables globally optimal correction<br>
                        <strong>12. Matroid greedy (independent set maximisation)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · sort + independence oracle · <em>New idea:</em> greedy on a matroid is always optimal; recognising matroid structure IS the insight<br>
                        <strong>13. Greedy + binary search (optimise the sort-key threshold)</strong> — Stage 5 · O(n log² n) · binary search on answer + greedy check · <em>New idea:</em> binary search on a parameter; greedy verifies feasibility at each midpoint<br>
                        <strong>14. Greedy + segment tree (range min/max for greedy choice)</strong> — Stage 5 · O(n log n) · segment tree · <em>New idea:</em> greedy choice requires range query on dynamic set; segment tree replaces O(n) scan<br>
                        <strong>15. Online greedy (decisions without future knowledge)</strong> — Stage 5 · O(n log n) · sorted set / BIT · <em>New idea:</em> items arrive in stream; greedy must use only past information; sorted set enables O(log n) best-match lookup
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Complexity Staircase</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Sub-Variant</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>What Changed from Previous</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Sort + linear scan</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Baseline: sort then greedy scan</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Sort by ratio</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Sort key is ratio, not scalar</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Two-pointer greedy</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Two sorted pointers instead of one</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Prefix-reach greedy</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>No sort needed; single-pass with reach variable</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Stack-based greedy</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Stack replaces comparison with top</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Heap-based greedy</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Dynamic "best available" via heap</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Two-heap greedy</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Two heaps for dual-criterion balance</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Sweep line greedy</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Events sorted; active set managed</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>String comparator greedy</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Comparator derived from exchange argument</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Regret-based greedy</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Virtual undo item added to heap</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Greedy + binary search</td><td>O(n log² n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Binary search wraps greedy check</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Greedy + segment tree</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Range query replaces O(n) scan</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>

