                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 4 Follow-Ups (Hidden Reductions)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>"Prove your Largest Number comparator is correct."</td><td>Exchange argument on any adjacent pair a, b: swapping produces b+a ≤ a+b by comparator. Since no swap improves, sorted order is globally optimal.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>"What if Candy requires each child gets at most 3 candies?"</td><td>Adds upper bound to directional greedy. Two-pass still works but each pass also enforces ≤ 3: min(max(left_pass, right_pass), 3) at each position.</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 5 Follow-Ups (Optimisation Pressure)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>"Minimize Deviation: what if numbers can also be doubled (not just halved)?"</td><td>All odd numbers can be multiplied by 2 once (doubling more is wasteful). Normalise all odds first; then only halving is needed. Same algorithm.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>"What if tasks in the scheduler arrive online and you must schedule in real time?"</td><td>Same min-heap; tasks added as they arrive. This is Shortest Remaining Processing Time (SRPT) — optimal for minimising average completion time.</td></tr>
