            <!-- Data Structures 15-18 -->
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp15">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">10</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">Top K Elements — Heap / Priority Queue</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Data Structures</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Heap Gate · Scheduler · Multi-Source Merge · Two-Heap Split · Retroactive Greedy · QuickSelect</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">42 problems · 5 stages · size-K gate, scheduler, multi-source merge, two-heap split, retroactive greedy, QuickSelect, bucket sort, binary search on value</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why This Topic Matters:</strong> The Heap / Priority Queue / Top K Elements cluster solves one precisely-defined class of problems: given n items and a criterion, efficiently identify, maintain, or repeatedly extract the best K items without fully sorting all n. The core invariant is: you never need to know the exact rank of all n elements — you only need to maintain a boundary element (the K-th best so far) and a structure that efficiently evicts anything worse than that boundary. This pattern dominates interviews because it sits at the intersection of three fundamental techniques: heap-based online maintenance O(n log K), QuickSelect-based offline selection O(n) expected, and bucket/counting-based linear-time selection O(n) when value range is bounded. It escalates into multi-source merging, sliding-window maintenance, retroactive greedy, two-heap boundary splitting, interval scheduling, and segment-tree rank queries — making it one of the richest single patterns in the entire DSA curriculum and a direct prerequisite for Dijkstra, Prim, Huffman coding, and external merge sort.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>A heap is a gatekeeping structure.</strong> You are a nightclub bouncer keeping exactly K VIPs inside at all times. The gate rule: maintain a min-heap of size K. The root is always the WEAKEST VIP currently inside (the K-th best). Every new arrival is compared only to the weakest VIP. Better → weakest evicted, new arrival enters. Worse → turned away. After all n candidates, the K people inside are exactly the K best.<br><br>
                        <strong>The universal heap invariant:</strong> A size-K min-heap contains exactly the K largest elements seen so far, and heap[0] = the K-th largest element seen so far.<br><br>
                        <strong>How this scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 1 — Simplest form:</strong> Key = element value. Min-heap of size K. Push every element; pop when size &gt; K. O(n log K). heap[0] = answer.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2 — What changes:</strong> The comparison key changes — frequency, distance to target, custom tiebreak, or the heap TYPE flips (min → max) depending on which end you want to evict. The heap structure is identical; only the comparator mutates.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 — What expands:</strong> Input is not a flat array. It is a matrix, K sorted lists, or a stream with expiry. The heap must track a SOURCE (list index, row/col) to generate the next candidate. Two heaps work together as a split boundary.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 4 — What is hidden:</strong> The problem does not say "find top K." The heap is a TOOL inside a larger algorithm — retroactive greedy, interval scheduler, graph traversal frontier, or running order statistic. Identifying WHAT to store in the heap is the hard part.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 5 — What is optimised:</strong> O(n log K) is too slow or space is insufficient. Replace with QuickSelect O(n), bucket sort O(n) when values are bounded, or binary search on answer value + count function O(n log V). For dynamic rank queries with deletions, use an order-statistics tree O(log n) per operation.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariants &amp; Proof Sketches</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant 1 — Size-K Min-Heap Gate:</strong> After processing i elements, the heap contains exactly min(i, K) elements, and every heap element ≥ every non-heap element (among the first i elements).<br>
                        <em>Proof sketch (loop invariant):</em> Base (i=0): heap empty, vacuously true. Step i &lt; K: push unconditionally, all elements in heap, trivially holds. Step i ≥ K, new element x: if x ≤ heap[0] → discard, heap unchanged ✓; if x &gt; heap[0] → evict root (now (K+1)-th best), push x, new root = new K-th best ✓. Termination: K heap elements ≥ all n−K discarded elements. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Invariant 2 — Two-Heap Median Split:</strong> lower = max-heap of smaller half; upper = min-heap of larger half. Invariants: |lower| − |upper| ∈ &#123;0, 1&#125; AND lower.top() ≤ upper.top().<br>
                        <em>Proof sketch:</em> Every insert routes to the correct half (order invariant), then rebalancing restores the size invariant. After both steps: lower.top() = largest of smaller half; upper.top() = smallest of larger half. Median = lower.top() (odd) or (lower.top() + upper.top()) / 2 (even). □<br><br>
                        <strong>Invariant 3 — QuickSelect Correctness:</strong> QuickSelect returns the K-th largest in O(n) expected.<br>
                        <em>Proof sketch:</em> Each partition places the pivot at its FINAL sorted index. If pivot lands at K−1: return it. Otherwise recurse into only one side. With random pivot, expected search space halves each step → T(n) = T(n/2) + O(n) → O(n) by geometric series. Median-of-medians: T(n) ≤ T(7n/10) + O(n) → O(n) worst-case. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Invariant 4 — Retroactive Greedy Optimality:</strong> Always using the best available skipped option when stuck gives the globally optimal solution.<br>
                        <em>Proof sketch (exchange argument):</em> Suppose optimal uses option s instead of s* (s* &gt; s). Swap: use s* instead of s → at least as good a result with same number of decisions. No other decision's feasibility changes. By induction, always popping the max from the heap of skipped options is never suboptimal. □
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>Group 1 — Static Size-K Gate (Single Source):</strong><br>
                        <strong>1. K-th largest / Top-K from flat array</strong> — Stage 1 · O(n log K) · min-heap size K · THE baseline; root = K-th largest always<br>
                        <strong>2. K-th smallest</strong> — Stage 1 · O(n log K) · max-heap size K (negate) · ONE flip: evict largest; root = K-th smallest<br>
                        <strong>3. Top-K by frequency</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n log K) · HashMap + min-heap (freq, elem) · derived key from preprocessing map<br>
                        <strong>4. Top-K by distance to target</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n log K) · max-heap; key = −|x−target| · keep K smallest distances → max-heap evicts farthest<br>
                        <strong>5. K closest points to origin (2D)</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n log K) · max-heap; key = −(x²+y²) · 2D computed key; no sqrt needed<br>
                        <strong>6. Top-K frequent words with tiebreak</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n log K) · min-heap; key = (−freq, word) · compound sort key; string comparison in heap tuple<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 2 — Online / Streaming:</strong><br>
                        <strong>7. K-th largest in a stream</strong> — Stage 2 · O(log K) per insert · size-K min-heap persistent across calls · heap lives between queries<br>
                        <strong>8. Running K-th order statistic with deletions</strong> — Stage 5 · O(log n) per op · SortedList / order-statistics tree · heap cannot delete<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 3 — Max-Heap Iterative Merge / Scheduler:</strong><br>
                        <strong>9. Min-heap iterative merge (Huffman)</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n log n) · min-heap as source AND sink · heap both consumes and produces values<br>
                        <strong>10. Max-heap iterative extraction (Last Stone)</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n log n) · max-heap; extract two, reinsert |a−b|<br>
                        <strong>11. Max-heap greedy transform (halving)</strong> — Stage 2 · O(n log n) · extract max, transform, reinsert; reinserted = f(popped)<br>
                        <strong>12. Task scheduler (max-heap + cooldown queue)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · heap stores frequencies + deque tracks cooldown<br>
                        <strong>13. Reorganise string</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · max-heap of char frequencies; output char by char<br>
                        <strong>14. Longest happy string (≤2 consecutive)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · skip top if last 2 chars match<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 4 — Multi-Source Merge:</strong><br>
                        <strong>15. K-th smallest in sorted matrix</strong> — Stage 3 · O(K log K) · min-heap of (val, row, col) · SOURCE TRACKING in heap entries<br>
                        <strong>16. Merge K sorted lists</strong> — Stage 3 · O(N log K) · min-heap of (val, list_idx, node)<br>
                        <strong>17. K pairs with smallest sums</strong> — Stage 3 · O(K log K) · Cartesian product lazy expansion<br>
                        <strong>18. K-th smallest prime fraction</strong> — Stage 3 · O(K log n) · implicit sorted structure; same seeding as K pairs<br>
                        <strong>19. Smallest range covering K lists</strong> — Stage 4 · O(N log K) · min-heap + running max variable<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 5 — Two-Heap Boundary Split:</strong><br>
                        <strong>20. Find median from data stream</strong> — Stage 4 · O(log n) insert / O(1) query · max-heap (lower) + min-heap (upper)<br>
                        <strong>21. Sliding window median (with expiry)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · two-heap + lazy deletion dict<br>
                        <strong>22. Dynamic K-th order statistic</strong> — Stage 5 · O(log n) per op · split point is K not n/2<br>
                        <strong>23. Dual order-book</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · max-heap (bids) + min-heap (asks); match when buy ≥ sell<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 6 — Interval / Scheduling Heap:</strong><br>
                        <strong>24. Meeting rooms II (min rooms)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · sort by start + min-heap of end times<br>
                        <strong>25. Meeting rooms III (assign by room ID)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · dual min-heaps with DIFFERENT keys<br>
                        <strong>26. Employee free time</strong> — Stage 4 · O(N log K) · multi-source interval merge + gap detection<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 7 — Retroactive Greedy:</strong><br>
                        <strong>27. Minimum refuelling stops</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · max-heap of skipped fuel stations<br>
                        <strong>28. Furthest building (ladder→bricks swap)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · min-heap of ladder assignments<br>
                        <strong>29. Maximum subsequence score</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · sort by second array desc + min-heap size K<br>
                        <strong>30. Potions greedy (CF 1526C)</strong> — Stage 4 · O(n log n) · max-heap of accepted; evict worst when negative<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 8 — Stage 5 Optimisations (Heap Replacement):</strong><br>
                        <strong>31. K-th largest via QuickSelect</strong> — Stage 5 · O(n) expected · in-place randomised partition<br>
                        <strong>32. Top-K frequent via bucket sort</strong> — Stage 5 · O(n) · frequency buckets [1..n]<br>
                        <strong>33. K-th smallest pair distance (BS + two-pointer)</strong> — Stage 5 · O(n log(max−min)) · binary search on answer + O(n) count<br>
                        <strong>34. K-th in multiplication table (BS + row count)</strong> — Stage 5 · O(m log(mn)) · BS + Σ floor(v/i) per row<br>
                        <strong>35. Segment tree rank queries</strong> — Stage 5 · O(log V) per query · value-domain tree; handles updates + arbitrary rank<br>
                        <strong>36. Order-statistics tree (insert + delete + rank)</strong> — Stage 5 · O(log n) per op · SortedList; only structure supporting insert + delete + K-th rank simultaneously
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Complexity Staircase</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Sub-Variant</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>What Changed from Previous</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Sort everything, take K</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Naive baseline</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Size-K min-heap gate</td><td>O(n log K)</td><td>O(K)</td><td>Heap gate: only K elements in memory</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>K-th largest in stream</td><td>O(log K) per add</td><td>O(K)</td><td>Each new element = one heap op</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Top-K by frequency</td><td>O(n log K)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>HashMap preprocessing + derived key</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Multi-source merge (K lists)</td><td>O(N log K)</td><td>O(K)</td><td>Source tracking (val, src, idx) in heap</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Two-heap median stream</td><td>O(log n) per add</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Two heaps as split boundary; O(1) median</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Sliding window median</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Expiry: lazy deletion on both heaps</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Retroactive greedy heap</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Heap stores past decisions for revision</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>QuickSelect (offline K-th)</td><td>O(n) expected</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Partition replaces heap; in-place</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Bucket sort Top-K frequent</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Bounded frequency → counting replaces heap</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Binary search on value + count</td><td>O(n log V)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Search value space; count function O(n)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Order-statistics tree</td><td>O(log n) per op</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Delete + arbitrary rank; heap cannot do this</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Max vs. Min Heap — Master Decision Table</div>
