                        <tr><td>Order-book sell side</td><td>Min-heap of ask prices</td><td>heapq default</td><td>Match when sell ≤ buy top</td><td>Lowest sell</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Mastery Problem Set (42 problems · 5 stages)</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Layer</th><th>Stage</th><th>Source</th><th>Problem</th><th>Diff</th><th>P</th><th>Sub-Variant / New Idea</th><th>Key Insight</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">1</td><td><span class="l1">Foundation</span></td><td>1</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/kth-largest-element-in-an-array/" target="_blank">LC 215</a> Kth Largest Element in an Array</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Static top-K; min-heap size K</td><td class="insight">THE baseline: min-heap size K; push every element; pop when size &gt; K; root = answer. heap[0] = K-th largest always; O(n log K); establishes the size-K gate invariant everything else builds on</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">2</td><td><span class="l1">Foundation</span></td><td>1</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/last-stone-weight/" target="_blank">LC 1046</a> Last Stone Weight</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Max-heap iterative extraction; conditional reinsertion</td><td class="insight">Max-heap baseline: extract two largest, push |a−b| if non-zero; loop until ≤ 1. Establishes MAX-HEAP pattern; heap is BOTH source and sink; contrast with min-heap gate in #1</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">3</td><td><span class="l1">Foundation</span></td><td>1</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/kth-largest-element-in-a-stream/" target="_blank">LC 703</a> Kth Largest in a Stream</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Online top-K; persistent min-heap across queries</td><td class="insight">Heap LIVES between queries; add(val) = push + conditional pop + return root; O(log K) per call. ONE change from #1: data arrives online; heap is a persistent object not a one-shot computation</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">4</td><td><span class="l1">Foundation</span></td><td>2</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/top-k-frequent-elements/" target="_blank">LC 347</a> Top K Frequent Elements</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Top-K by derived frequency key</td><td class="insight">Key = frequency from HashMap not element value; min-heap of (freq, elem). Adds HashMap preprocessing; comparator changes from value to frequency; same size-K gate</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">5</td><td><span class="l1">Foundation</span></td><td>2</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/k-closest-points-to-origin/" target="_blank">LC 973</a> K Closest Points to Origin</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Top-K by 2D computed distance</td><td class="insight">Key = x²+y²; max-heap size K; evict farthest; no sqrt needed (monotone). Direction flip: K SMALLEST distances → max-heap (evict largest); key computed from two coordinates</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">6</td><td><span class="l1">Foundation</span></td><td>2</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/top-k-frequent-words/" target="_blank">LC 692</a> Top K Frequent Words</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Top-K with lexicographic tiebreak</td><td class="insight">Tuple key (−freq, word); string comparison is lexicographic; min-heap evicts correctly under ties. Adds COMPOUND SORT KEY; equal-freq → larger word evicted first</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">7</td><td><span class="l1">Foundation</span></td><td>2</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-operations-to-halve-array-sum/" target="_blank">LC 2208</a> Min Ops to Halve Array Sum</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Max-heap; extracted value transformed then reinserted</td><td class="insight">Extract max; push val/2; stop when sum ≤ original/2. ONE change from #2: reinserted value = transformation of popped value (halved), not a difference</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">8</td><td><span class="l2">Variants</span></td><td>2</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/sort-characters-by-frequency/" target="_blank">LC 451</a> Sort Characters By Frequency</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">K = n; full frequency sort; bucket sort is O(n)</td><td class="insight">K = all elements; bucket array indexed by freq; scan high to low; O(n). When K = n AND freq bounded, bucket array O(n) beats heap O(n log n)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">9</td><td><span class="l2">Variants</span></td><td>2</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-cost-to-connect-sticks/" target="_blank">LC 1167</a> Min Cost to Connect Sticks</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td><span class="prem">✅</span></td><td class="variant-cell">Min-heap iterative merge (Huffman)</td><td class="insight">Always merge TWO SMALLEST; cost += sum; push sum back. Greedy: merge cheapest pair first minimises total (exchange argument). Min-heap counterpart to #2</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">10</td><td><span class="l2">Variants</span></td><td>2</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/number-of-orders-in-the-backlog/" target="_blank">LC 1801</a> Number of Orders in Backlog</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Dual opposing heap: buy max-heap + sell min-heap</td><td class="insight">Buy backlog = max-heap; sell backlog = min-heap; match when buy ≥ sell. Introduces OPPOSING DUAL HEAP: two heaps face each other; match on boundary condition; order-book simulation</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">11</td><td><span class="l2">Variants</span></td><td>2</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/meeting-rooms-ii/" target="_blank">LC 253</a> Meeting Rooms II</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td><span class="prem">✅</span></td><td class="variant-cell">Min-heap of end times; interval scheduling</td><td class="insight">Sort by start time; min-heap of end times; if new_start ≥ root → heapreplace; else push. Heap tracks ACTIVE INTERVALS not values; heap size = minimum rooms needed</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">12</td><td><span class="l2">Variants</span></td><td>3</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/reorganize-string/" target="_blank">LC 767</a> Reorganize String</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Max-heap greedy string builder</td><td class="insight">Max-heap of (freq, char); always pick most-frequent char ≠ previous; decrement; reinsert if &gt; 0. Scheduler without cooldown window; impossible if max_freq &gt; (n+1)//2</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">13</td><td><span class="l2">Variants</span></td><td>3</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/task-scheduler/" target="_blank">LC 621</a> Task Scheduler</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Max-heap of frequencies + cooldown queue</td><td class="insight">Max-heap of task counts; cooldown deque = (remaining_count, available_at); advance time when heap empty. Adds COOLDOWN QUEUE alongside max-heap; release after n cycles</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">14</td><td><span class="l2">Variants</span></td><td>3</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/longest-happy-string/" target="_blank">LC 1405</a> Longest Happy String</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Max-heap scheduler with per-char consecutive limit ≤ 2</td><td class="insight">If top char = last 2 chars, pop second-top instead; reinsert skipped top after. ONE change from #12: consecutive limit = 2; must temporarily skip top when limit hit</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">15</td><td><span class="l3">Combo</span></td><td>3</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/kth-smallest-element-in-a-sorted-matrix/" target="_blank">LC 378</a> Kth Smallest in Sorted Matrix</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Multi-source min-heap; track (val, row, col)</td><td class="insight">Heap entry = (val, r, c); seed first column; advance: push (matrix[r+1][c], r+1, c). SOURCE TRACKING in heap entries; bridges single-array heap to multi-source pattern</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">16</td><td><span class="l3">Combo</span></td><td>3</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/find-k-pairs-with-smallest-sums/" target="_blank">LC 373</a> Find K Pairs with Smallest Sums</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Cartesian product lazy expansion</td><td class="insight">Seed (a[i]+b[0], i, 0) for i in 0..min(K, len(a)); advance j: push (a[i]+b[j+1], i, j+1). CARTESIAN PRODUCT generated on demand; seeding only first column avoids O(n²) enumeration</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">17</td><td><span class="l3">Combo</span></td><td>3</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/k-th-smallest-prime-fraction/" target="_blank">LC 786</a> K-th Smallest Prime Fraction</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Implicit sorted structure; heap or binary search</td><td class="insight">Heap of (arr[i]/arr[j], i, j); OR binary search on fraction value with count. Implicit (unstored) sorted structure; same seeding as #16; introduces BS-on-answer as alternative</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">18</td><td><span class="l3">Combo</span></td><td>3</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/merge-k-sorted-lists/" target="_blank">LC 23</a> Merge K Sorted Lists</td><td><span class="diff-h">Hard</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">K-source merge with linked list pointer advancement</td><td class="insight">Hard: heap entry = (node.val, list_idx, node); push node.next after extraction. Pointer advancement replaces index arithmetic; None-checking; K up to 10⁴; N up to 5×10⁴</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">19</td><td><span class="l3">Combo</span></td><td>3</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/smallest-range-covering-elements-from-k-lists/" target="_blank">LC 632</a> Smallest Range Covering K Lists</td><td><span class="diff-h">Hard</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Multi-source heap + running max; dual-boundary range</td><td class="insight">Hard: heap minimises left boundary (min of current reps); cur_max variable tracks right boundary. Heap controls ONLY one side of the range; right boundary tracked separately; two boundaries move asymmetrically</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">20</td><td><span class="l3">Combo</span></td><td>4</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/find-median-from-data-stream/" target="_blank">LC 295</a> Find Median from Data Stream</td><td><span class="diff-h">Hard</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Two-heap boundary split: max-heap (lower) + min-heap (upper)</td><td class="insight">Hard: lower = max-heap of smaller half; upper = min-heap of larger half; invariants: size and order. Two heaps as SPLIT BOUNDARY; median from tops in O(1); rebalancing on every insert</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">21</td><td><span class="l3">Combo</span></td><td>4</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/employee-free-time/" target="_blank">LC 759</a> Employee Free Time</td><td><span class="diff-h">Hard</span></td><td><span class="prem">✅</span></td><td class="variant-cell">Multi-source interval merge; find GAPS</td><td class="insight">Hard: K employee schedules; min-heap of (start, emp, idx); track max_end; gap when next_start &gt; max_end. Multi-source INTERVAL merge not value merge; gap detection requires tracking max_end outside the heap</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">22</td><td><span class="l3">Combo</span></td><td>4</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/meeting-rooms-iii/" target="_blank">LC 2402</a> Meeting Rooms III</td><td><span class="diff-h">Hard</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Dual min-heaps with DIFFERENT comparison keys</td><td class="insight">Hard: free = min-heap of room IDs; used = min-heap of (end_time, room_id); interact on every meeting. Two min-heaps with different keys interact on every event; tie-breaking by room ID</td></tr>
                        <tr><td colspan="9" style="background:linear-gradient(90deg,#fff3cd,#ffe69c);padding:.55rem .8rem;font-weight:600;text-align:center">⚡ CLIFF WARNING — Layer 3 → Layer 4. The next problems require using the heap as a RETROACTIVE GREEDY instrument. The heap stores past decisions that can be revised. The insight shifts from "what is the current best?" to "which past decision should I undo to improve the outcome?"</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">23</td><td><span class="l4">Hard</span></td><td>4</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/minimum-number-of-refueling-stops/" target="_blank">LC 871</a> Minimum Number of Refueling Stops</td><td><span class="diff-h">Hard</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Max-heap retroactive greedy; defer refuel until stuck</td><td class="insight">Hard: push all SKIPPABLE stations to max-heap while driving; when tank empty, retroactively use best skipped station. Max-heap enables RETROACTIVE GREEDY — store options as you pass them; exercise only when forced</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">24</td><td><span class="l4">Hard</span></td><td>4</td><td>LeetCode</td><td class="prob-name"><a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/furthest-building-you-can-reach/" target="_blank">LC 1642</a> Furthest Building You Can Reach</td><td><span class="diff-m">Med</span></td><td></td><td class="variant-cell">Min-heap retroactive swap; ladder→bricks conversion</td><td class="insight">Push every positive climb to min-heap as "ladder use"; when size &gt; k, pop smallest (convert to bricks). Same retroactive pattern as #23 but direction reversed: assign ladders to BIGGEST climbs by evicting smallest</td></tr>
