            <div class="topic-card" id="tp19">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">26</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div class="topic-title">Graph Fundamentals — Absolute Mastery Guide</div>
                        <div class="topic-meta"><span class="tier-badge tier-T3">T3</span> <span class="topic-type">Core Primitive</span></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="sec-title">Why This Topic Matters</div>
                    <div class="info-box">Graph Fundamentals are the bedrock of <strong>40–60% of all hard interview and competition problems</strong>. Every shortest-path, connectivity, scheduling, game-state, and constraint-propagation problem is secretly a graph problem. The core invariant is deceptively simple: <em>a graph is a set of states (nodes) and transitions (edges).</em> The candidate who internalises this model can reduce problems from completely unrelated domains — word ladders, DNA mutation chains, grid mazes, puzzle states — into a single canonical traversal, and then apply the right search strategy. Missing this foundation means failing silently: you can implement BFS correctly and still get the wrong answer because you modeled the graph wrong.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>A graph is a state machine.</strong> BFS finds the shortest path through state space. DFS exhausts all reachable states. Every graph problem is asking: <em>"What states exist, what transitions are legal, and what property of the reachable set do I need?"</em></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap">
                        <table>
                            <thead><tr><th>Stage</th><th>Mental Model Form</th></tr></thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr><td><strong>Stage 1</strong></td><td>Nodes are explicit vertices; edges are given. Count or traverse.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td><strong>Stage 2</strong></td><td>Same graph, but one constraint mutates: directed vs undirected, weighted vs unweighted, one component vs many.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td><strong>Stage 3</strong></td><td>State gains a second dimension: (node, visited-set), (node, color), (node, step-count mod k).</td></tr>
                                <tr><td><strong>Stage 4</strong></td><td>The graph is not given — you must construct it from strings, grids, arithmetic rules, or game positions.</td></tr>
                                <tr><td><strong>Stage 5</strong></td><td>The naive BFS/DFS is O(V·E) or worse. Replace the linear scan with a heap, deque, or bitset.</td></tr>
                            </tbody>
                        </table>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant / Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>BFS Layer Invariant:</strong> When BFS dequeues a node <code>u</code> at distance <code>d</code>, every node at distance &lt; d has already been dequeued, and every node at distance d is either in the queue or about to be enqueued.<br><br>
                        <em>Proof sketch (induction on d):</em><br>
                        • Base: Source is enqueued at distance 0. Correct.<br>
                        • Inductive step: Assume all nodes at distance &lt; d are correctly settled. When node u at distance d−1 is dequeued, every unvisited neighbor v of u has dist[v] ≥ d. We set dist[v] = d and enqueue. No shorter path to v exists because all nodes at distance &lt; d are already settled and cannot provide a path of length d−1 to v without u being an intermediate — contradicting that u is the first settled at d−1.<br>
                        Therefore: first time v is enqueued = shortest distance. ∎
                    </div>
                    <div class="core-box"><strong>DFS Reachability Invariant:</strong> DFS from node s visits all and only nodes reachable from s via directed/undirected edges. The white-gray-black coloring scheme partitions nodes into: unseen (white), in current path (gray), fully explored (black). A back edge (gray → gray) proves a cycle exists.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.8">
                        <strong>📌 A — Undirected Graph</strong><br>
                        <strong>A1.</strong> Connectivity / Component Count — Stage 1 · O(V+E) · Union-Find or BFS/DFS · base traversal<br>
                        <strong>A2.</strong> Bipartite Check (2-coloring) — Stage 2 · O(V+E) · BFS with coloring · adds odd-cycle detection<br>
                        <strong>A3.</strong> Cycle Detection (undirected) — Stage 2 · O(V+E) · DFS with parent tracking · adds parent != visited neighbor check<br>
                        <strong>A4.</strong> Bridges and Articulation Points — Stage 3 · O(V+E) · DFS + low/disc arrays (Tarjan) · adds low-link values over plain DFS<br>
                        <strong>A5.</strong> Eulerian Path/Circuit — Stage 3 · O(V+E) · Hierholzer's algorithm · adds degree-parity constraint<br>
                        <strong>A6.</strong> Minimum Spanning Tree — Stage 3 · O(E log V) · Kruskal / Prim · adds edge-weight optimization
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.8">
                        <strong>📌 B — Directed Graph</strong><br>
                        <strong>B1.</strong> Reachability / DFS on Digraph — Stage 1 · O(V+E) · DFS · base directed traversal<br>
                        <strong>B2.</strong> Topological Sort — Stage 2 · O(V+E) · Kahn's BFS / DFS post-order · adds ordering constraint on DAG<br>
                        <strong>B3.</strong> Cycle Detection (directed) — Stage 2 · O(V+E) · DFS 3-color · adds gray-to-gray back-edge detection<br>
                        <strong>B4.</strong> Strongly Connected Components — Stage 3 · O(V+E) · Kosaraju's / Tarjan's · adds condensation DAG concept<br>
                        <strong>B5.</strong> Condensation Graph — Stage 3 · O(V+E) · SCC + DAG rebuild · adds collapsing SCCs to DAG nodes<br>
                        <strong>B6.</strong> Functional Graph (out-degree = 1) — Stage 4 · O(V) · Rho-shaped cycle detection · adds the rho-structure insight
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.8">
                        <strong>📌 C — Grid Graph</strong><br>
                        <strong>C1.</strong> Flood Fill / Island Count — Stage 1 · O(R·C) · BFS/DFS on 4-neighbors · base grid traversal<br>
                        <strong>C2.</strong> Shortest Path on Grid — Stage 2 · O(R·C) · BFS (unweighted) · adds distance tracking on grid<br>
                        <strong>C3.</strong> Multi-source BFS — Stage 2 · O(R·C) · multiple sources seeded simultaneously · adds virtual-source node concept<br>
                        <strong>C4.</strong> 0-1 BFS on Grid — Stage 3 · O(R·C) · Deque · adds two-tier priority queue for 0/1 edge weights<br>
                        <strong>C5.</strong> BFS on Grid with State — Stage 3 · O(R·C·K) · BFS with (row,col,extra_state) · adds state dimension to grid cell<br>
                        <strong>C6.</strong> Minimum Cut on Grid — Stage 4 · O(R·C log(R·C)) · Binary search + BFS/DFS feasibility · adds non-obvious reduction to connectivity
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.8">
                        <strong>📌 D — Implicit Graph</strong><br>
                        <strong>D1.</strong> Word Ladder (string state-space) — Stage 4 · O(N·L²) · BFS on string neighbors · graph constructed from alphabet transitions<br>
                        <strong>D2.</strong> Sliding Puzzle / Game State BFS — Stage 4 · O(S·branching) · BFS on serialized state · state is a permutation, not a node ID<br>
                        <strong>D3.</strong> Number Theory Graph — Stage 4 · O(√N·V) · BFS on arithmetic rules · edges defined by number-theoretic predicates<br>
                        <strong>D4.</strong> Bidirectional BFS — Stage 5 · O(b^(d/2)) vs O(b^d) · Two simultaneous BFS frontiers · reduces exponential blowup for implicit graphs
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Complexity Staircase</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap">
                        <table>
                            <thead><tr><th>Sub-Variant</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>What Changed from Previous</th></tr></thead>
                            <tbody>
                                <tr><td>Basic BFS/DFS traversal</td><td>O(V+E)</td><td>O(V)</td><td>Baseline</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Bipartite / cycle detection</td><td>O(V+E)</td><td>O(V)</td><td>Extra color array per node</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Bridges / Articulation points</td><td>O(V+E)</td><td>O(V)</td><td>Two extra arrays (disc, low) + DFS tree</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>SCC (Tarjan/Kosaraju)</td><td>O(V+E)</td><td>O(V)</td><td>Stack for SCC extraction</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Topo sort + DAG DP</td><td>O(V+E)</td><td>O(V)</td><td>In-degree array + processing order</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>0-1 BFS (deque)</td><td>O(V+E)</td><td>O(V)</td><td>Deque replaces queue; two-tier priority</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Dijkstra (positive weights)</td><td>O((V+E) log V)</td><td>O(V)</td><td>Min-heap; log factor from priority queue</td></tr>
                                <tr><td>Multi-source BFS</td><td>O(V+E)</td><td>O(V)</td><td>Virtual source node; same complexity</td></tr>
