                    <div class="sec-title">🔧 Custom Problem 35 — Full Statement</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Minimum Transformation Distance (Bidirectional BFS)</strong><br>
                        You are given two states <code>start</code> and <code>end</code>, each a binary string of length n (1 ≤ n ≤ 20). A single transition flips any one bit. Transitions to a "forbidden" state (given as a set of up to 10⁴ strings) are not allowed. Find the minimum number of transitions to reach <code>end</code> from <code>start</code>, or return −1.<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> n ≤ 20, |forbidden| ≤ 10⁴, all strings length n.<br>
                        <strong>Input:</strong> start = "00000", end = "11111", forbidden = ["10000", "01111"] → <strong>Output:</strong> 7<br><br>
                        <strong>Intended Solution:</strong> Bidirectional BFS — expand from start forward and end backward simultaneously. At each step, expand the smaller frontier. Stop when a state appears in both frontiers. Check against forbidden set in O(1) per lookup.<br>
                        <strong>Time:</strong> O(n · 2^(n/2)), dramatically better than O(n · 2^n) unidirectional.<br>
                        <strong>Stage:</strong> 5 — BFS logic identical to Stage 4; only addition is bidirectionality.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • "Find the minimum number of steps/moves/operations..." → Stage 2–3 BFS (guarantees shortest path in unweighted state space)<br>
                        • "Return all nodes reachable from..." → Stage 1 DFS/BFS reachability<br>
                        • "Determine if X and Y are in the same group/component..." → Stage 1 Union-Find or BFS/DFS connectivity<br>
                        • "Find an ordering such that X comes before Y..." → Stage 2 Topological sort on a DAG<br>
                        • "Detect if a cycle/loop exists..." → Stage 2 DFS 3-color (directed) or parent-check DFS (undirected)
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • Input is a list of [u, v] edges or prerequisites[] → Explicit graph; check directed vs undirected from context<br>
                        • Input is a 2D grid of 0s and 1s → Grid graph; 4/8 adjacent cells; default to BFS for min-steps<br>
                        • Input is a set of strings/states with a "one step away" rule → Implicit graph; enumerate neighbors programmatically
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • V, E ≤ 10⁵ and answer is "minimum steps" → O(V+E) BFS expected; anything slower TLEs<br>
                        • V ≤ 20 or state space ≤ 10⁶ → Implicit graph BFS over full state space is feasible
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Anti-Triggers ⚠️:</strong><br>
                        🚩 "Find the shortest path with edge weights" → NOT plain BFS → Dijkstra / Bellman-Ford<br>
                        🚩 "Find the minimum spanning tree" → NOT BFS/DFS traversal → Kruskal or Prim<br>
                        🚩 "Find a path visiting every node exactly once" → NOT BFS/DFS → Hamiltonian path (backtracking / bitmask DP); NP-complete
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;font-size:.88em;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.55">
<strong>Q1:</strong> Is the input a set of nodes with pairwise relationships (edges)?
  → YES: You have a graph problem. Continue.
  → NO:  Check if state transitions can be modeled as edges (implicit graph).

<strong>Q2:</strong> Are edges weighted (non-unit cost)?
  → YES: Use Dijkstra (non-negative) or Bellman-Ford (negative). Exit.
  → NO:  BFS gives shortest path. Continue.

<strong>Q3:</strong> Is the graph directed?
  → YES: Go to Q4.
  → NO:  Go to Q6.

<strong>Q4 (Directed):</strong> Do you need an ordering, or to detect cycles?
  → YES: Topological sort (Kahn's BFS or DFS postorder). Stage 2.
  → NO:  Go to Q5.

<strong>Q5 (Directed):</strong> Do you need strongly connected components?
  → YES: Tarjan's or Kosaraju's SCC. Stage 3.
  → NO:  Plain DFS reachability. Stage 1.

<strong>Q6 (Undirected):</strong> Do you need to find components?
  → YES: BFS/DFS component count or Union-Find. Stage 1.
  → NO:  Go to Q7.

<strong>Q7 (Undirected):</strong> Do you need bridges, articulation points, or MST?
  → BRIDGES/APs: Tarjan's low-link DFS. Stage 3.
  → MST:         Kruskal or Prim. Stage 3.
  → NO:          Go to Q8.

<strong>Q8:</strong> Is the graph a grid?
  → YES: BFS for shortest path, multi-source BFS for min-distance. Stage 2–3.
  → NO:  Go to Q9.

<strong>Q9:</strong> Must you construct the graph from the problem description?
  → YES: Implicit graph. Model states as nodes, transitions as edges. Stage 4.
         → Is the state space large (&gt; 10⁷)? Use bidirectional BFS. Stage 5.
  → NO:  You are at Stage 1–2. Expected O(V+E).

<strong>Summary:</strong>
  Reach Q9 YES → Stage 4. Expected time: O(S · b) where S = state space, b = branching.
  If your solution exceeds this, look for the Stage 5 bidirectional or A* optimisation.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Negative edge weights with BFS</strong> — BFS assumes unit-cost edges; one negative edge invalidates the layer-invariant. [Stage 2 failure] → Bellman-Ford.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Revisiting nodes in implicit graphs without proper state hashing</strong> — if two different states hash to the same key, you miss paths. [Stage 4 failure] → HashSet of serialized states, not node indices.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>DFS cycle detection on undirected graphs ignoring the parent edge</strong> — marking parent visited then seeing it is NOT a cycle. [Stage 2 failure] → Track parent explicitly; skip it.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>BFS when ALL shortest paths are needed</strong> — BFS finds one shortest path, not all. [Stage 3 failure] → Two-phase: BFS builds level-DAG, DFS enumerates paths (Problem 34).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Recursive DFS on large graphs (stack overflow)</strong> — recursion depth = longest path; V = 10⁵ chain graphs blow the stack. [Stage 1 implementation failure] → Iterative DFS with explicit stack.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>Topo sort on a graph with cycles</strong> — Kahn silently produces incomplete ordering. [Stage 2 failure] → Verify count == V after Kahn's.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>SCC on undirected graphs</strong> — Tarjan's SCC is for directed graphs; on undirected every edge creates a trivial 2-node SCC. [Stage 3 failure] → Simple DFS component count.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 1 — BFS Reachability Completeness</strong><br>
                        <em>Invariant:</em> At all times, V_t = set of all nodes reachable from source via paths of length ≤ t.<br>
                        • <strong>Init:</strong> V_0 = &#123;source&#125;. Correct.<br>
                        • <strong>Maintenance:</strong> When processing level t, every edge (u,v) with u ∈ V_t \\ V_&#123;t−1&#125; and v ∉ V_t adds v to V_&#123;t+1&#125;. All such edges are examined; no node is missed.<br>
                        • <strong>Termination:</strong> Queue empties when no new reachable nodes exist. V_final = full reachable set. ∎
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 2 — Cycle Detection (Directed, 3-Color DFS)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> A directed graph has a cycle iff DFS discovers a gray-to-gray (back) edge.<br>
                        • <strong>If:</strong> Cycle v₁→...→vₖ→v₁ exists; when DFS enters v₁, it reaches vₖ before v₁ is blackened. Edge vₖ→v₁ leads to a gray node = back edge.<br>
                        • <strong>Only if:</strong> Back edge u→v (v gray) implies DFS tree path from v down to u. Adding u→v completes a cycle. ∎
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 3 — Topological Sort (Kahn's)</strong><br>
                        Every node is enqueued only when its in-degree reaches 0 — all predecessors are already processed. By induction, the output is a valid topological sequence. If the queue empties with fewer than V nodes processed, a cycle exists. ∎
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 1 — Not marking visited BEFORE enqueuing (duplicate processing)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// BUGGY
queue.add(start);
while (!queue.isEmpty()) &#123;
    int u = queue.poll();
    visited[u] = true;          // too late — u may be enqueued multiple times
    for (int v : adj[u]) if (!visited[v]) queue.add(v);
&#125;
// FIX: mark visited when enqueuing
visited[start] = true; queue.add(start);
while (!queue.isEmpty()) &#123;
    int u = queue.poll();
    for (int v : adj[u]) if (!visited[v]) &#123; visited[v] = true; queue.add(v); &#125;
&#125;</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 2 — Undirected cycle detection treats parent edge as back-edge</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// FIX
for (int v : adj[u]) &#123;
    if (!visited[v]) dfs(v, u);
    else if (v != parent) return true;  // only non-parent visited = real cycle
&#125;</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 3 — Bipartite check not handling multiple components</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// BUGGY: only starts BFS from node 0 — bfs(0, color);
// FIX: iterate all nodes
for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++)
    if (color[i] == -1 &amp;&amp; !bfs(i, color)) return false;</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 4 — Kahn's topo sort not validating all nodes were processed</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// FIX
return result.size() == n ? result : new int[]&#123;&#125;;</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 5 — Grid BFS using BOTH in-place mutation and visited array (double-counting)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// FIX: Choose ONE. Either grid[r][c] = '0' OR visited[r][c] = true. Never both.</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 6 — Tarjan's low-link: updating through tree edges only, forgetting back-edges</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>if (!visited[v]) &#123; dfs(v); low[u] = min(low[u], low[v]); &#125;
else if (v != parent) low[u] = min(low[u], disc[v]);  // back-edge update</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 7 — Grid+state BFS: wrong visited dimensions</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// BUGGY: boolean[][] visited = new boolean[rows][cols];  // misses k
// FIX:   boolean[][][] visited = new boolean[rows][cols][k+1];</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 8 — Implicit graph: List.contains O(n) instead of HashSet O(1)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// FIX: Set&lt;String&gt; bankSet = new HashSet&lt;&gt;(bank);
if (bankSet.contains(next)) queue.add(next);</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 9 — Word Ladder: not restoring character array after mutation</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>for (char c = 'a'; c &lt;= 'z'; c++) &#123;
    char orig = arr[i]; arr[i] = c;
    // ... process
    arr[i] = orig;
&#125;</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 10 — Bidirectional BFS: expanding the wrong (larger) frontier</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// FIX: always expand the smaller frontier
if (frontierA.size() &lt;= frontierB.size()) expandFrontier(frontierA, frontierB);
else                                        expandFrontier(frontierB, frontierA);</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Stage 1 — "I'll use DFS for shortest path"</strong> — DFS finds A path, not THE shortest. BFS guarantees the first time a node is visited = minimum distance in an unweighted graph.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Stage 2 — "Every graph with a back-edge has a cycle"</strong> — In undirected graphs, every edge is a "back-edge" to the parent during DFS. A cycle requires an edge to a visited non-parent node.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Stage 2 — "Topological sort works on any graph"</strong> — Topo sort is only defined on DAGs. Always validate output contains V nodes; otherwise a cycle exists and the answer is undefined.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Stage 3 — "All SCCs can be found with one DFS pass"</strong> — Kosaraju requires two DFS passes. Tarjan's does it in one pass but uses an explicit stack + low-link values — not a plain DFS.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Stage 4 — "The graph is explicit; I just need to traverse it"</strong> — Many Stage 4 problems hide the graph inside strings, numbers, or coordinates. Ask: "What is the state? What transitions are valid?" If you find answers, you have an implicit graph.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>Q1 (constraint mutation):</strong> "BFS finds shortest path. What if cells have cost 0 or 1?" → 0-1 BFS with deque; cost-0 push front, cost-1 push back. O(V+E) preserved.<br>
                        <strong>Q2 (constraint mutation):</strong> "Edges traversable a limited number of times?" → Add edge-use count to state: (node, uses_remaining). BFS over expanded state. O(V·K).<br>
                        <strong>Q3 (state expansion):</strong> "Graph is weighted. How does your approach change?" → Replace queue with min-heap → Dijkstra (non-negative weights).<br>
                        <strong>Q4 (state expansion):</strong> "Find all components AND the largest size?" → Standard BFS/DFS tracking component size per traversal. One pass, O(V+E).<br>
                        <strong>Q5 (hidden reduction):</strong> "Nodes are words, connected by one-char-diff; path exists?" → Implicit graph; build adjacency by mutating each char position; BFS for reachability.<br>
                        <strong>Q6 (hidden reduction):</strong> "Word Ladder: reduce neighbor-gen from O(N·L·26)?" → Wildcard buckets: each word creates L patterns like <code>*ot, h*t, ho*</code>; group by shared pattern. O(N·L) preprocessing.<br>
                        <strong>Q7 (optimisation pressure):</strong> "BFS visits 10⁸ states. Reduce this?" → Bidirectional BFS: expand from source and target, always expand smaller frontier. O(b^(d/2)).<br>
                        <strong>Q8 (optimisation pressure):</strong> "Shortest path with millions of nodes + heuristic?" → A* search: f(n) = g(n) + h(n) with admissible h. Visits fewer nodes than Dijkstra when heuristic is tight.<br>
                        <strong>Q9 (distributed):</strong> "10¹² nodes, doesn't fit in memory?" → External-memory / distributed BFS (Pregel model). Partition graph; each round = one BFS level; communicate frontier. O(diameter · communication_rounds).<br>
                        <strong>Q10 (dynamic):</strong> "Edges added/removed dynamically; maintain connectivity?" → Link-Cut Trees (O(log n) per update/query), or offline divide-and-conquer on the edge timeline.
                    </div>

