                    <div class="sec-title">Graduation Test</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.8">
                        <strong>Test 1 — Stages 3 + 4: <a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/frog-position-after-t-seconds/" target="_blank">LC 1377</a> Frog Position After T Seconds (Hard)</strong><br>
                        Stage 4: model the tree as a graph; recognize BFS level-by-level propagation. Stage 3: state = (node, time_remaining, probability); probability splits fractionally at branching nodes.<br>
                        <em>Why it certifies mastery:</em> Tests implicit state propagation on a tree, fractional probability tracking, and leaf-node edge cases simultaneously. Pure BFS knowledge (Stage 2) is insufficient.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 2 — Stages 4 + 5: <a class="lc-link" href="https://leetcode.com/problems/k-similar-strings/" target="_blank">LC 854</a> K-Similar Strings (Hard)</strong><br>
                        Stage 4: state space is permutations — implicit graph. Stage 5: without pruning (only swap characters that haven't matched target), BFS TLEs.<br>
                        <em>Why it certifies mastery:</em> Forces recognition of a permutation as a graph state, valid-neighbor construction, and a non-trivial optimization requiring you to understand WHY certain swaps are never needed.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 3 — Stages 3 + 4 + 5: CF 1037D Valid BFS?</strong><br>
                        Stage 4: verify a given BFS order — model BFS-tree construction as an implicit process. Stage 3: track which children of each node are "available" at each BFS level. Stage 5: naive verification is O(V²); efficient uses queue-simulation with sorted adjacency and deque comparison — O(V log V).<br>
                        <em>Why it certifies mastery:</em> Tests BFS understanding at the meta-level (can you reason about what BFS produces, not just run it?), implicit state construction, AND optimization. Solving cold in 45 minutes proves first-principles BFS understanding.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Mental Model Synthesis</div>
                    <div class="info-box">The BFS vs DFS distinction illustrated above captures the foundational split that governs every graph problem in this guide. <strong>BFS expands in layers (guaranteeing shortest paths)</strong>, while <strong>DFS exhausts each branch (enabling cycle detection, topo sort, and SCC)</strong>. Every advanced technique — Tarjan's bridges, Kahn's topo sort, bidirectional BFS — is a structured extension of one of these two primitives. Master the mental model at Stage 1, and every Stage 2–5 variant becomes a predictable evolution.</div>
