                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statement (#42)</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>🔧 Minimum Cost Segment Cover — Convex Hull Trick (Stage 5):</strong> You are given an array a[1..n] of positive integers. You must partition the array into contiguous segments; the cost of a segment ending at index i (with the previous segment ending at j, so the current segment is (j, i]) is (i − j) · a[i]. Find the minimum total cost to cover the entire array (segment ending at i = n).<br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 ≤ n ≤ 10⁶, 1 ≤ a[i] ≤ 10⁹.<br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> a = [3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9], n = 6 → answer = 15 (optimal partition [1][1,4][1][5,9]: costs 3 + 2·4 + 1 + 2·9 = 3 + 8 + 1 + 18 = 30 would be a naïve partition; the minimum via CHT is 15 by a better split).<br>
                        <strong>Intended solution:</strong> dp[i] = min over j &lt; i of (dp[j] + (i − j) · a[i]). Expand: dp[i] = i · a[i] + min over j of (dp[j] − j · a[i]). Treat each j as line y = −j · x + dp[j]; query at x = a[i]. Maintain the lower convex hull of lines — O(1) amortised per query when a[i] is monotone, else O(log n) via Li Chao tree. Total: O(n) or O(n log n).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 1: Fixed-Window / Skip-Constraint</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 1 (Min Cost Climbing):</strong> dp[i] = min cost reaching step i. Recurrence: dp[i] = cost[i] + min(dp[i-1], dp[i-2]). Base: dp[0]=cost[0], dp[1]=cost[1]. Bottom-up, O(1) space with two variables.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2 (House Robber):</strong> dp[i] = max loot robbing from houses 0..i with house i robbed. Recurrence: dp[i] = max(dp[i-1], dp[i-2] + nums[i]). Base: dp[0]=nums[0], dp[1]=max(nums[0],nums[1]). Circular → run twice; transform → bucket first.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 2: Knapsack</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2 (Unbounded):</strong> dp[j] = min coins / ways to reach sum j; forward iteration. dp[j] = min(dp[j], dp[j-c]+1) or dp[j] += dp[j-c]. Base: dp[0]=0 (min-coins) / dp[0]=1 (count). Forward iteration → reuse allowed.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2 (0/1):</strong> Reverse iteration → each item used once. dp[j] = dp[j] or dp[j-nums[i]] (iterate j from target down).<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 (Full 2D):</strong> dp[i][j] = optimal using first i items with weight j. Needed only when reconstructing which items were chosen.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 3: LIS Family</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 (LIS O(n²)):</strong> dp[i] = length of LIS ending at index i. dp[i] = 1 + max(dp[j] for j&lt;i if arr[j]&lt;arr[i]). Base: dp[i]=1. Answer: max(dp) — NOT dp[n-1].<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 (Fibonacci Subsequence):</strong> dp[i][j] = length of Fib-like subseq ending at indices i, j. Look up arr[j]−arr[i] in hash map for predecessor. O(n²) states, O(1) per transition with hash map.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 (Arithmetic Subsequence):</strong> dp[i][d] = length of AP ending at index i with difference d. Hash map per index; same O(n²) structure.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 5 (LIS O(n log n)):</strong> tails[k] = smallest tail of IS of length k+1. Update: pos = bisect_left(tails, arr[i]); tails[pos] = arr[i]. Answer: len(tails). bisect_left for strict; bisect_right for non-strict.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 4: State Machine (Stock / Paint / Attendance)</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 (2-state, unlimited transactions):</strong> held = max(held, rest − price); not_held = max(not_held, held + price). Two rolling variables.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 (3-state, cooldown):</strong> held = max(held, rest − price); sold = prev_held + price; rest = max(rest, prev_sold). Three rolling variables; save previous before updating.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 (Paint House, 3 colors):</strong> dp[i][c] = costs[i][c] + min(dp[i-1][c'] for c'≠c). Three variables per row; exclude-self transitions.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 (6-state, Student Attendance):</strong> States (a ∈ &#123;0,1&#125;) × (l ∈ &#123;0,1,2&#125;) = 6 variables. 'P' resets l; 'A' increments a if a&lt;1; 'L' increments l if l&lt;2. Write all 6 transitions explicitly — avoid index arithmetic.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 (k transactions, Stock III/IV):</strong> dp[i][t][0/1] = max profit, day i, t transactions, holding/not. Counter increments on SELL, not buy.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 5: Counting DP</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2 (Additive):</strong> dp[i] = ways to reach state i. dp[i] = sum(dp[j] for valid j). Base: dp[0]=1 (one way to reach empty/start state).<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 (Catalan — Product):</strong> dp[i] = sum(dp[j-1] * dp[i-j] for j in 1..i). Product because two sub-problems are independent. Base: dp[0]=1.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • "maximum sum / minimum cost of a contiguous subarray" → Stage 1 Kadane — reset when extending is worse<br>
                        • "minimum number of coins / steps to reach target" → Stage 2 unbounded knapsack — dp[j] = min(dp[j-c]+1)<br>
                        • "number of ways to [decode / tile / reach / arrange]" → Stage 2/3 counting DP — additive or product recurrence<br>
                        • "longest subsequence where each element satisfies [condition vs. previous]" → Stage 3 LIS-style — sort if needed; custom order relation<br>
                        • "partition / segment string or array into [valid pieces]; minimise / count" → Stage 3/4 — partition DP with inner loop over valid split points
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • Input is a 1D array and answer is a single scalar (max, min, count) → 1D DP where dp[i] anchors at index i<br>
                        • Output is a subsequence (not subarray) satisfying an ordering condition → LIS-style; sort may be needed<br>
                        • Problem has discrete states (holding/not, color, absence count) that transition at each step → state machine DP
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • N ≤ 10⁵ with no obvious O(n log n) algorithm → check for 1D DP with O(n) or O(n log n) optimisation<br>
                        • target ≤ 10⁴ and items up to 10⁴ → knapsack DP; target is the second dimension
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Anti-Triggers (when NOT to use 1D DP):</strong><br>
                        🚩 "minimum number of swaps to sort" → NOT 1D DP → Cycle decomposition on permutation; O(n)<br>
                        🚩 "find ALL subsequences satisfying [condition]" → NOT optimisation DP → Backtracking (enumeration)<br>
                        🚩 "shortest path from A to B in a graph" → NOT 1D DP → BFS / Dijkstra; graph ≠ linear ordering
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;font-size:.88em;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.55">
<strong>Q1:</strong> Is the input a 1D sequence (array, string) and the answer
    a scalar (max, min, count, boolean)?
  → NO:  Consider 2D DP, graph, or greedy.
  → YES: Continue.

<strong>Q2:</strong> Does dp[i] depend on a FIXED number of previous positions only?
  → YES: Stage 1/2 — fixed-window.
         Adjacency constraint? → House Robber pattern.
         Circular? → Run twice.
         Count instead of optimise? → Sum dp[i], same recurrence.
         Expected: O(n) time, O(1) space.
  → NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q3:</strong> Is there a TARGET SUM / CAPACITY as a second dimension?
  → YES: Knapsack DP.
         Reuse allowed? → Forward iteration (unbounded).
         No reuse? → Reverse iteration (0/1).
         Count ways? → dp[j] += dp[j-c]; base dp[0]=1.
         Expected: O(n·target).
  → NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q4:</strong> Does dp[i] depend on ALL previous positions satisfying a
    COMPARISON or RELATION (arr[j] &lt; arr[i], divides, etc.)?
  → YES: LIS-style DP.
         Simple comparison? → O(n²) inner scan; Stage 3.
         N ≤ 10⁵? → Stage 5: O(n log n) via tails + binary search.
         Value-range condition? → Segment tree on value domain.
         Two previous elements needed? → dp[i][j] pair state.
         Difference is explicit? → dp[i][d] hash map state.
  → NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q5:</strong> Are there DISCRETE STATES (holding, color, absent, cooldown)
    that transition at each step?
  → YES: State machine DP.
         How many constraints? → States = product of constraint ranges.
         Expected: O(n · S) time, O(S) space.
  → NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q6:</strong> Is the recurrence a PARTITION (split s[0..i] at some j)?
  → YES: Partition DP.
         Validity of segment = palindrome? → Precompute palindrome table.
         Validity = dictionary lookup? → Word Break / hash set.
         Expected: O(n²).
  → NO:  Continue.

<strong>Q7:</strong> Is dp[i] of the form min/max over j of (f(j) + g(j)*h(i))?
  → YES: Stage 5 — Convex Hull Trick.
         Queries monotone? → Deque, O(n) amortised.
         Queries non-monotone? → Li Chao tree, O(n log n).
  → NO:  Is the optimal split point opt(i) monotone in i?
         → YES: Stage 5 — D&amp;C DP, O(n log n).
         → NO:  Is there a k-window max in the recurrence?
                → YES: Stage 5 — Monotone deque, O(n).

<strong>Stage identification summary:</strong>
  Q2 YES → Stage 1/2. O(n).
  Q3 YES → Stage 2. O(n·target).
  Q4 YES (simple) → Stage 3. O(n²); Stage 5 → O(n log n).
  Q5 YES → Stage 3. O(n·S).
  Q6 YES → Stage 3/4. O(n²).
  Q7 YES → Stage 5. O(n) to O(n log n).
  If O(n²) TLEs: binary search (LIS), deque (window max),
  CHT (linear recurrence), D&amp;C (monotone opt).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 1] Circular array without two-run split</strong> — Applying linear DP directly to a circular problem corrupts boundary results. Always split into two linear subproblems.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 2] 0/1 Knapsack with forward iteration</strong> — Forward iteration silently converts 0/1 to unbounded — items get reused. Reverse iteration for 0/1. No exceptions.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] LIS state defined as "LIS of first i elements" instead of "LIS ending at i"</strong> — The former has no clean recurrence for the strictly-increasing constraint. The anchor-at-i definition is mandatory.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] State machine with wrong base case for holding state</strong> — dp[0][1] = −prices[0], not 0. Holding on day 0 means you paid for the stock.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] Returning dp[n-1] instead of max(dp) for LIS</strong> — The LIS might end anywhere, not necessarily at the last index.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 4] Applying LIS to unsorted input for divisibility / chain problems</strong> — Divisibility is a partial order — valid predecessors may appear anywhere. Sort first so predecessors always appear before the current element.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] Tails array used to reconstruct the actual LIS</strong> — tails gives correct LENGTH but is NOT a valid LIS (elements may come from different subsequences). Reconstruct with a separate parent array during binary search updates.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] CHT deque with non-monotone queries</strong> — Deque CHT requires monotone query order. Non-monotone queries → Li Chao tree or sort queries offline.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] Palindrome min-cut without precomputing palindrome table</strong> — Computing isPalin(j,i) inside DP loop is O(n) per check → O(n³) total. Precompute the full O(n²) table first.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 1 — House Robber (Strong Induction)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> dp[i] = max(dp[i-1], dp[i-2] + nums[i]) = max loot from houses 0..i.<br>
                        • <em>Base:</em> dp[0]=nums[0], dp[1]=max(nums[0],nums[1]). Both correct by inspection.<br>
                        • <em>Step:</em> Any plan for 0..i either includes house i (→ skip i-1, best is dp[i-2]+nums[i]) or excludes it (→ best is dp[i-1]). The recurrence takes the max. No other cases exist. □
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 3 — LIS O(n²) (Invariant Maintenance)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> dp[i] = length of longest strictly increasing subsequence of arr[0..i] ending at arr[i].<br>
                        • <em>Base:</em> dp[0]=1. Only [arr[0]] is valid. ✓<br>
                        • <em>Step:</em> Longest IS ending at arr[i] either starts fresh (length 1) or extends some IS ending at arr[j]&lt;arr[i], j&lt;i. Take max over all valid j. By induction all dp[j] are correct. No valid IS ending at arr[i] is missed. □
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 5 — LIS O(n log n) Tails Invariant</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> After processing arr[0..i], tails[k] = smallest tail of all IS of length k+1. len(tails) = LIS length.<br>
                        • <em>Update:</em> pos = bisect_left(tails, arr[i]).<br>
                        • pos == len(tails): extends longest IS → append. Length increases. ✓<br>
                        • Otherwise: replaces tails[pos] with smaller tail → strictly better for future extensions. ✓<br>
                        • <em>Sorted invariant:</em> tails is always sorted (replacement preserves order by binary search). ✓<br>
                        • <em>Answer:</em> len(tails) = longest IS length. □
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 1 (Stage 1-2) — Off-by-one: dp array size n instead of n+1</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: dp[n] out of bounds for partition DP where answer is dp[n]
dp = [False] * n
# FIX:
dp = [False] * (n + 1)
dp[0] = True</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 2 (Stage 2) — House Robber: dp initialised to nums only</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: ignores that house 0 alone might be better
dp[1] = nums[1]
# FIX:
dp[1] = max(nums[0], nums[1])</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 3 (Stage 2) — 0/1 Knapsack: forward iteration causes item reuse</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: forward loop → same item used multiple times
for num in nums:
    for j in range(num, target + 1):   # forward
        dp[j] = dp[j] or dp[j - num]
# FIX: reverse for 0/1
    for j in range(target, num - 1, -1):  # reverse
        dp[j] = dp[j] or dp[j - num]</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 4 (Stage 2) — Circular House Robber: single DP on full array</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: first and last house can both be robbed
return rob(nums)
# FIX:
return max(rob(nums[:-1]), rob(nums[1:]))</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 5 (Stage 2) — Coin Change: dp initialised to infinity for dp[0]</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: dp[0]=inf → dp[coin]=inf+1 → wrong
dp = [float('inf')] * (amount + 1)
# FIX:
dp[0] = 0  # zero coins needed to make amount 0</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 6 (Stage 3) — LIS: &lt;= instead of &lt; for strict increase</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: equal elements allowed in "strictly increasing" LIS
if nums[j] &lt;= nums[i]:
# FIX:
if nums[j] &lt; nums[i]:</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 7 (Stage 3) — Stock with cooldown: using updated held to compute sold</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: sold uses new held value, not previous day's held
held = max(held, rest - price)
sold = held + price   # BUG: held already updated
# FIX: save previous held first
prev_held = held
held = max(held, rest - price)
sold = prev_held + price</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 8 (Stage 3) — Student Attendance: updating states in wrong order</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: later state reads already-updated earlier state from same day
p00 = p00 + p01 + p02  # p01, p02 about to be overwritten
p01 = p00              # BUG: p00 is already the NEW value
# FIX: compute ALL new values first, then assign
new_p00 = p00 + p01 + p02
new_p01 = p00          # use OLD p00
# ... assign all new_ values at end</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 9 (Stage 4) — Word Break: inner loop starting at j=1 misses j=0</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: misses full-prefix matches starting at index 0
for i in range(1, n + 1):
    for j in range(1, i):   # BUG: j=0 needed
# FIX:
    for j in range(0, i):
        if dp[j] and s[j:i] in word_set:</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 10 (Stage 5) — LIS O(n log n): bisect_right instead of bisect_left for strict LIS</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: allows equal elements → non-strict subsequence
pos = bisect.bisect_right(tails, num)
# FIX: bisect_left for STRICT; bisect_right for non-strict
pos = bisect.bisect_left(tails, num)</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 1] Defining dp[i] as "optimal for first i elements" instead of "optimal ending at element i"</strong> — The "ending at i" definition anchors the state, making the recurrence tractable. The "first i elements" definition silently adds a hidden dimension (what was the last chosen element?). <em>Correct model:</em> "dp[i] = best answer for the prefix WITH arr[i] as the last chosen element; final answer = max/min over all i."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 2] Forgetting that the knapsack base case identity depends on the objective</strong> — For min-coins: dp[0]=0, dp[j]=∞. For count-ways: dp[0]=1, dp[j]=0. For boolean: dp[0]=True. Swapping these produces subtly wrong answers that pass small tests. <em>Correct model:</em> "dp is the identity element of the recurrence operation: 0 for min, 1 for product/count, True for OR."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] LIS: returning dp[n-1] instead of max(dp)</strong> — The LIS might end at any index, not the last. House Robber's answer is dp[n-1] because you must consider all houses. LIS terminates the subsequence at the best possible position. <em>Correct model:</em> "For 'ending-at-i' formulations, aggregate over ALL positions."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] State machine DP: transaction counter incremented on both buy and sell</strong> — One buy + one sell = one transaction. Increment counter exactly once per complete cycle. <em>Correct model:</em> "Pick one side (buy OR sell) to increment; be consistent."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 4] Applying LIS to unsorted input for divisibility/chain problems</strong> — Valid predecessors may appear anywhere in an unsorted array. Sort first so that valid predecessors always precede the current element in array order. <em>Correct model:</em> "LIS-style DP requires valid predecessors to always appear earlier in the array. If the problem's order relation doesn't match array order, sort first."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] Tails array mistaken for the actual LIS</strong> — tails gives the correct length, but the array itself is not a valid subsequence. To recover the actual sequence, maintain a separate parent/predecessor array indexed by the position where each element was placed in tails. <em>Correct model:</em> "Tails is a bookkeeping structure for length computation, not a valid output."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] CHT deque with non-monotone queries producing silent wrong answers</strong> — Deque CHT gives O(1) amortised only when queries are monotone. Non-monotone queries cause the pointer to move backward, violating the deque invariant and reading wrong hull segments. <em>Correct model:</em> "Verify query monotonicity before using deque CHT. If in doubt, use Li Chao tree."</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
