            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
                 TOPIC 31 — 2D GRID DP (MASTERY)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp31">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">31</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">2D Grid DP</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Dynamic Programming</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Path · Reverse · Multi-Agent · DFS-Memo · Histogram · Step-Reduction</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">30 problems · 5 stages · path DP, geometric DP, multi-agent, 3D state expansion, DFS+memo, histogram reduction</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> 2D Grid DP solves problems where the state is a position in a 2D structure (grid, matrix, triangle, or multi-agent path through a grid) and the optimal value at each cell depends on values at adjacent previously-computed cells. The core invariant is: dp[i][j] represents the optimal answer for the subproblem rooted at cell (i,j), reachable from a defined starting boundary, and this value is computed exactly once in a topological order consistent with the movement rules. It is one of the most tested DP categories in Google-level interviews because: (1) the state definition is immediately visual, making it approachable; (2) the hard variants (multi-agent, boundary paths, constrained movement) require precise state expansion that separates good from great candidates; and (3) the transition direction (top-down vs bottom-up, which direction is "earlier") must be chosen deliberately — a common failure point under pressure.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>2D Grid DP is a flooding process.</strong> You fill cells with optimal values, flowing in from the boundary. Every cell asks: "What is the best I can achieve given where I am?" It answers using only cells that have already been filled. The shape of the flood (where it starts, which directions it flows) defines the entire algorithm.<br><br>
                        <strong>How the mental model scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 1:</strong> Flood starts at one corner, flows right and down. dp[i][j] depends on dp[i-1][j] and dp[i][j-1]. One source, one destination, no obstacles.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2:</strong> The flood hits an obstacle or a boundary constraint — some cells are blocked, some paths are invalid. Same direction, same recurrence — just add a validity check.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3:</strong> The state expands — track something beyond position: remaining moves, number of cuts, a second agent moving simultaneously. The recurrence grows but the flooding direction is unchanged.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 4:</strong> The grid is implicit or disguised — the problem doesn't hand you a grid. You must model the state space as a grid, then flood it.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 5:</strong> The naïve flood is O(n²) per cell or has an inner scan. Replace with a data structure (sparse table, segment tree, deque) to reduce the per-cell cost.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant &amp; Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> dp[i][j] holds the optimal value of the subproblem for cell (i,j), computed after all cells that can transition INTO (i,j) have already been computed.<br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (by induction on topological order):</strong><br>
                        • <strong>DAG structure:</strong> The movement rules (e.g., only right/down) define a DAG on the grid cells. Topological order = row-major scan.<br>
                        • <strong>Base case:</strong> Boundary cells (row 0 and column 0, or the starting cell) are computed directly from the problem definition.<br>
                        • <strong>Inductive step:</strong> When computing dp[i][j], all cells (i-1,j) and (i,j-1) (and others depending on movement) have already been computed by the row-major scan. The recurrence dp[i][j] = f(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], grid[i][j]) is therefore valid.<br>
                        • <strong>Correctness of recurrence:</strong> The recurrence is valid IFF the problem has optimal substructure: "the optimal path to (i,j) consists of the optimal path to one of (i,j)'s predecessors, plus the cost/value of (i,j) itself." Verify this once for each new problem.<br>
                        • <strong>Answer extraction:</strong> The answer is at dp[n-1][m-1], or along a boundary row/column, or the max/min over all cells depending on the problem.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master (20 total)</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>1. Unique path counting (no obstacles)</strong> — Stage 1 · O(nm) · combinatorics or DP table<br>
                        <strong>2. Path counting with obstacles</strong> — Stage 2 · O(nm) · same recurrence with cell validity check<br>
