                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statement (#27)</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>🔧 Maximum Cherries with Exactly K Robots — Multi-Agent Generalisation (Stage 4):</strong> You are given an n×m grid where each cell contains a non-negative integer of cherries. K robots start at different columns of row 0 (you choose which columns). All robots move simultaneously, one row per step, and each robot moves to an adjacent column (left, same, or right) at each step. A cherry at cell (i,j) is collected only ONCE regardless of how many robots visit it. Find the maximum cherries collectible when all K robots reach the last row.<br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 ≤ n ≤ 50, 1 ≤ m ≤ 50, 1 ≤ K ≤ min(m, 5), 0 ≤ grid[i][j] ≤ 100.<br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> n=3, m=3, K=2, grid=[[3,1,1],[2,5,1],[1,5,5]] → Answer: 24.<br>
                        <strong>Intended solution:</strong> Bottom-up DP with state dp[row][c₁][c₂]...[cₖ]; cherry deduplication when any two columns are equal. For K=2 this is Cherry Pickup II. For K&gt;2, state space is O(n·mᴷ). Maintain c₁ ≤ c₂ ≤ ... ≤ cₖ (column order doesn't matter) to cut state space by K! Divide-and-conquer on the agent axis (process pairs of agents, merge their optimal column assignments) reduces to O(n·m²·K).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 1: Single-Agent Path DP</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 1 — Min Path Sum:</strong> dp[i][j] = minimum cost to reach (i,j) from (0,0). dp[i][j] = grid[i][j] + min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]). Base: dp[0][0]=grid[0][0]; first row/col are prefix sums. Bottom-up row-major; O(m) space with rolling row.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2 — Dungeon Game (Reverse):</strong> dp[i][j] = minimum HP needed AT cell (i,j) to reach exit alive. dp[i][j] = max(1, min(dp[i+1][j], dp[i][j+1]) − dungeon[i][j]). Base: dp[n-1][m-1] = max(1, 1 − dungeon[n-1][m-1]). Bottom-up from bottom-right — forward DP cannot express lower-bound constraint.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 — Out of Boundary Paths (3D):</strong> dp[i][j][k] = number of ways to leave grid from (i,j) in exactly k steps. dp[i][j][k] = sum over 4 directions of dp[ni][nj][k-1] (out-of-bounds counts as 1). Fill layer by layer; O(m) space per step.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 2: Geometric Constraint DP</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 1 — Unique Paths:</strong> dp[i][j] = number of distinct paths from (0,0) to (i,j) moving right/down. dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j] + dp[i][j-1]. Base: dp[0][j]=1, dp[i][0]=1. Equivalent to Pascal's triangle.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2 — Maximal Square:</strong> dp[i][j] = side length of largest square of 1s with bottom-right at (i,j). dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]) + 1 if grid[i][j]=='1' else 0. Answer = max(dp)².<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 4 — Maximal Rectangle:</strong> For each row i, compute heights[j] = number of consecutive 1s in column j ending at row i. Then largest rectangle in histogram (monotone stack) → O(m) per row. Total: O(nm), O(m) space. The 2D → 1D reduction IS the Stage 4 transformation.
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 3: Multi-Agent DP</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3 — Cherry Pickup II:</strong> dp[row][c1][c2] = max cherries with two robots ending at columns c1, c2 in first row+1 rows. Transitions over (dc1, dc2) ∈ &#123;-1, 0, 1&#125;²; cherries(row, c1, c2) = grid[row][c1] + (grid[row][c2] if c2≠c1 else 0). By symmetry c1 ≤ c2 cuts state space in half.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 4 — Cherry Pickup I (step reduction):</strong> Both agents travel (0,0)→(n-1,n-1). On step t, r1+c1 = r2+c2 = t → r = t − c. State reduces from dp[r1][c1][r2][c2] to dp[t][c1][c2]. Transitions over (dc1, dc2) ∈ &#123;0, 1&#125;². Base: dp[0][0][0] = grid[0][0]. Answer: max(dp[2(n-1)][n-1][n-1], 0).
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Group 4: Falling Path DP (Optimised)</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2 — Minimum Falling Path Sum II:</strong> dp[i][j] = min falling path sum ending at (i,j) with no consecutive same-column. Naïve: dp[i][j] = matrix[i][j] + min(dp[i-1][j'] for j'≠j) — O(n³).<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 5 optimisation:</strong> Track min1 (global row min), min2 (second row min), min1_col: dp[i][j] = matrix[i][j] + (min1 if j≠min1_col else min2). O(n²) time, O(n) space.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • "minimum/maximum cost path from top-left to bottom-right" → Stage 1/2 grid DP — dp[i][j] = grid[i][j] + min/max(up, left)<br>
                        • "number of distinct paths / ways to reach" → Stage 1 counting DP — dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j] + dp[i][j-1]<br>
                        • "maximum square / rectangle of 1s" → Stage 2 geometric DP — dp[i][j] = side length or histogram height<br>
                        • "two robots / players move simultaneously through the same grid" → Stage 3/4 multi-agent — joint state (c1, c2) per row; deduplication when positions coincide<br>
                        • "minimum health / resource required to survive the path" → Stage 2 reverse DP — traverse from exit to start; state = lower bound to survive
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • Input is n×m grid, movement only right/down → row-major bottom-up; O(m) rolling space<br>
                        • n×m grid + 4-directional movement + monotone condition (strictly inc/dec) → DFS + memoisation (data-dependent topological order)<br>
                        • Two (r1,c1) AND (r2,c2) both move through the same grid → check if step = r+c is conserved; if so, reduce 4D to 3D
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • 1 ≤ n, m ≤ 200 with O(nm) or O(nm²) budget → standard grid DP, optional rolling space<br>
                        • 1 ≤ n, m ≤ 50 with third dimension k ≤ 50 → 3D DP acceptable; O(nm·k) ≤ 125,000
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Anti-Triggers (when NOT to use 2D Grid DP):</strong><br>
                        🚩 "distance to nearest 0/obstacle for each cell" → NOT grid DP → multi-source BFS; DP two-pass works but BFS is simpler and more general<br>
                        🚩 "minimum path with 8-directional movement or can revisit" → NOT standard grid DP → BFS (unweighted) or Dijkstra (weighted); DP breaks when topological order doesn't exist<br>
                        🚩 "largest connected region of 1s" → NOT geometric grid DP → DFS/BFS flood fill; irregular shape can't be expressed as square/rectangle invariant
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;font-size:.88em;white-space:pre-wrap;line-height:1.55">
<strong>Q1:</strong> Is the input a 2D grid (matrix) or triangle/jagged array,
    and is the answer a scalar (count, min, max)?
  → NO:  Not 2D grid DP. Consider 1D DP, graph, or greedy.
  → YES: Continue.

<strong>Q2:</strong> What is the movement rule?
  → RIGHT/DOWN only (or DOWN only, fixed direction):
       Row-major bottom-up DP. O(nm) time, O(m) space.
       Go to Q3.
  → 4-directional with a MONOTONE condition (strict inc/dec):
       DFS + memoisation (topological order data-dependent).
       Stage 4. O(nm).
  → 4-directional with NO monotone condition (arbitrary):
       → Unweighted: BFS. → Weighted: Dijkstra. NOT grid DP.

<strong>Q3:</strong> Is the answer a path VALUE (sum, product, min, max along path)?
  → YES: Value-accumulation DP.
         Negative values? → Track both max_dp and min_dp (dual-tracking).
         Lower-bound constraint (survive)? → Reverse DP from exit.
         Go to Q4.
  → NO (counting paths): Counting DP. dp[i][j] = sum of valid predecessors.
         Go to Q4.

<strong>Q4:</strong> Are there additional constraints beyond position?
  → Step budget / remaining moves:
       Step counter as third dim. O(nm·steps).
  → Running sum mod k:
       Sum mod k as third dim. O(nm·k).
  → Cut count / partition:
       Cut counter as third dim + 2D prefix sum. O(nm·k) to O(n²m²k).
  → NO: Stage 1/2. Expected O(nm).

<strong>Q5:</strong> Are there TWO or MORE AGENTS moving simultaneously?
  → YES: Multi-agent DP.
         Same grid, both go corner-to-corner?
           → Check if step = i+j is conserved → reduce 4D to 3D. Stage 4.
         Different starts/ends?
           → Explicit 3D state (row, c1, c2). Stage 3. O(n·m²).
  → NO: Continue.

<strong>Q6:</strong> Is the per-cell transition an inner SCAN over a row/column?
  → YES: Stage 5 — look for optimisation.
         Non-same-column exclusion? → min1/min2 trick. O(1) per cell.
         Range max/min query? → Sparse table or segment tree.
         Max subarray sum ≤ K? → Sorted set + binary search.
  → NO: Solution is complete at current stage.

<strong>Stage identification summary:</strong>
  Q3 YES, Q4 NO → Stage 1/2. O(nm).
  Q4 YES (extra dimension) → Stage 3. O(nm·k).
  Q5 YES (multi-agent) → Stage 3 (explicit) or Stage 4 (reduction).
  Q6 YES (inner scan) → Stage 5. O(nm) to O(nm log n).
  If O(nm²) or worse and n,m &gt; 200: look for Stage 5 optimisation.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 1] Movement allows going UP or LEFT</strong> — If movement is not strictly in the direction of increasing (i, j), there is no topological order for a simple row-major scan. The recurrence would form cycles. Use BFS (unweighted) or Dijkstra (weighted) instead.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 2] Reverse DP forgotten for lower-bound problems (Dungeon Game)</strong> — Forward DP accumulates the path value achieved — it cannot express "minimum resource needed to survive." Problems asking for a lower bound on a resource (HP, fuel) always require reverse traversal from the destination.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 2] Blocked cells in first row/column not stopping propagation</strong> — For Unique Paths II, once a blocked cell appears in row 0 or column 0, all cells AFTER it must also be 0. Forgetting to stop propagation gives wrong answers for the first row/column.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] Two-agent DP: double-counting cherries when c1==c2</strong> — When both agents are at the same column, counting grid[row][c1] + grid[row][c2] gives twice the cherries. Always check: cherries = grid[row][c1] + (grid[row][c2] if c2 != c1 else 0).</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 4] Cherry Pickup I: not enforcing valid cell bounds in 3D state</strong> — Since r = step − c, when step − c &lt; 0 or step − c ≥ n, the cell is out of bounds. Failing to check 0 ≤ r &lt; n for both agents gives wrong transitions.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 4] Applying row-major DP to Longest Increasing Path</strong> — The DAG direction is data-dependent (increasing values). Row-major scan processes cells in the wrong order — a cell might be computed before all its predecessors. Use DFS + memoisation which discovers the correct topological order implicitly.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] min1/min2 trick: forgetting to track the COLUMN of min1</strong> — When the current column equals min1_col, you must use min2. If you only track the VALUE of min1 (not its column), you can't determine when to fall back to min2.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] Maximal Rectangle: applying histogram stack to the wrong axis</strong> — The histogram DP must run on columns (heights of consecutive 1s in each column per row). Running it on rows gives wrong heights. Recompute heights row by row.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 1 — Minimum Path Sum (Induction on i+j)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> dp[i][j] = minimum sum path from (0,0) to (i,j).<br>
                        • <em>Base:</em> dp[0][0] = grid[0][0]. Trivially the only path to itself. ✓<br>
                        • <em>Inductive step:</em> Assume dp[i'][j'] correct for all i'+j' &lt; i+j. Any path to (i,j) passes through exactly one of (i-1,j) or (i,j-1) as its last step. Minimum-sum path to (i,j) = grid[i][j] + minimum of the two optimal predecessors. Both predecessors have i'+j' &lt; i+j, so they are correct by hypothesis.<br>
                        • <em>No other cases:</em> Movement is strictly right/down; no other predecessors exist. □
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 2 — Maximal Square (Invariant on dp[i][j])</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> dp[i][j] = side length of largest all-1s square with bottom-right at (i,j).<br>
                        • <em>Invariant:</em> A square of side s with bottom-right at (i,j) requires all three sub-squares of side s-1 ending at (i-1,j), (i,j-1), (i-1,j-1). The side is limited by the minimum of all three.<br>
                        • <em>Forward:</em> If dp[i][j] = k, a k×k all-1s square exists (constructible from the three sub-squares). ✓<br>
                        • <em>Reverse:</em> If a k×k all-1s square ends at (i,j), all three neighbours have dp ≥ k-1. ✓<br>
                        • <em>Combined:</em> dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]) + 1 when grid[i][j]='1'. □
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 4 — Cherry Pickup I (Step-Reduction Correctness)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> The 4D state dp[r1][c1][r2][c2] (where r1+c1 = r2+c2 = t) reduces correctly to 3D dp[t][c1][c2].<br>
                        • <em>Reduction validity:</em> On step t, any valid forward path has r+c=t for each agent. Given c1 and c2, r1 and r2 are uniquely determined as r1 = t-c1, r2 = t-c2. No information lost.<br>
                        • <em>Transition validity:</em> Moving right increments c; moving down keeps r+c=t+1. Transitions (dc1, dc2) ∈ &#123;0,1&#125;² correctly enumerate all valid joint moves.<br>
                        • <em>Deduplication:</em> Cherry at (r,c) is collected by both agents only if r1=r2 AND c1=c2, i.e., c1=c2. Correct: add grid[r1][c1] + (grid[r2][c2] if c1≠c2 else 0). □
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 1 (Stage 2) — First row/column base case: not stopping after obstacle (Unique Paths II)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: sets all first-row cells to 1, ignoring obstacle
for j in range(m):
    dp[0][j] = 1   # wrong if obstacle exists in first row
# FIX: stop propagating after first obstacle
for j in range(m):
    if obstacleGrid[0][j] == 1:
        break
    dp[0][j] = 1</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 2 (Stage 2) — Dungeon game: forgetting max(1, ...) at destination</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: knight can have 0 or negative HP at exit
dp[n-1][m-1] = 1 - dungeon[n-1][m-1]   # can be ≤ 0
# FIX:
dp[n-1][m-1] = max(1, 1 - dungeon[n-1][m-1])</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 3 (Stage 2) — Triangle bottom-up: using wrong column indices</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: iterates j to full row length, accessing out of bounds
for i in range(n-2, -1, -1):
    for j in range(n):   # BUG: should be range(i+1)
        triangle[i][j] += min(triangle[i+1][j], triangle[i+1][j+1])
# FIX:
    for j in range(i+1):   # row i has i+1 elements</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 4 (Stage 2) — Maximal square: not checking grid[i][j]=='1' before applying recurrence</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: applies recurrence to 0-cells, inflating dp
dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]) + 1
# FIX:
if grid[i][j] == '1':
    dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1], dp[i-1][j-1]) + 1
else:
    dp[i][j] = 0</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 5 (Stage 5) — Min falling path II: not saving min1_col</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: always uses min1, even when j equals min1_col
dp[i][j] = matrix[i][j] + min1_prev   # wrong when j == min1_col
# FIX:
dp[i][j] = matrix[i][j] + (min1_prev if j != min1_col else min2_prev)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 6 (Stage 3) — Cherry Pickup II: double-counting cherries when c1==c2</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: counts grid[row][c1] + grid[row][c2] even when c1==c2
val = grid[row][c1] + grid[row][c2]
# FIX:
val = grid[row][c1] + (grid[row][c2] if c1 != c2 else 0)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 7 (Stage 3) — Out of Boundary Paths: forgetting modulo on intermediate values</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: dp values overflow without modulo
dp[i][j][k] += dp[ni][nj][k-1]
# FIX:
dp[i][j][k] = (dp[i][j][k] + dp[ni][nj][k-1]) % MOD</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 8 (Stage 3) — 3D DP rolling array: overwriting current layer</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: in-place update of dp[k] overwrites values needed for same layer
for i in range(n):
    for j in range(m):
        dp[i][j][k] = sum(dp[ni][nj][k-1] for ...)   # using dp[k] before done
# FIX: allocate a new 2D layer, fill from dp[k-1] only
new_layer = [[0]*m for _ in range(n)]
# populate new_layer from dp_prev[...]
dp_prev = new_layer</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 9 (Stage 4) — Cherry Pickup I: not bounding r1, r2 in [0, n-1]</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: accesses grid[-1][c] when step &lt; c (r = step - c &lt; 0)
val = grid[step-c1][c1]   # step-c1 can be negative
# FIX:
r1, r2 = step - c1, step - c2
if not (0 &lt;= r1 &lt; n and 0 &lt;= r2 &lt; n):
    continue   # skip invalid states</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="warn-box"><strong>Bug 10 (Stage 4) — Longest Increasing Path: only checking right and down</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># BUG: only 2 directions, misses left and up
dirs = [(0,1),(1,0)]   # misses left and up
# FIX: all 4 directions + strictly increasing condition
dirs = [(0,1),(1,0),(0,-1),(-1,0)]
if 0 &lt;= ni &lt; n and 0 &lt;= nj &lt; m and matrix[ni][nj] &gt; matrix[i][j]:
    dfs(ni, nj)</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 1] Using the same base case formula for all grid DPs</strong> — The base case is NOT always "first row and first column = 1." For min-path-sum it's the prefix sum of costs. For Dungeon Game it's a reverse computation from the exit. For triangle it's the bottom row values. <em>Correct model:</em> "The base case encodes the problem's boundary condition: what is the answer when there are no choices left?"</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 2] Applying forward DP to problems with a survival/resource lower bound</strong> — Forward DP accumulates "how much I've collected" — it cannot express "minimum I need to start with." Dungeon Game requires the state to be a lower bound, which only makes sense computed backwards. <em>Wrong model:</em> "dp[i][j] = max HP arriving at (i,j)." <em>Correct model:</em> "dp[i][j] = min HP needed at (i,j) to survive to exit."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] Multi-agent DP: processing agents sequentially instead of simultaneously</strong> — Computing the first agent's optimal path, then the second agent's "greedy best given what's left" is provably suboptimal. Agents must be modelled with a JOINT state because their collections interact. <em>Wrong model:</em> "Run two separate DPs." <em>Correct model:</em> "State = (row, c1, c2); both agents advance one row per step; deduplication at c1==c2."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 4] Applying row-major DP to Longest Increasing Path</strong> — Row-major DP processes cells in row 0, then row 1. For LIP, cell (0,3) might depend on (1,3) if matrix[1][3] &lt; matrix[0][3]. The DAG direction is data-dependent. <em>Wrong model:</em> "Use bottom-up DP like other grid problems." <em>Correct model:</em> "When topological order is data-dependent, use DFS + memoisation; DFS naturally follows edges in the correct order."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 3] Number of Paths with Max Score: overwriting count on score tie</strong> — When dp[i][j].score == candidate_score, the correct action is to ADD the incoming count to the existing count, not overwrite it. <em>Correct model:</em> "When updating a (score, count) pair: new_score &gt; old → replace; equal → add counts; less → ignore."</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 5] Maximal Rectangle: not resetting heights on 0-cell</strong> — If grid[i][j]='0', the height must reset to 0 — the consecutive-1s streak is broken. <em>Correct model:</em> heights[j] = heights[j] + 1 if grid[i][j]=='1' else 0.</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">🚩 <strong>[Stage 2/5] Space optimisation breaking the recurrence (rolling row overwriting needed values)</strong> — Rolling a 2D DP into O(m) space requires that dp[i][j] only needs the PREVIOUS row and already-computed current row values. <em>Correct model:</em> "Before optimising space, list which previous cells the recurrence reads; ensure none are overwritten before they are read."</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 2 Follow-Ups (Constraint Mutations)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>"In Minimum Path Sum, what if you can also move UP in addition to right/down?"</td><td>Topological order breaks; use BFS or Dijkstra on the grid as a weighted graph; DP no longer directly applicable</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>"What if the grid has negative weights in Minimum Path Sum? Does your solution still work?"</td><td>Yes — the recurrence handles negative values correctly; key is that movement is still strictly right/down, so topological order is preserved</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 3 Follow-Ups (State Expansion)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>"Extend Unique Paths to count paths where the total sum of cells visited equals exactly S."</td><td>Add sum S as third dimension: dp[i][j][s] = number of paths to (i,j) with cell-sum exactly s; O(nm·S); feasible only for small S</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>"In Cherry Pickup II, what if three robots start from row 0 instead of two?"</td><td>State = dp[row][c1][c2][c3]; O(n·m³) — feasible for m≤20; cherry deduplication: add grid value once for each unique column among &#123;c1,c2,c3&#125;</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 4 Follow-Ups (Hidden Reductions)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>"How would you solve Maximal Square if the constraint is rectangles instead of squares?"</td><td>Reduce to Maximal Rectangle (LC 85): for each row, compute column heights; apply largest rectangle in histogram (monotone stack); O(nm)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>"In Longest Increasing Path, what if you need the actual path, not just the length?"</td><td>During DFS+memo, also store the next cell in the optimal direction; during answer extraction, follow parent pointers; O(nm) space for parent array</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 5 Follow-Ups (Optimisation Pressure)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>"Minimum Falling Path Sum II TLEs for n=1000. How do you speed it up from O(n³) to O(n²)?"</td><td>Track min1, min2, min1_col across the previous row; each cell in the new row uses min1 unless column equals min1_col, then uses min2; O(1) per cell</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>"What if in Minimum Path Sum you must avoid all cells with value &gt; K?"</td><td>Validity check: if grid[i][j] &gt; K, set dp[i][j] = ∞; propagation avoids infeasible cells; if dp[n-1][m-1] = ∞, no valid path exists</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Beyond Stage 5 (Online / Distributed)</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>"The grid is too large to store in memory (n=10⁶). How do you compute min path sum row-by-row?"</td><td>Only the previous row's dp values are needed; stream the grid row by row, keeping a single O(m) array; update in-place left to right; O(m) memory</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>"Grid values change dynamically (online updates). How do you maintain min path sum efficiently?"</td><td>2D segment tree or 2D BIT for point updates + range queries; a single cell update affects O(nm) downstream cells in the worst case — motivates caching the DP and only recomputing the affected subgraph</td></tr>
                        </tbody></table></div>

