            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
                 TOPIC 32 — THE KNAPSACK FAMILY (MASTERY)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp32">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">32</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">The Knapsack Family</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Dynamic Programming</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">0/1 · Unbounded · Bounded · 2D · Grouped · Tree · Bitset · Meet-in-Middle</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">31 problems · 5 stages · subset sum, count ways, multi-dimensional capacity, disguised reductions, bitset optimisation</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> The Knapsack Family solves problems where you must select a subset of items to optimise a value subject to one or more capacity constraints, where each item can be taken 0 times (0/1), unlimited times (unbounded), or a bounded number of times. The core invariant is: dp[j] = the optimal value achievable using exactly (or at most) capacity j, computed by iterating items one by one and deciding whether to include each. It appears in nearly every top-tier interview because the surface variants (boolean, count, min, max) look different but share identical recurrence structure — the only thing that changes is the operation (OR, +, min, max) and the iteration direction (forward for unbounded reuse, reverse for 0/1). At ICPC level, the hard variants involve multi-dimensional capacity, grouped items, and disguised reductions where the "items" and "capacity" are not obvious from the problem statement.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>The Knapsack is a budget problem.</strong> You have a budget (capacity). Each item has a price (weight) and a benefit (value). You fill the budget optimally, one item at a time, by asking: "For every budget level j, does including this item improve the answer?" The answer at each budget level is computed from previously computed budget levels.<br><br>
                        <strong>How this scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 1:</strong> One item type, one capacity. dp[j] = can we hit exactly sum j? Reverse iterate to prevent reuse (0/1).<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2:</strong> Change the operation — count ways instead of boolean. Or change the item limit — unbounded (forward iterate). Same 1D array, one rule flips.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3:</strong> Add a second capacity dimension. dp[j][k] — two independent budgets must both be satisfied simultaneously. State grows but invariant is identical.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 4:</strong> The problem doesn't hand you items and a capacity. You must derive what the items are, what the weights are, and what the capacity is. Recognition IS the hard part.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 5:</strong> The capacity is too large for a table. Replace with a sparse representation (bitset, hash map) or reduce via mathematical insight (meet-in-the-middle, binary grouping of bounded items).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant &amp; Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> After processing item i, dp[j] = optimal value achievable using items from &#123;1..i&#125; with capacity exactly (or at most) j.<br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (by induction on items processed):</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Base case:</strong> Before any item is processed, dp[0] = 0 (or True/1 for counting) and dp[j] = ∞/False/0 for j&gt;0 (infeasible). Correct vacuously.<br>
                        • <strong>Inductive hypothesis:</strong> After processing items &#123;1..i-1&#125;, dp[j] is correct for all j.<br>
                        • <strong>Inductive step for 0/1:</strong> For item i with weight w and value v, iterating j from W down to w: dp[j] = op(dp[j], dp[j-w] + v). Since we iterate high-to-low, dp[j-w] still reflects items &#123;1..i-1&#125; (not yet updated for item i) — so item i is counted at most once. ✓<br>
                        • <strong>Inductive step for unbounded:</strong> Forward iteration: dp[j-w] may already include item i, allowing unlimited reuse. ✓<br>
                        • <strong>Correctness of operation:</strong> The recurrence is valid IFF "the optimal solution for budget j either includes item i (using dp[j-w] from a sub-budget) or doesn't (using the old dp[j])." This is optimal substructure — verify once per problem.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Variant</th><th>Stage</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>New Idea</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>0/1 Knapsack — boolean (subset sum)</td><td>1</td><td>O(nW)</td><td>O(W)</td><td>dp[j] |= dp[j-w[i]]; reverse iteration is the ONLY mechanism preventing reuse</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>0/1 Knapsack — count ways</td><td>2</td><td>O(nW)</td><td>O(W)</td><td>Additive recurrence replaces boolean OR; dp[0]=1</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>0/1 Knapsack — max value</td><td>2</td><td>O(nW)</td><td>O(W)</td><td>Value array added; recurrence maximises instead of counting</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Unbounded Knapsack — min cost</td><td>2</td><td>O(nW)</td><td>O(W)</td><td>Forward iteration enables unlimited item reuse; base case dp[0]=0, rest =∞</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Unbounded Knapsack — count ways</td><td>2</td><td>O(nW)</td><td>O(W)</td><td>Same forward iterate but additive; counts ordered vs unordered depends on loop nesting</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Ordered vs unordered count</td><td>2</td><td>O(nW)</td><td>O(W)</td><td>Putting capacity loop OUTER, items INNER counts ordered compositions (permutations); items OUTER counts unordered combinations</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Bounded Knapsack (each item i usable at most k[i] times)</td><td>3</td><td>O(nWK) naïve → O(nW log K) binary grouping → O(nW) deque</td><td>O(W)</td><td>Per-item count limit; binary grouping converts to 0/1 knapsack in O(log K) items per type</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2D Knapsack (two capacity dimensions)</td><td>3</td><td>O(n·W₁·W₂)</td><td>O(W₁·W₂)</td><td>Second independent capacity constraint; state is dp[j][k]</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Grouped Knapsack (exactly one item from each group)</td><td>3</td><td>O(n·W·G)</td><td>O(W)</td><td>Items are partitioned into groups; exactly one from each group must be chosen</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Multiple-choice Knapsack</td><td>3</td><td>O(n·W)</td><td>O(W)</td><td>From each group, choose at most one item (not exactly one)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Knapsack with item dependency (tree knapsack)</td><td>4</td><td>O(n²W)</td><td>O(nW)</td><td>Item j can only be selected if parent item is also selected; tree structure on items</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Subset-sum with balanced partition</td><td>4</td><td>O(nW)</td><td>O(W)</td><td>"Partition into two equal halves" → find subset summing to total/2; reduction IS the insight</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Bitset-optimised knapsack</td><td>5</td><td>O(nW/64)</td><td>O(W/64)</td><td>Boolean knapsack as bitset; each bit shift = adding one item weight; 64× speedup</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Meet-in-the-middle knapsack</td><td>5</td><td>O(2^(n/2) log n)</td><td>O(2^(n/2))</td><td>When n is small (≤40) but W is huge, enumerate all subset sums of half the items; binary search for complement</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Knapsack on difference / "closest to target"</td><td>4</td><td>O(nW)</td><td>O(W)</td><td>Instead of exact target, find the achievable sum closest to W; scan dp array after filling</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Knapsack with profit threshold (Profitable Schemes)</td><td>3</td><td>O(n·members·profit)</td><td>O(members·profit)</td><td>Second value dimension (profit) capped/bucketed at threshold; overflow treated as exact target</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>

