                    <div class="sec-title">Graduation Test</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        These three problems are NOT in the table above. Solving all three cold (no hints, no editorial, 45 min each) certifies full mastery.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 1 — LC 2809: Minimum Time to Make Array Sum At Most k</strong> (Stage 4 + Stage 3)<br>
                        <em>Primary stage: Stage 4.</em> Combination: Stage 4 (recognise as "select a subset to zero out, others grow over time" — the optimal subset to freeze is the k items with largest value; combined with a knapsack feasibility check on time budget) + Stage 3 (the "time" calculation requires tracking two quantities simultaneously: current sum and number of items selected). Why it certifies mastery: The reduction from "time-based array sum" to knapsack is non-obvious (Stage 4). Once reduced, the state requires simultaneous tracking of sum and count (Stage 3). Solving cold proves the candidate can identify knapsack structure in a dynamic array problem.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 2 — CF 1856E – I Wanna be the Team Leader</strong> (Stage 3 + Stage 4)<br>
                        <em>Primary stage: Stage 3.</em> Combination: Stage 4 (recognise as knapsack where items are team members, "weight" is skill coverage, and "capacity" is the required full coverage) + Stage 3 (coverage is a bitmask — adds a bitmask dimension to the state; dp[j][mask] = can j people cover skill set mask). Why it certifies mastery: The bitmask-dimension knapsack requires Stage 4 recognition (skills → bitmask = capacity) AND Stage 3 state expansion (bitmask as extra dimension). Both must fire simultaneously on an unseen Codeforces problem.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 3 — USACO Gold: Talent Show</strong> (Stage 4 + Stage 5)<br>
                        <em>Primary stage: Stage 5.</em> Combination: Stage 4 (reduce "maximise talent-to-weight ratio subject to minimum total weight W" to a fractional/parametric knapsack — binary search on the ratio, convert to standard 0/1 feasibility knapsack per binary search step) + Stage 5 (the binary search on the real-valued ratio reduces an O(nW·log) search to O(nW·log(maxRatio)) which needs careful precision handling). Why it certifies mastery: Parametric search converting an optimisation knapsack to a feasibility knapsack is a non-obvious Stage 4 transformation. The precision management of binary search on rational ratios is a Stage 5 implementation challenge. Solving cold in 45 minutes proves mastery of the full knapsack staircase.
                    </div>
