            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
                 TOPIC 33 — STRINGS & SUBSEQUENCES (MASTERY)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp33">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">33</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">Strings &amp; Subsequences</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Dynamic Programming</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">LCS · Edit Distance · Interval DP · Regex · Wildcard · Palindrome · Distinct Subseq</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">31 problems · 5 stages · two-string prefix DP, interval DP, pattern matching, affine gap, suffix array reduction</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> String &amp; Subsequence DP solves problems where the answer depends on relationships between characters across one or two strings — matching, aligning, transforming, or selecting characters in order. The core invariant is: dp[i][j] represents the optimal answer for the subproblem defined on the first i characters of string 1 and the first j characters of string 2 (or dp[i][j] for the substring s[i..j] in single-string interval DP), computed from strictly smaller subproblems in a defined topological order. It is one of the most tested categories in top-tier interviews because: (1) the state is always 2D but the transitions have only 3–4 cases — the pattern is learnable; (2) interval DP on a single string (palindrome problems) looks structurally different but uses the same filling order; and (3) the hard variants (edit distance with costs, regex matching, wildcard matching, SCS reconstruction) require precise state definition and transition logic that separates candidates who memorised from those who understood.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>String DP is a table-filling race.</strong> You place two strings along the axes of a grid. Each cell (i,j) asks: "What is the best relationship between the prefix of string 1 up to position i and the prefix of string 2 up to position j?" You fill the cell using only cells to its left, above, or diagonally above-left — because those represent strictly smaller prefixes. The shape of "best" (longest match, fewest edits, number of ways) defines the recurrence.<br><br>
                        <strong>How this scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 1:</strong> Two strings. Cell (i,j) depends on (i-1,j-1), (i-1,j), (i,j-1). One simple condition on s1[i] == s2[j].<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2:</strong> Same grid, ONE condition flips — count instead of length, strict vs. non-strict, single string instead of two (LPS = LCS of string and its reverse).<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3:</strong> State gains a third dimension — an edit cost type, a constraint (at most k mismatches), or a multiplier.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 4:</strong> The problem doesn't hand you two strings. You must derive the strings or recognise that the DP grid on ONE string indexed by (i,j) represents an INTERVAL, not a pair of prefixes.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 5:</strong> The O(n²) or O(nm) solution is too slow. Replace the inner loop with a suffix array, bitset, or sparse data structure.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant &amp; Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant for two-string DP:</strong> dp[i][j] = optimal value for the subproblem on s1[0..i-1] and s2[0..j-1], computed after all dp[i'][j'] with i' ≤ i, j' ≤ j, (i',j') ≠ (i,j).<br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (strong induction on i+j):</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Base cases:</strong> dp[0][j] and dp[i][0] are computed directly (empty prefix vs. non-empty prefix).<br>
                        • <strong>Inductive step:</strong> dp[i][j] depends only on dp[i-1][j-1], dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]. Each has a strictly smaller value of i+j, so they are computed first in row-major order.<br>
                        • <strong>Optimal substructure:</strong> For LCS: any common subsequence of s1[0..i-1] and s2[0..j-1] either includes both s1[i-1] and s2[j-1] (if they match), or excludes at least one. These three cases are exhaustive and mutually exclusive.<br>
                        • <strong>Correctness:</strong> The maximum over the three cases = LCS length. Each case is handled by the three recurrence branches. No case is missed. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Invariant for interval DP:</strong> dp[i][j] = optimal value for substring s[i..j]. Filling in order of increasing length (j - i) ensures all sub-intervals are computed before the interval that contains them.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Variant</th><th>Stage</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>New Idea</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Longest Common Subsequence (LCS)</td><td>1</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(min(n,m))</td><td>dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]+1 if match, else max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]); the fundamental two-string DP template</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Longest Common Substring (contiguous)</td><td>2</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(min(n,m))</td><td>dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]+1 if match, else 0; no max — reset forces contiguity</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Edit Distance (Levenshtein)</td><td>2</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(min(n,m))</td><td>Three transitions (insert, delete, substitute) instead of two; mismatch adds cost instead of taking max</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Edit Distance with custom costs</td><td>2</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(min(n,m))</td><td>Insert cost ≠ delete cost ≠ substitute cost; weights parameterised per operation</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Shortest Common Supersequence (SCS)</td><td>3</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>SCS length = n + m - LCS; reconstruct by traversing the LCS table; teaches table reconstruction</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Count distinct LCS</td><td>3</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>Track (length, count) per cell; on tie, ADD counts; on new max, replace</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Longest Palindromic Subsequence (LPS)</td><td>2</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Single string → reduce to LCS with its own reverse; introduces the "reverse trick"</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Minimum insertions to make palindrome</td><td>2</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>Min insertions = n - LPS; reduction to LPS IS the insight</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Palindrome partitioning DP (min cuts)</td><td>3</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>dp[i] = min cuts for s[0..i]; inner loop over all palindromic suffixes; two-phase DP</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Interval DP — palindrome counting/length</td><td>3</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Single string indexed by INTERVAL (i,j) not prefix pair; fill order = increasing length</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Regular expression matching</td><td>3</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>* in pattern matches zero or more of preceding char; dp[i][j] = dp[i][j-2] (zero) OR dp[i-1][j] (one more)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Wildcard matching</td><td>3</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>* matches any sequence (not "zero or more of preceding"); dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j] or dp[i][j-1] when p[j-1]='*'</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Distinct subsequences (count occurrences of t in s)</td><td>3</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>On match, ADD skip-option: dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j]; teaches additive branching</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Is subsequence (check, not count)</td><td>1</td><td>O(n) two-pointer</td><td>O(1)</td><td>When count is just boolean and t is short, two-pointer is O(n); teaches when to not use 2D DP</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Interleaving strings</td><td>3</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>Boolean DP; two transitions (use char from s1 OR from s2); character matching with position constraint</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Minimum ASCII delete sum</td><td>2</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>Weighted LCS — instead of counting length, accumulate character costs; same recurrence structure</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Longest Repeating Subsequence</td><td>4</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>LCS of a string with itself, but position indices must differ; adds one index-inequality constraint</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Number of distinct palindromic subsequences</td><td>4</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Count distinct subsequences that are palindromes; requires tracking first/last character positions in interval</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>LCS with at most k mismatches</td><td>3</td><td>O(nmk)</td><td>O(nmk)</td><td>Third dimension tracks remaining mismatch budget; dp[i][j][k] grows state but invariant unchanged</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Longest Common Extension / Z-function DP</td><td>5</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>LCS/LRS on long strings → suffix array + LCP array collapses O(n²) to O(n log n)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Sequence alignment with affine gap penalty</td><td>3</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>Gap OPEN cost ≠ gap EXTEND cost; requires 3-state DP (match, gap-in-s1, gap-in-s2)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Edit distance with block operations</td><td>4</td><td>O(n²m²)</td><td>O(n²m²)</td><td>Operations are on SUBSTRINGS, not single characters; state must encode source and target substrings</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Shortest common supersequence reconstruction</td><td>3</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>O(nm)</td><td>Reconstruction from DP table using three-way backtracking; teaches table backtracking</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>

