                    <div class="sec-title">🔧 Custom Problem 29 — Longest Common Subsequence of K Strings</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Problem:</strong> Given K strings s₁, s₂, ..., sₖ each of length at most N, find the length of their longest common subsequence (a subsequence appearing in all K strings).<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 2 ≤ K ≤ 5, 1 ≤ N ≤ 100<br><br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> K=3, s1="abcde", s2="ace", s3="aec" → LCS = "ac" = 2<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3/4 solution:</strong> Generalise the 2D LCS: state is dp[i1][i2]...[ik] = length of LCS of s1[0..i1-1], s2[0..i2-1], ..., sk[0..ik-1]. Recurrence: if all characters s1[i1-1] == s2[i2-1] == ... == sk[ik-1], then dp[...] = dp[i1-1,...,ik-1] + 1. Otherwise, take max over k options of decrementing one index. Time: O(Nᴷ). For K=5, N=100: 10¹⁰ — infeasible. For K≤3, N≤100: 10⁶ — feasible. The problem teaches: (1) natural generalisation of 2D to kD DP; (2) exponential blowup and when to stop generalising; (3) the "all-match diagonal" branch scales to k dimensions cleanly.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 1: Two-String Prefix DP</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 — LCS:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = length of LCS of s1[0..i-1] and s2[0..j-1]<br>
                        If s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]: dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1; else: dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])<br>
                        Base: dp[0][j] = dp[i][0] = 0<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up row by row — O(min(n,m)) space with single rolling row<br>
                        Optimisation (Stage 5): LCS → LIS reduction for special character sets; O(n log n)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — Edit Distance:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = min edits to convert s1[0..i-1] to s2[0..j-1]<br>
                        If match: dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]; else: dp[i][j] = 1 + min(dp[i-1][j-1], dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])<br>
                        Base: dp[0][j] = j; dp[i][0] = i<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up — two rows sufficient (rolling)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — Longest Common Substring:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = length of common substring ending at s1[i-1] and s2[j-1]<br>
                        dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1 if s1[i-1]==s2[j-1] else 0; answer = max(dp[i][j])<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up; O(min(n,m)) rolling space; track global max<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 2: Single-String Interval DP</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — Longest Palindromic Subsequence:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = length of LPS in s[i..j]<br>
                        If s[i] == s[j]: dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j-1] + 2; else: dp[i][j] = max(dp[i+1][j], dp[i][j-1])<br>
                        Base: dp[i][i] = 1; dp[i][i-1] = 0<br>
                        Key traversal: <code>for l in range(1, n+1): for i in range(n-l+1): j = i+l-1</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Palindrome Boolean Table:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = True if s[i..j] is a palindrome<br>
                        dp[i][j] = (s[i]==s[j]) and dp[i+1][j-1]; base: dp[i][i]=True; dp[i][i+1] = (s[i]==s[i+1])<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up by increasing length (same traversal as LPS)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Min Palindrome Cuts:</strong><br>
                        Phase 1: Build isPalin[i][j] as above<br>
                        Phase 2: cuts[i] = min cuts for s[0..i]; cuts[i] = min(cuts[j-1]+1 for j in 0..i if isPalin[j][i]); cuts[j-1] uses -1 for j==0<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 3: Three-State / Complex Pattern Matching</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Regular Expression:</strong><br>
                        dp[i][j] = True if s[0..i-1] matches p[0..j-1]<br>
                        p[j-1]=='*': dp[i][j] = dp[i][j-2] (zero of prev) OR (dp[i-1][j] and (s[i-1]==p[j-2] or p[j-2]=='.'))<br>
                        p[j-1]=='.': dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]<br>
                        else: dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] and s[i-1]==p[j-1]<br>
                        Base: dp[0][0]=True; dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-2] if p[j-1]=='*' (handle a*b*c* matching empty)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Affine Gap Alignment (3-state machine):</strong><br>
                        Three states per cell: M[i][j] (match/mismatch), X[i][j] (gap in s2), Y[i][j] (gap in s1)<br>
                        M[i][j] = max(M[i-1][j-1], X[i-1][j-1], Y[i-1][j-1]) + score(s1[i-1],s2[j-1])<br>
                        X[i][j] = max(M[i-1][j] - gap_open, X[i-1][j] - gap_extend)<br>
                        Y[i][j] = max(M[i][j-1] - gap_open, Y[i][j-1] - gap_extend)<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up — each cell computes three values; O(nm) time
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • "longest common subsequence / substring between two strings" → Stage 1 LCS / Stage 2 substring — immediate 2D DP; check contiguous (reset) vs non-contiguous (max)<br>
                        • "minimum edits / insertions / deletions to transform / match" → Stage 2 Edit Distance — three-operation recurrence; base = i or j (delete full prefix)<br>
                        • "number of distinct ways to form / embed string t in string s" → Stage 3 Distinct Subsequences — additive match branch; dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j] on match<br>
                        • "is s a valid interleaving of s1 and s2" → Stage 3 Interleaving — boolean DP; two source strings contribute to one target<br>
                        • "minimum cuts to partition string into palindromes" → Stage 3 Palindrome Cuts — two-phase: precompute palindrome table; then cut DP<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • Two strings given as input; answer is a scalar (length, count, cost) → Row-major 2D DP; O(nm) time; check direction (forward accumulation vs. reverse for LPS)<br>
                        • Single string; answer involves SUBSTRINGS s[i..j] (not prefixes) → Interval DP; fill by increasing length j-i<br>
                        • Pattern has * or . wildcard characters → Regex or Wildcard matching; * is the distinguishing branch<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • n, m ≤ 1000 → O(nm) DP is 10⁶ operations; feasible; standard 2D string DP<br>
                        • n ≤ 500 and answer is on single string intervals → O(n²) interval DP; also feasible<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • "find if pattern exists as substring (not subsequence)" → NOT DP → Use KMP or Z-function; substring matching has linear algorithms<br>
                        • "find all occurrences of a set of words in a stream" → NOT subsequence DP → Use Aho-Corasick automaton; multiple pattern matching ≠ subsequence DP<br>
                        • "longest duplicate substring for n ≥ 10⁴" → NOT LCS(s,s) because O(n²) TLEs → Use binary search + Rabin-Karp rolling hash for O(n log n)
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;white-space:pre-wrap">Q1: Does the problem involve one or two strings and ask for
    a scalar about character relationships (length, count, cost)?
  → NO:  Not string DP. Consider graph, greedy, or hashing.
  → YES: Continue.

Q2: Are there TWO strings (or does the problem compare a string
    with another string / its reverse / a pattern)?
  → YES: Two-string prefix DP. dp[i][j] on prefix pair.
         Go to Q3.
  → NO (single string, intervals): Interval DP.
         Fill by increasing length. Go to Q6.

Q3: What is the relationship on MATCH (s1[i-1] == s2[j-1])?
  → Extend (dp = dp[i-1][j-1]+1): LCS / common substring.
       Contiguous? → Reset on mismatch (dp[i][j]=0 on mismatch).
       Non-contiguous? → max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]) on mismatch.
  → No cost (dp = dp[i-1][j-1]): Edit Distance on match.
       Three-operation mismatch: dp[i][j] = 1 + min(diag, up, left).
  → Count (dp += dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j]): Distinct Subsequences.
  → Boolean (True): Regex / Wildcard / Interleaving.
         Has '*'? → Regex (with prev char) or Wildcard (standalone).
         Two source strings → one target? → Interleaving.

Q4: Is there an additional constraint (k mismatches, k deletions)?
  → YES: Add k as third dimension. O(nmk). Stage 3.
  → NO: Continue.

Q5: Is the problem disguised?
  → Sequence of arrays/integers matching a pattern?
       → Treat array elements as characters. Same 2D DP.
  → Column-frequency from word list?
       → Preprocess to frequency table; then subsequence count DP.
  → YES to any: Stage 4. O(nm) after transformation.

Q6 (Interval DP path): What does dp[i][j] represent?
  → Is s[i..j] a palindrome? → Boolean interval DP. Base dp[i][i]=True.
  → Length of LPS in s[i..j]? → LPS interval DP. Base dp[i][i]=1.
  → Min cuts in s[i..j]? → Cut DP after palindrome precomputation.
  → Can s1[i..l] scramble to s2[j..l]? → 3D interval DP. Stage 4.

Q7: Is the solution too slow?
  → O(nm) with n,m &gt; 10⁴: LCS → LIS reduction → O(n log n).
  → O(n²) with n &gt; 10⁴: Binary search + rolling hash for substring problems.
  → Suffix array + LCP array for LRS / distinct substrings.

Stage identification:
  Q3 (simple match/mismatch) → Stage 1/2. O(nm).
  Q4 (extra dimension) → Stage 3. O(nmk).
  Q5 (disguised) → Stage 4. O(nm) after transform.
  Q7 (TLE) → Stage 5. O(n log n).</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Using LCS recurrence for contiguous substring:</strong> The LCS max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]) propagates length forward even through mismatches. For contiguous substrings, this is wrong — reset to 0 on mismatch. Applying LCS to "longest common substring" gives inflated lengths.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Edit distance with wrong base cases:</strong> dp[i][0] must equal i (delete all i characters from s1 to reach empty). Setting dp[i][0]=0 makes the first column wrong, corrupting the entire table. Similarly dp[0][j]=j.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Distinct subsequences: missing the skip branch on match:</strong> On s[i-1]==t[j-1], the correct recurrence is dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j]. The + dp[i-1][j] term counts the cases where s[i-1] is NOT used to match t[j-1]. Missing this gives wrong counts by ignoring valid matchings.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Regex matching: wrong base case for patterns like a*b*c* matching empty string:</strong> dp[0][j] must handle patterns that can match empty: if p[j-1]=='*', then dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-2]. Without this, a* can't match an empty string — breaking all downstream cells.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Interval DP wrong traversal order:</strong> Filling dp[i][j] row by row (increasing i, then j) processes dp[i+1][j-1] before dp[i][j] only if i+1 &gt; i — which means the diagonal is computed AFTER, not before. Must fill by INCREASING LENGTH l = j-i+1, otherwise inner intervals aren't ready.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Applying 2D prefix DP to interval DP problems:</strong> For problems about substrings s[i..j] (not prefixes), the state is not "first i characters vs first j characters" but "characters from i to j." The recurrence and traversal order are fundamentally different. Mixing them gives wrong answers.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] LCS for large n using O(n²) DP (TLE):</strong> When n &gt; 10⁴, the standard O(nm) DP TLEs. For strings over small alphabets, reduce to LIS: find the positions of each character of s1 in s2 (reverse-sorted), concatenate, run LIS → O(n log n). Not recognising this reduction leads to TLE.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 — LCS (Optimal Substructure by Cases)</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[i][j] = length of LCS of s1[0..i-1] and s2[0..j-1].<br>
                        Case 1 (s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]): The LCS must end with this character (exchange argument: any LCS of the prefixes that doesn't end with this character can be extended by appending it, contradicting maximality). So dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1. ✓<br>
                        Case 2 (mismatch): The LCS cannot use both s1[i-1] and s2[j-1] (they differ). It either uses s1[i-1] (meaning s2[j-1] is excluded → dp[i][j-1]), or uses s2[j-1] (meaning s1[i-1] excluded → dp[i-1][j]), or neither (bounded by both). The max of the first two covers all cases. ✓<br>
                        Induction: Both cases use values at strictly smaller (i+j), which are correct by induction. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — Edit Distance (Correctness of Three Operations)</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[i][j] = minimum edits to transform s1[0..i-1] into s2[0..j-1].<br>
                        Base cases: dp[0][j] = j (insert j characters); dp[i][0] = i (delete i characters). Both correct.<br>
                        Inductive step: To transform s1[0..i-1] to s2[0..j-1], the last operation is one of:<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Match/replace s1[i-1] → s2[j-1]: cost = dp[i-1][j-1] + (0 if match else 1)<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Delete s1[i-1] (not in s2 prefix): cost = dp[i-1][j] + 1<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Insert s2[j-1] (after processing s1[0..i-1]): cost = dp[i][j-1] + 1<br>
                        These three cases are exhaustive (every sequence of edits has a last operation that falls into one of these categories). Taking the minimum gives the optimal. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Interval DP Palindrome (Correctness of Length-Based Filling)</strong><br>
                        Claim: If we fill dp[i][j] for all intervals with j-i = l before processing j-i = l+1, then dp[i][j] is correctly computed when needed by larger intervals.<br>
                        Invariant: When computing dp[i][j] (interval of length l+1), the recurrence uses dp[i+1][j-1] (length l-1) and dp[i+1][j], dp[i][j-1] (length l). All three have length ≤ l, so they were computed in earlier iterations. ✓<br>
                        Row-major order fails: If we fill row i before row i+1, dp[i][j] needs dp[i+1][j-1] which is in row i+1 — not yet computed. This demonstrates why length-based filling is mandatory for interval DP. □
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Bug 1 — LCS: using 0-indexed strings with 1-indexed DP without offset</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: dp[i][j] reads s1[i] instead of s1[i-1]
if s1[i] == s2[j]:
    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1
# FIX: DP is 1-indexed; strings are 0-indexed
if s1[i-1] == s2[j-1]:
    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 2 — Edit distance: wrong base case dp[0][0]=1</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: dp[0][0]=1 → transforming empty to empty costs 1
dp[0][0] = 1  # BUG
# FIX:
dp[0][0] = 0  # empty to empty = 0 edits</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 3 — Edit distance: not initialising first row and column</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: base cases for first row and column not set
dp = [[0]*(m+1) for _ in range(n+1)]
# FIX: fill entire first row and column
for i in range(n+1): dp[i][0] = i
for j in range(m+1): dp[0][j] = j</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 4 — Longest common substring: propagating length through mismatch</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]) gives LCS not substring
if s1[i-1] != s2[j-1]:
    dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1])  # BUG
# FIX: reset to 0 on mismatch for contiguous
    dp[i][j] = 0</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 5 — Distinct subsequences: forgetting skip branch on match</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: only counts matchings that USE s[i-1]
if s[i-1] == t[j-1]:
    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]  # BUG: missing + dp[i-1][j]
# FIX:
    dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + dp[i-1][j]</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 6 — Regex matching: missing dp[0][j] for patterns with *</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: dp[0][j]=False for all j → "a*" can't match ""
dp = [[False]*(len(p)+1) for _ in range(len(s)+1)]
dp[0][0] = True
# FIX: handle patterns that match empty string
for j in range(2, len(p)+1):
    if p[j-1] == '*':
        dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-2]  # "x*" matches empty</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 7 — Interval DP: filling by row instead of by length</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: dp[i+1][j-1] not computed yet in row-major order
for i in range(n):
    for j in range(i, n):    # BUG: row-major
        if s[i]==s[j]: dp[i][j] = dp[i+1][j-1] and True
# FIX: fill by increasing length
for l in range(2, n+1):
    for i in range(n-l+1):
        j = i + l - 1
        dp[i][j] = (s[i]==s[j]) and dp[i+1][j-1]</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 8 — Palindrome cuts: off-by-one in cuts array</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: cuts[j-1] when j=0 → cuts[-1] (Python wraps to last element)
for i in range(n):
    for j in range(i+1):
        if isPalin[j][i]:
            cuts[i] = min(cuts[i], cuts[j-1] + 1)  # BUG when j=0
# FIX:
            cuts[i] = min(cuts[i], 0 if j == 0 else cuts[j-1] + 1)</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 9 — LPS via LCS(s, reverse): passing same string twice</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: LCS of s with itself gives len(s), not LPS
lps = LCS(s, s)   # BUG: trivial self-match
# FIX:
lps = LCS(s, s[::-1])  # reverse s; LCS with reversed gives LPS</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 10 — Rolling row LCS: overwriting values in current row</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: dp[j-1] in current row already updated; prev diagonal lost
for i in range(m):
    for j in range(n):
        if s1[i] == s2[j]:
            dp[j] = prev_dp[j-1] + 1
        else:
            dp[j] = max(prev_dp[j], dp[j-1])
# FIX: copy prev_dp BEFORE the inner loop
prev_dp = dp[:]  # snapshot before row i updates</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Treating LCS and Longest Common Substring as the same problem:</strong> LCS is non-contiguous (characters can be scattered). Longest Common Substring is contiguous (characters must be adjacent). The recurrence differs in one critical place: LCS takes max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]) on mismatch; substring resets to 0. Wrong model: "Both find 'common' characters." Correct model: "Subsequence = characters in order but not necessarily adjacent; substring = characters in order AND adjacent."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Edit distance: counting match as cost 1 instead of 0:</strong> The diagonal transition on match is dp[i-1][j-1] (no cost added), not dp[i-1][j-1]+1. This mistake makes the algorithm count the total number of character pairs, not the minimum edits. Correct model: "Match costs 0 (no edit needed). Only the three mismatch operations cost 1 each."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Interval DP filled in row-major order:</strong> For interval DP, dp[i][j] depends on dp[i+1][j-1] — which is in the NEXT row. Row-major order computes row i before row i+1, so dp[i+1][j-1] isn't ready. This gives wrong answers for all intervals of length ≥ 3. Correct model: "Interval DP must be filled in increasing ORDER OF INTERVAL LENGTH, not row by row."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Regex matching: treating * as standalone (like wildcard) instead of bound to previous character:</strong> In regex, * means "zero or more of the PRECEDING character." The pattern index jumps by 2 (j-2) to consume both x and *. Treating * as standalone makes it match any single character — wrong. Correct model: "a* in regex is a unit; it matches '', 'a', 'aa', etc. The * consumes both itself and its predecessor from the pattern."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Distinct subsequences: confusing dp[i][j] semantics:</strong> The outer loop should iterate over s (i from 1 to m) and inner over t (j from 1 to n). Swapping them gives wrong state semantics where j advances over s and i over t, inverting the "embedding" direction. Correct model: "dp[i][j] = number of ways to form t[0..j-1] using characters from s[0..i-1]. s is the longer string; t is the pattern being embedded."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Using two-pointer for distinct subsequences count:</strong> Two-pointer correctly determines IF t is a subsequence of s (O(n) time). But it cannot COUNT the distinct ways — it greedily takes the first available match. Counting requires the full 2D DP. Correct model: "Two-pointer for boolean IS-subsequence. 2D DP for COUNT of distinct subsequence occurrences."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Not applying LCS→LIS reduction when n is large:</strong> For strings with small alphabets (binary, DNA), LCS can be reduced to LIS using position lists, giving O(n log n). Applying the O(nm) DP for n=m=10⁵ gives 10¹⁰ operations — always TLE. Correct model: "If n,m &gt; 5×10³ for LCS, immediately ask: is a reduction to LIS or suffix array possible?"
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 2 Follow-Ups:</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>"In Edit Distance, what if substitution is not allowed (only insert and delete)?"</td><td>dp[i][j] = min(dp[i-1][j]+1, dp[i][j-1]+1) on mismatch; diagonal branch only on match; this is equivalent to n + m - 2·LCS — the min-deletion problem</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>"What if in LCS, we want the ACTUAL sequence, not just the length?"</td><td>Backtrack the DP table from dp[m][n]: if s1[i-1]==s2[j-1], take the char and move diagonally; else move in the direction of the larger value; O(n+m) backtracking</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Stage 3 Follow-Ups:</strong></div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>"Count the number of DISTINCT LCS strings, not just the length."</td><td>Add count dimension: dp[i][j] = (length, count); on new max, replace count; on tie, add counts; apply modular arithmetic</td></tr>
