            <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════
                 TOPIC 34 — STATE MACHINE DP (MASTERY)
            ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp34">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">34</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">State Machine DP</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T1">Dynamic Programming</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Stock Problems · Cooldown · Fee · K Transactions · Sign-Tracking · Alternating · Bitmask · Matrix Exp</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">27 problems · 5 stages · 2-state, 3-state, k×2, bitmask, matrix exponentiation state machines</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> State Machine DP solves problems where a system moves through a finite, explicitly enumerable set of states as it processes elements one by one, and the optimal value depends not just on which element you are processing but on which state you are currently in. The core invariant is: dp[i][s] = optimal value after processing element i while being in state s, where transitions between states are governed by a fixed, known set of rules. This pattern appears in virtually every top-tier interview because: (1) the Stock Problems are the canonical teaching example — every interviewer knows them and escalates through exactly these stages; (2) the technique generalises to any system with modes (holding/not holding, sign-alternating, sign-tracking, cooldown timers); and (3) the hard variants require identifying what the "states" are in a disguised input — the single skill that separates candidates who solve Hard problems from those who struggle at Medium.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>State Machine DP is a finite automaton with memory.</strong> You are a robot walking along a sequence of elements. At each element, you are in exactly one of K states. Each state has a value. You can stay in your current state or transition to another state (paying a transition cost or gaining a transition reward). The DP fills one column of the state machine per element, left to right.<br><br>
                        <strong>Draw this literally:</strong>
                        <pre style="margin:.5rem 0">States:   HOLD    REST    COOL
Day 0:    [−∞]    [0]     [−∞]
Day 1:    [?] ←── [?] ←── [?]
Day 2:    ...</pre>
                        Every cell depends only on the previous column (previous day's states). This means O(K) space is always achievable with rolling variables.<br><br>
                        <strong>How this scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Stage 1:</strong> 2 states (hold / not-hold). One transition rule. Pure O(n) time, O(1) space.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 2:</strong> Same 2 states, ONE constraint changes: cooldown adds a forced intermediate state. 3 states now. Algorithm 95% identical.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 3:</strong> State gains a count dimension: dp[i][k] = at most k transactions. State machine runs k times or adds k as an explicit dimension.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 4:</strong> Problem doesn't say "stock" or "hold." The states are implicit — positive/negative sign, building type 0/1, same-position/moved. Recognition IS the hard part.<br>
                        • <strong>Stage 5:</strong> k is large, n is large. Matrix exponentiation collapses O(nk) to O(k² log n). Or the transaction count dimension is shown to be irrelevant above a threshold.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant &amp; Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> After processing day i, dp[i][s] holds the maximum profit achievable using the first i days while ending in state s. All transitions from dp[i-1][s'] to dp[i][s] are valid state machine edges.<br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (by induction on days processed):</strong><br>
                        • <strong>Base case (day 0):</strong> dp[0][REST] = 0 (own nothing, zero profit). dp[0][HOLD] = -prices[0] (bought on day 0). All other states: -∞ (unreachable). Correct by definition.<br>
                        • <strong>Inductive step:</strong> Assume dp[i-1][s'] is correct for all states s'. On day i:<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;– To be in HOLD on day i: either we were already holding (dp[i-1][HOLD]) or we just bought (dp[i-1][REST] - prices[i]). We take the max. ✓<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;– To be in REST on day i: either we were resting (dp[i-1][REST]) or we just sold (dp[i-1][HOLD] + prices[i]). ✓<br>
                        • <strong>State completeness:</strong> The state set is exhaustive — every possible situation the system can be in is represented by exactly one state. No valid configuration is omitted; no invalid transition is allowed.<br>
                        • <strong>Answer extraction:</strong> The answer is max(dp[n-1][s] for non-hold states s) — we never want to end holding an asset. □
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Variant</th><th>Stage</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>New Idea</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>2-state no-constraint (buy/sell once)</td><td>1</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>hold = max(hold, -price), rest = max(rest, hold+price); THE baseline state machine</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2-state unlimited transactions</td><td>1</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>hold = max(hold, rest-price) — can buy again after selling; difference from "once" is only the buy transition</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2-state with transaction fee</td><td>2</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Fee subtracted on sell; no new states, one term changes</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>3-state with cooldown</td><td>2</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>After selling, must spend one day in COOL state (cannot buy); adds one mandatory intermediate state</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2-state with at most 2 transactions</td><td>3</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Transaction counter k added as state dimension; 4 states: (hold/rest) × (0/1 transactions used)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2-state with at most k transactions</td><td>3</td><td>O(nk)</td><td>O(k)</td><td>k can be large; naïve O(nk) works when k ≤ n/2; identifies when unlimited is equivalent</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2-state with exactly k transactions</td><td>3</td><td>O(nk)</td><td>O(k)</td><td>"exactly k" vs "at most k" changes initialisation; -∞ for unreachable states</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Sign-tracking 2-state (positive product subarray)</td><td>4</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>States are product sign; "transaction" = encountering a negative number</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Alternating-sign state machine</td><td>4</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Forced alternation between states; both transitions run every step; no "skip" option</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Position-tracking state machine (random walk)</td><td>3</td><td>O(n·steps·pos)</td><td>O(steps·pos)</td><td>Position is a third state dimension; moves left/right; state = (step, position)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Building-type state machine (0/1 sequence)</td><td>4</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Selection constraint is "last chosen must be different type"; states encode last-chosen type</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Multi-mode scoring (visit positions + state)</td><td>4</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Position selection with type-based bonus; state = last-chosen element's type</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>State machine with matrix exponentiation</td><td>5</td><td>O(k² log n)</td><td>O(k²)</td><td>When n is huge and k states are small; matrix exponentiation collapses O(nk) to O(k² log n)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>State machine on circular sequence</td><td>3</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>Circular constraint: first and last states must be consistent; two separate DP runs</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>

