                    <div class="sec-title">🔧 Custom Problem 7 — At Most K Transactions with Cooldown</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Problem:</strong> Given an array prices of length n and integers k and cooldown, find the maximum profit from at most k buy-sell transactions where after each sell, you must wait exactly cooldown days before buying again.<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraints:</strong> 1 ≤ n ≤ 1000, 1 ≤ k ≤ 100, 1 ≤ cooldown ≤ 3<br><br>
                        <strong>Example:</strong> prices=[1,3,1,5], k=2, cooldown=1 → buy day 0 (cost 1), sell day 1 (profit +2), wait day 2, buy day 3 (cost 1), sell… → answer = 6<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 solution:</strong> State is dp[t][state] where t ∈ &#123;0..k&#125;, state ∈ &#123;HOLD, REST_0, REST_1, ..., REST_&#123;cooldown-1&#125;&#125;. When you sell, you enter REST_0, which transitions to REST_1, ..., REST_&#123;cooldown-1&#125;, which finally enables buy again. The number of states is k × (cooldown + 1). For k=100, cooldown=3: 400 states, each updated in O(1) → O(400n) total. This problem teaches: (1) cooldown = a CHAIN of intermediate REST states; (2) k-dimension and cooldown-dimension compose independently; (3) compositional state machine design is mechanical once each sub-machine is mastered.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 1: Stock DP State Machine</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 — Two variables (buy once):</strong><br>
                        hold = max profit achievable while holding a stock<br>
                        rest = max profit achievable while not holding a stock<br>
                        hold = max(hold, -prices[i]); rest = max(rest, hold + prices[i])<br>
                        Base: hold = -prices[0], rest = 0; Answer: rest<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up O(1) space — two rolling variables<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 — Two variables (unlimited transactions):</strong><br>
                        hold = max(hold, rest - prices[i]) ← can buy after any sell<br>
                        rest = max(rest, hold + prices[i])<br>
                        ONE difference from "buy once": hold now references rest (prior accumulated profit)<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — Three variables (cooldown):</strong><br>
                        hold, rest, cool (the day after selling)<br>
                        new_hold = max(hold, cool - prices[i]) ← buy only from COOL<br>
                        new_rest = max(rest, cool) ← skip during cooldown or after resting<br>
                        new_cool = hold + prices[i] ← sell today; tomorrow enters COOL<br>
                        Base: hold = -prices[0], rest = 0, cool = -∞<br>
                        Key: use new_ variables — all new states computed from old states simultaneously<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — k×2 table (at most k transactions):</strong><br>
                        dp[t][0] = max profit with t sells completed, NOT holding<br>
                        dp[t][1] = max profit with t sells completed, HOLDING<br>
                        dp[t][1] = max(dp[t][1], dp[t][0] - prices[i]) ← buy (doesn't increase t yet)<br>
                        dp[t][0] = max(dp[t][0], dp[t-1][1] + prices[i]) ← sell (increases t by 1)<br>
                        Base: dp[0][0] = 0, dp[t][1] = -∞ for t≥0, dp[t][0] = -∞ for t&gt;0<br>
                        Optimisation: If k ≥ n//2, answer = unlimited transactions solution (O(n))<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 2: Sign-Tracking / Alternating State Machine</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 — Positive Product Subarray:</strong><br>
                        pos = length of longest subarray ending here with positive product<br>
                        neg = length of longest subarray ending here with negative product<br>
                        When a[i] &gt; 0: pos = pos + 1; neg = neg + 1 if neg &gt; 0 else 0<br>
                        When a[i] &lt; 0: new_pos = neg + 1 if neg &gt; 0 else 0; new_neg = pos + 1<br>
                        When a[i] == 0: pos = neg = 0 (reset both)<br>
                        Answer: max(pos) across all days<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 — Maximum Alternating Subsequence Sum:</strong><br>
                        even = max sum ending at even-indexed position; odd = max sum ending at odd-indexed position<br>
                        new_even = max(even, odd + a[i]); new_odd = max(odd, even - a[i])<br>
                        Base: even = 0, odd = 0; Answer: even<br>
                        Key: BOTH transitions always run each step; no conditional on direction<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 3: Position-Tracking State Machine</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Number of Ways to Stay in Same Place:</strong><br>
                        dp[step][pos] = number of ways to be at position pos after step steps<br>
                        dp[step+1][pos] += dp[step][pos] (stay)<br>
                        dp[step+1][pos+1] += dp[step][pos] (move right, if pos+1 &lt; arrLen)<br>
                        dp[step+1][pos-1] += dp[step][pos] (move left, if pos-1 ≥ 0)<br>
                        Base: dp[0][0] = 1; Answer: dp[steps][0]<br>
                        Optimisation: Position never exceeds min(arrLen-1, steps//2) — critical bound<br><br>
                        <strong>Group 4: Sequence-Type State Machine</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 — Number of Ways to Select Buildings:</strong><br>
                        Want to count subsequences that are "010" or "101"<br>
                        For "010": zeros = count of single 0s; ones_after_zero = (0,1) pairs; twos = (0,1,0) triples<br>
                        At each building b: if b==0: zeros+=1; twos+=ones_after_zero<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;if b==1: ones+=1; ones_after_zero+=zeros<br>
                        Run two separate DPs for "010" and "101"; sum the answers<br>
                        Preferred: Single pass with 6 counters — three per pattern; O(1) space
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • "at most k transactions / operations / flips" → Stage 3 k-dimension state machine — add k as second state dimension<br>
                        • "cooldown of d days after each [sell/action]" → Stage 2 — add d intermediate REST states between transitions<br>
                        • "alternating [sign/type/direction]" → Stage 4 — 2-state forced alternation machine; both transitions run every step<br>
                        • "transaction fee on each [buy/sell]" → Stage 2 — one constant term in one transition; no new states<br>
                        • "maximum score / profit / sum by selecting elements with [parity/type] constraint" → Stage 4 — states = type of last selected element<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • Input is a 1D sequence; output is a scalar (max profit/score/sum); answer depends on "mode" (holding/not, bought/not, type of last action) → State machine DP; K states; O(nK)<br>
                        • Problem has explicit "cooldown" or "wait N periods" between actions → State chain for the cooldown; K = actions + cooldown states<br>
                        • Sequence must alternate between two types (0/1, +/-) with value maximisation → 2-state alternating machine; both transitions fire every step<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • k ≤ 100 or k ≤ n in stock-type problems → O(nk) is feasible; add k as state dimension<br>
                        • n ≤ 500 and state space involves pairs → O(n·states) is fine; full 2D table<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        • "no two adjacent elements selected" → NOT state machine DP → Linear DP dp[i] = max(dp[i-1], dp[i-2]+a[i]); state machine overcomplicated<br>
                        • "shortest path between two positions" → NOT state machine DP → BFS/Dijkstra; states don't capture "path cost" without O(n) blowup<br>
                        • "maximum product subarray" → NOT stock state machine → Two-variable Kadane tracking running max and min; categorically different recurrence
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box" style="font-family:monospace;white-space:pre-wrap">Q1: Is the problem a 1D sequence where the optimal decision at
    each element depends on a FINITE "mode" you are currently in?
  → NO:  Not state machine DP. Check grid DP, interval DP, or greedy.
  → YES: Continue.

Q2: Can you enumerate ALL possible modes (states)?
  → YES: List them explicitly. Count = K.
         K = 2 → 2-state machine. K = 3 → add cooldown or sign.
         K = 2k → k transaction levels.
         K = 2^n → bitmask state machine (n ≤ 20).
  → NO:  State space continuous/too large → LIS, interval DP, or greedy.

Q3: Are transactions bounded (at most k)?
  → YES: Add k as second dimension. dp[k][state]. O(nK).
         k ≥ n//2? → Unlimited equivalent; drop k dimension.
  → NO:  1D state machine. O(n·K).

Q4: Is there a cooldown of d days between actions?
  → YES: Add d intermediate states between "sell" and "buy-enabled."
         Chain: SELL → COOL_1 → ... → COOL_d → CAN_BUY. K increases by d.
  → NO:  Continue.

Q5: Is the problem DISGUISED (no explicit "buy/sell/hold")?
  → Check: alternating types → 2-state alternation.
  → Check: sign tracking → POS/NEG/ZERO states.
  → Check: last-selected-type constraint → states = types.
  → Check: counting length-k subsequences of a pattern → k-state counter.
  → If disguised: name states explicitly, draw transition diagram,
    THEN write the recurrence.

Q6: Is n or K too large?
  → n ≤ 10^5, K ≤ 100: Standard O(nK) fine.
  → n ≤ 10^18, K ≤ 20: Matrix exponentiation. O(K² log n).
  → K ≤ 20, states are bitmasks: Bitmask DP. O(2^K · n).

Stage identification:
  Q2 (K=2, no constraints) → Stage 1. O(n).
  Q4 (cooldown) or fee → Stage 2. O(n).
  Q3 (k transactions) → Stage 3. O(nk).
  Q5 (disguised) → Stage 4. O(n·K) after identification.
  Q6 (matrix exp) → Stage 5. O(K² log n).</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] States are not independent:</strong> State machine DP requires that each state's value is computed independently from other states at the same step using only the previous step's values. If state A can only have a certain value IF state B has a specific value (not just "≤ best B"), the simple max-over-predecessors recurrence is insufficient. Use min-cost-flow or constraint programming.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Cooldown uses wrong transition source:</strong> With cooldown, hold must source from the COOLDOWN state, NOT from the generic REST state. Sourcing from REST allows buying on the day after selling — violating the cooldown. This is a Stage 2 bug that produces silently inflated profits.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Stale-read in k-transaction DP:</strong> When iterating over k and days in a nested loop, if dp[t][1] is updated and then immediately used to update dp[t][0] in the same day's loop iteration, the sell transition uses a SAME-DAY buy — meaning you buy and sell on the same day using the same transaction slot. Fix: process sells AFTER all buys, or use temporary variables.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Treating "last selected type" problems as position DP:</strong> When the constraint is on the TYPE of the last selected element (not its position), position-indexed DP dp[i] doesn't capture enough state. Need dp[type] = best score ending with that type. Missing the state dimension gives wrong greedy-like answers.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Matrix exponentiation: wrong state vector initialisation:</strong> The initial state vector must precisely encode the base case of the state machine. Off-by-one in which step's state vector is used (step 0 vs step 1) shifts all subsequent states and gives wrong answers for large n.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 — Two-State Stock (Buy Once): Correctness of Rolling Variables</strong><br>
                        Claim: At each day i, hold = max(-prices[j] for j ≤ i) and rest = max(0, max(-prices[j] + prices[k]) for j &lt; k ≤ i).<br>
                        hold invariant: hold = max(hold_prev, -prices[i]). By induction, hold_prev = max(-prices[j] for j &lt; i). After update: hold = max(-prices[j] for j ≤ i). ✓<br>
                        rest invariant: rest = max(rest_prev, hold_prev + prices[i]). hold_prev + prices[i] = max one-transaction profit ending at day i. Taking max with rest_prev gives the global best profit up to day i. ✓<br>
                        Strict buy-before-sell: hold_prev reflects purchases strictly before day i, so hold_prev + prices[i] represents selling on day i after a past purchase. ✓ □<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — Cooldown State Machine: Correctness of Three-State Separation</strong><br>
                        Claim: The three-state machine (HOLD, REST, COOL) correctly models the cooldown constraint.<br>
                        State completeness: Any configuration is exactly one of: holding stock (HOLD), not holding and can buy (REST), not holding and cannot buy yet — day immediately after a sell (COOL). These three are exhaustive and mutually exclusive. ✓<br>
                        COOL → REST transition: After one day in COOL, you move to REST (can buy again). The transition rest = max(rest, cool) on the NEXT day correctly delays buy eligibility by one day. ✓<br>
                        No-stale-read guarantee: Using temporary new_hold, new_rest, new_cool ensures all three new states use the previous day's configuration — not a partially-updated current day. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — K-Transaction DP: Induction on Transactions</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[t][0] = max profit using at most t complete transactions, not holding; dp[t][1] = max profit using t-1 complete sells and currently holding.<br>
                        Base: t=0: dp[0][0] = 0 (no transactions, no stock). dp[0][1] = -∞ (holding without any context). ✓<br>
                        Induction on t: dp[t][0] = max(dp[t][0], dp[t-1][1] + prices[i]). This correctly sources from t-1 completed transactions. ✓<br>
                        Why dp[t-1] for the sell? Holding with t-1 completed sells means the t-th transaction is open; selling it completes the t-th transaction. □
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Bug 1 — Stale-read in cooldown: updating hold before cool is read</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: hold updated first; cool references NEW hold (wrong)
hold = max(hold, cool - prices[i])   # new hold computed
cool = hold + prices[i]              # BUG: uses new hold
# FIX: compute all new states from old values simultaneously
new_hold = max(hold, cool - prices[i])
new_cool = hold + prices[i]          # old hold
hold, cool = new_hold, new_cool</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 2 — Buy-once stock: using rest - prices[i] instead of -prices[i]</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: allows buying multiple times (uses accumulated rest profit)
hold = max(hold, rest - prices[i])  # BUG for buy-once
# FIX for buy ONCE:
hold = max(hold, -prices[i])        # can only spend cash, not prior profit</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 3 — Fee: applying fee on BOTH buy and sell</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: fee deducted twice per transaction
hold = max(hold, rest - prices[i] - fee)  # BUG: fee on buy
rest = max(rest, hold + prices[i] - fee)  # AND on sell = double fee
# FIX: apply fee once — on SELL only
hold = max(hold, rest - prices[i])
rest = max(rest, hold + prices[i] - fee)</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 4 — K-transaction: stale-read sell uses same-day buy</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: sell reads dp[k][1] that was just updated this same day
for k in range(1, K+1):
    dp[k][1] = max(dp[k][1], dp[k][0] - prices[i])   # buy
    dp[k][0] = max(dp[k][0], dp[k][1] + prices[i])   # BUG: same-day buy
# FIX: sell sources from PREVIOUS transaction's buy
    dp[k][0] = max(dp[k][0], dp[k-1][1] + prices[i])  # sell increases count
    dp[k][1] = max(dp[k][1], dp[k][0] - prices[i])    # buy at count k</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 5 — At most k: not handling k ≥ n//2 edge case</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: for k = n = 10^5, allocating dp[k][2] → MLE or TLE
dp = [[0, -float('inf')] for _ in range(k+1)]  # BUG: k up to 10^5
# FIX: reduce to unlimited when k is large
if k >= len(prices) // 2:
    return solve_unlimited(prices)</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 6 — Alternating subsequence: updating even and odd in wrong order</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: even updated first; odd uses NEW even (wrong)
even = max(even, odd + a[i])   # new even
odd = max(odd, even - a[i])    # BUG: uses new even
# FIX: use temp variables
new_even = max(even, odd + a[i])
new_odd = max(odd, even - a[i])   # old even
even, odd = new_even, new_odd</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 7 — Positive product: not resetting BOTH pos and neg on zero</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: only resetting pos on zero; neg carries stale state
if a[i] == 0:
    pos = 0   # BUG: neg not reset
# FIX:
    pos, neg = 0, 0  # zero resets ALL product-length tracking</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 8 — Number of ways to select buildings: missing "101" pattern</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: only counts "010" patterns, missing "101"
ans = count_pattern(buildings, pattern="010")  # BUG
# FIX:
ans = count_pattern(buildings, "010") + count_pattern(buildings, "101")</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 9 — Matrix exponentiation: off-by-one in initial state vector</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: applying transition matrix n times instead of n-1
result = matrix_pow(transition, n) @ initial_vector  # BUG: one extra step
# FIX: initial_vector is state AFTER day 0; apply n-1 more transitions
result = matrix_pow(transition, n-1) @ initial_vector</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 10 — Random walk DP: not clamping position to min(arrLen, steps//2)</strong>
                        <pre><code># BUG: iterating pos up to arrLen → huge state space for large arrLen
for pos in range(arrLen):   # BUG for arrLen=10^6
    ...
# FIX: position can never exceed steps//2 moves from start
max_pos = min(arrLen - 1, steps // 2)
for pos in range(max_pos + 1):
    ...</code></pre>
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Forgetting that "buy once" and "unlimited" differ by one term in one transition:</strong> For buy-once, rest before the first buy is always 0, so rest - prices[i] = -prices[i] — equivalent ONLY in that sense. But adding rest's accumulated profit conceptually allows a second "free buy." Correct model: "Buy-once: hold = max(hold, -prices[i]). Unlimited: hold = max(hold, rest - prices[i]). The ONLY difference is whether prior profit is reinvested."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Cooldown: sourcing the buy transition from REST instead of COOL:</strong> If you buy from REST, you allow buying the day after selling — violating the cooldown. The buy must source from COOL. Correct model: "Cooldown creates a directed chain: HOLD → (sell) → COOL → (next day) → REST → (buy) → HOLD. The buy arrow comes from REST, but REST is only reachable from COOL."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] K-transaction: updating buy and sell in same loop iteration without temporary variables:</strong> The sell transition dp[t][0] = dp[t-1][1] + prices[i] correctly uses t-1 transaction buy. But if buy dp[t][1] = dp[t][0] - prices[i] runs first and updates dp[t][0], then the sell reads a same-day value. Correct model: "Compute ALL new state values into temporary variables first. Write ALL new values simultaneously."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Missing the state in disguised problems:</strong> When a problem says "select elements with alternating types" or "build a sequence with no two consecutive same elements," candidates jump to greedy or brute-force. The state IS the type of the last selected element. Correct model: "For any problem with 'the last selected element must satisfy property P,' make P the state. Draw K states. Fill the state machine."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Not detecting the k ≥ n//2 threshold for unlimited equivalence:</strong> When k ≥ n//2, you can never exhaust k transactions (a transaction requires at least 2 days). Allocating O(nk) DP table for k=10^9 is MLE. Correct model: "Before writing the k-transaction DP, check: if k ≥ len(prices)//2, return the unlimited-transactions answer. This is not an optimisation — it's a correctness requirement for large k."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Treating alternating subsequence as a greedy problem:</strong> The alternating subsequence sum looks like it could be solved greedily. In fact, the optimal can skip profitable segments to enable future gains. Correct model: "Greedy works for LONGEST alternating (count direction changes), but for MAXIMUM SUM alternating, you must track even and odd states explicitly."<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Fee applied twice:</strong> Some candidates apply fee on both the buy (rest - prices[i] - fee) and the sell (hold + prices[i] - fee). This charges double per transaction. Correct model: "One transaction = one buy + one sell = one fee. Apply fee on exactly ONE of the two transitions (convention: on sell). Never on both."
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Stage</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>2</td><td>"What if the transaction fee varies per transaction (fee[t] for t-th transaction)?"</td><td>Add t as state dimension; dp[t][hold]; on sell: dp[t][0] = dp[t-1][1] + price - fee[t]; O(nk)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>2</td><td>"What if you can hold at most 2 stocks simultaneously?"</td><td>Add "2 stocks held" state; 3 states per transaction level: REST, HOLD_1, HOLD_2; transitions include buying a 2nd stock and selling either</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>3</td><td>"How do you recover the actual sequence of buy/sell days, not just the profit?"</td><td>Parent-pointer array: at each state transition, record which previous state was chosen; backtrack from final optimal state</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>3</td><td>"What if cooldown is k days (not just 1)?"</td><td>k intermediate COOL states chained: SELL → COOL_1 → ... → COOL_k → REST; total states = original + k; O(n·(states+k))</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>4</td><td>"Design a state machine for: select elements to maximise sum where no two selected elements can both be divisible by 3."</td><td>States: LAST_DIV3, LAST_NOT_DIV3; transitions: from LAST_DIV3, can only add NOT_DIV3 elements; from LAST_NOT_DIV3, can add either</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>4</td><td>"Stock problem but you can short-sell (profit when price falls). What changes?"</td><td>Add SHORT state alongside LONG; 3 states: REST, LONG (bought expecting rise), SHORT (sold expecting fall); buy-back from SHORT adds profit when price fell</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>5</td><td>"n = 10^18 days, prices repeat with period p = 10. How do you solve at-most-k-transactions?"</td><td>Matrix exponentiation: build p×p state machine for one cycle; matrix-exponentiate to get n//p full cycles; handle remainder separately; O(K² log n)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>5</td><td>"Prove that for k ≥ n//2, the k-transaction solution equals the unlimited solution."</td><td>A transaction requires buying then selling = at least 2 days. Maximum possible non-overlapping transactions in n days = n//2. So k ≥ n//2 means the k-cap is never reached; unlimited solution achievable within k transactions.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>Beyond</td><td>"Distribute the stock DP across 10 machines, each holding n/10 days. How?"</td><td>Segment tree of state machines: each machine holds a 2K×2K transition matrix for its segment; combine via matrix multiplication; O(K² log n) with O(K²) communication per merge</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>Beyond</td><td>"Adversary sets prices after seeing your strategy. What's the optimal guarantee?"</td><td>Minimax stock trading: adversary maximises regret; optimal strategy = hold nothing (profit = 0 guaranteed); any holding exposes to adversarial price drop to 0; competitive ratio = 1 for any deterministic strategy</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>

                    <div class="sec-title">3-Phase Mastery Plan</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Phase 1 — Solve (strictly by Stage across all sub-variants):</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 — core 2-state machine:</strong><br>
                        S.No 1 (121) → S.No 2 (122). Write both with rolling variables only. Draw the 2-node state diagram before coding. Verify: can you reconstruct the recurrence from the state diagram alone?<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — one constraint mutation at a time:</strong><br>
                        S.No 3 (714 fee) → S.No 4 (309 cooldown). For each: (1) redraw the state diagram adding the new state/edge, (2) write the recurrence, (3) code with temporary variables.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — state dimension expansion:</strong><br>
                        S.No 5 (123, k=2) → S.No 6 (188, k=any) → S.No 9 (1911 alternating) → S.No 10 (1567 sign) → S.No 11 (1186 deletion) → S.No 18 (1269 random walk). For each: draw the FULL state diagram with all K nodes and all directed edges.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 — disguised state machines:</strong><br>
                        S.No 12 (Wiggle) → S.No 13 (2222 Buildings) → S.No 14 (1537 Get Score) → S.No 19 (2786 Visit Positions). For each: name the states and transitions BEFORE reading any editorial.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5 — matrix exponentiation:</strong><br>
                        S.No 22 (AtCoder Sushi) → S.No 23 (CF 833B). Implement matrix exponentiation for a 3-state machine; verify by checking against O(nk) DP for small n.<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 2 — Drill (speed and pattern recognition):</strong><br>
                        • Stage 1/2: Full stock family (S.No 1–4) under 8 minutes each<br>
                        • Stage 3: K-transaction variants under 20 minutes<br>
                        • Stage 4: Disguised problems — given title only, name the states in 60 seconds before reading<br>
                        • State diagram drill: For any state machine problem, draw the complete transition diagram on paper first. If you can't draw it in 2 minutes, you don't know the states yet.<br>
                        • Rolling-variable drill: Implement every 2-state solution with exactly 2 Python variables. Implement every 3-state solution with 3 variables. Use temporary variables to prevent stale reads.<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 3 — Validate (unseen sources per Stage):</strong><br>
                        • Stage 1/2: LeetCode contest problems tagged "dynamic programming" from the last 6 months<br>
                        • Stage 3: AtCoder EDPC problems H–L (knapsack/DP variants with state machine structure)<br>
                        • Stage 4: Codeforces Div 2 D problems tagged "dp" with no explicit "buy/sell" — 3 problems<br>
                        • Stage 5: USACO Platinum problems involving state machine + matrix exponentiation
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Graduation Test</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        These three problems are NOT in the table above. Solving all three cold (no hints, no editorial, 45 min each) certifies full mastery.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 1 — LC 1840: Maximum Building Height (modified: cooldown between restricted floors)</strong> (Stage 3 + Stage 4)<br>
                        <em>Primary stage: Stage 4.</em> Combination: Stage 4 (recognise the height propagation as a state machine with RESTRICTED and FREE states for each floor, where transitions encode height constraints) + Stage 3 (the k-restriction state = how many restrictions have been applied; sorting restrictions by floor creates a processable sequence). Why it certifies mastery: The input is restrictions on floor heights — no stock, no explicit states. The reduction to a "state machine on sorted restrictions" with height-as-state-value requires Stage 4 recognition. Handling the variable transition cost between restrictions (geometric arithmetic on height differences) requires Stage 3 multi-dimensional thinking.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 2 — AtCoder DP Contest – Sushi (Expected Value State Machine)</strong> (Stage 3 + Stage 4 + Stage 5)<br>
                        <em>Primary stage: Stage 4.</em> Combination: Stage 4 (states are counts of 1/2/3-piece dishes; not a standard hold/rest machine) + Stage 3 (3-dimensional state (a,b,c) where a+b+c ≤ n; each transition depends on uniform random selection) + Stage 5 (memoisation makes the O(n³) state space tractable; without it, exponential recursion). Why it certifies mastery: Expected-value state machines are a fundamental extension — the "state" is still (a,b,c) but the transition VALUE is probabilistic. Solving cold proves the candidate can apply state machine DP to non-deterministic processes.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 3 — CF 1600F: Playground (Colour-State Machine on Segments)</strong> (Stage 4 + Stage 5)<br>
                        <em>Primary stage: Stage 4.</em> Combination: Stage 4 (input is coloured segments; states are the current colour group and its accumulated value — not explicit) + Stage 5 (naïve O(n²) per state; segment tree with lazy propagation reduces to O(n log n); the state machine runs on top of the segment tree). Why it certifies mastery: The states must be derived from the segment colouring structure (Stage 4). The merge of adjacent same-colour segments requires a data structure integration (Stage 5). Both layers must be identified and implemented correctly within 45 minutes on an unseen Codeforces Div 1 problem.
                    </div>
                </div>
