                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why It Matters:</strong> Interval DP solves problems where the answer for a sequence s[i..j] is built from the answers for all strict sub-intervals s[i..k] and s[k+1..j] (or s[i..k-1] and s[k..j]), with an additional cost or value contributed by the split point k or the boundary elements. The core invariant is: <strong>dp[i][j] = optimal value for the sub-problem on interval [i,j], computed after all dp[i'][j'] with j'-i' &lt; j-i</strong> — that is, after all strictly shorter intervals are solved. This mandatory fill-order by increasing length is what distinguishes interval DP from every other 2D DP pattern. It appears relentlessly in top-tier interviews and ICPC/IOI competitions because: (1) the state definition is always dp[i][j] on a contiguous range — learnable and systematic; (2) the split-point loop <code>for k in range(i, j)</code> is the universal recurrence skeleton; (3) disguised variants (balloon popping, matrix chain, stone merging, polygon triangulation) look wildly different on the surface but reduce to the same O(n³) structure; and (4) the hard problems require identifying the CORRECT split-point semantics, which is the single skill that separates good candidates from great ones.</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box">Interval DP is <strong>recursive demolition</strong>. You have a row of objects. To solve a problem on range [i,j], you decide LAST which object at position k is the "last one standing" (the last to be processed, removed, or merged). Everything to its left ([i,k-1]) and everything to its right ([k+1,j]) must be fully resolved first. The cost of the current decision depends on what remains at the boundaries when k is processed last.<br><br>This <strong>"last one standing" framing</strong> is the universal template. The key question for every new interval DP problem is: <em>"What object, when processed last, makes its cost easy to compute?"</em><br><br><strong>How this scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br><strong>Stage 1:</strong> dp[i][j] = cost to solve [i,j] by splitting at k; uniform cost per split; fill by length j-i ascending.<br><strong>Stage 2:</strong> Same structure, ONE constraint changes: circular boundary (wrap-around), penalty depends on boundary elements (not just split), or the answer is a COUNT not a cost.<br><strong>Stage 3:</strong> State gains a dimension: dp[i][j][k] where k tracks a count, a color/group, or a number of remaining merges. The split recurrence is identical but the third dimension gates transitions.<br><strong>Stage 4:</strong> Problem looks nothing like interval DP. The "interval" must be identified: balloons burst in an order (frame as "last to burst"), polygon diagonals (triangles = splits), matrix chain (parenthesisation = split). The reduction IS the insight.<br><strong>Stage 5:</strong> The O(n³) solution TLEs. Apply the Knuth-Yao optimisation: if the split point opt[i][j] is monotone, the total work reduces from O(n³) to O(n²).</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant / Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Invariant:</strong> dp[i][j] is correct for all intervals of length L = j-i+1, computed before any interval of length L+1 is computed.<br><br><strong>Proof sketch (strong induction on interval length L):</strong><br><strong>Base case (L=1):</strong> dp[i][i] is trivially correct — a single element has no split point; its value is defined directly (zero cost, or the element itself). ✓<br><strong>Base case (L=2):</strong> dp[i][i+1] has exactly one split point k=i; computed directly from the two length-1 sub-problems, which are already correct. ✓<br><strong>Inductive step:</strong> Assume dp[i'][j'] is correct for all j'-i' &lt; L. For interval [i,j] with length L+1, the recurrence dp[i][j] = min/max over k in [i,j-1] of (dp[i][k] + dp[k+1][j] + cost(i,k,j)) references only sub-intervals of length ≤ L. By the inductive hypothesis, all of these are correct. Therefore dp[i][j] is correct. ✓<br><strong>Fill order guarantee:</strong> Filling in increasing order of L = j-i+1 (outer loop) ensures that when computing dp[i][j], all dp[i][k] and dp[k+1][j] for k ∈ [i,j-1] have already been computed (they are shorter intervals). □<br><br><strong>Why "last one standing" works for non-standard problems (e.g., Burst Balloons):</strong> When the cost of removing element k depends on its neighbours, we need those neighbours to still be present when k is removed. Framing k as "the LAST removed" guarantees its neighbours a[i-1] and a[j+1] are still present (they are outside the interval being solved). This converts a variable-cost dependent problem into a well-defined subproblem. □</div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Sub-Variant</th><th>Stage</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>New Idea</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Matrix Chain Multiplication / Optimal Parenthesisation</td><td>Stage 1</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>THE baseline — dp[i][j] = min over k of dp[i][k] + dp[k+1][j] + cost(i,k,j); split-point k divides [i,j] into two independent sub-chains; 2D table + split-point loop</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Palindrome interval DP (is/length/count)</td><td>Stage 1</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>dp[i][j] depends on dp[i+1][j-1] (SHRINK from both ends), not a split-point; teaches the SHRINK variant of interval DP; fill by increasing length</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Optimal BST</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>O(n³) → O(n²)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Cost of split = sum(freq[i..j]) (all elements in interval contribute); prefix sums needed; Knuth-Yao applicable; dp[i][j] = min over k of dp[i][k-1] + dp[k+1][j] + pre[j+1]-pre[i]</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Burst Balloons</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Cost of removing k DEPENDS ON ITS CURRENT NEIGHBOURS — must frame k as LAST removed so boundaries are predictable; add sentinel 1s; the most important non-obvious transformation in interval DP</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Minimum Score Triangulation of a Polygon</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Polygon → interval DP by fixing one vertex; split = third vertex of a triangle whose base is always [i,j]; dp[i][j] = min over k of dp[i][k]+dp[k][j]+V[i]*V[k]*V[j]; sub-problems SHARE endpoints</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Strange Printer</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>If s[i]==s[k], the turn for s[i] can extend to cover s[k] at no extra cost; dp[i][j] = min(dp[i+1][k]+dp[k+1][j]) when s[i]==s[k]; "last interval printed" insight</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Minimum Cost to Merge Stones</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Not all intervals are mergeable — feasibility check: (j-i) % (K-1) == 0; only add final merge cost when feasible; gated split recurrence</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Minimum Cost to Cut a Stick</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Sort cuts + add endpoints 0 and n as boundaries; dp[i][j] = min over k of dp[i][k]+dp[k][j]+(cuts[j]-cuts[i]); cost = current segment length; order of cuts is the decision</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Remove Boxes</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>O(n⁴)</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>Third dimension k = count of EXTRA identical boxes attached at boundary; "teleport" non-adjacent equal boxes; dp[i][j][k] = max points for boxes[i..j] with k extra equal to boxes[i] on left</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Allocate Mailboxes</td><td>Stages 3+4</td><td>O(n²k)</td><td>O(nk)</td><td>2D DP over (houses, clusters); cost[i][j] = min distance for one mailbox over houses[i..j] = sum of distances to median; prefix sums + median precomputation needed</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Guess Number Higher or Lower II</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Minimax recurrence — dp[i][j] = min over k of (k + max(dp[i][k-1], dp[k+1][j])); adversarial max inside optimal min; teaches minimax interval DP</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Zuma Game / Strange Printer variants</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Consecutive matching collapses sub-problems differently from Strange Printer; segment-elimination structure; contiguous groups must match</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Circular interval DP</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Fix one element to break the circle; run two separate passes (element included / excluded); combine results; prevents wrap-around inconsistency</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Maximum Score from Performing Multiplication Operations</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>O(n·m²)</td><td>O(m²)</td><td>Two-pointer boundary: take from LEFT or RIGHT at each step; state = (ops_done, left_count); right_count = ops-left; fill by diagonal ops = i+j; outside-in construction</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Knuth-Yao Optimisation</td><td>Stage 5</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>If optimal split opt[i][j] is monotone (opt[i][j-1] ≤ opt[i][j] ≤ opt[i+1][j]), reduce O(n³) to O(n²) amortised; requires proof of the quadrangle inequality for the cost function</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Interval DP on trees (tree DP as interval DP)</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Euler tour of tree converts tree sub-problems to linear intervals; interval DP on the tour = tree DP; tree sub-problems correspond exactly to contiguous tour ranges</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Minimum cost to partition string with dictionary</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>String partitioning with word-cost lookup; combines interval DP with trie for O(n) lookup per endpoint; dp[i][j] = min cost to partition s[i..j]</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Expected-value interval DP (probabilistic)</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Recurrence uses expected value (weighted average over split points with uniform probability); teaches probabilistic transitions in interval DP</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Complexity Staircase</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Sub-Variant</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>What Changed from Previous</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Palindrome check (interval)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Baseline: shrink from ends, no split-point loop; dp[i][j] = (s[i]==s[j]) and dp[i+1][j-1]</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Matrix chain / Merge intervals</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Split-point loop added; cost per merge; prefix sum for interval cost</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Optimal BST</td><td>O(n³) → O(n²)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Prefix sum for cost; Knuth-Yao optimisation applicable; root k is not a split midpoint</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Burst Balloons</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>"Last to burst" transformation; sentinel boundaries 1,1 added; sub-problem boundaries are EXCLUSIVE</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Strange Printer</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Merge-on-match optimisation in split loop; base case changes from split to single-character</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Minimum Cost Merge Stones</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Feasibility constraint (j-i) % (K-1) == 0 gating final merge; infeasible intervals skip the cost addition</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Remove Boxes</td><td>O(n⁴)</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>Third dimension for attached-count; O(n) inner scan per cell; top-down memoisation preferred</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Allocate Mailboxes</td><td>O(n²k)</td><td>O(nk)</td><td>Second dimension = number of mailbox clusters; median cost precomputation; prefix sums for O(1) cost lookup</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Knuth-Yao Optimal BST</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>Monotone opt property collapses O(n) inner loop to O(1) amortised; requires quadrangle inequality verification</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>
