            <div class="topic-card" id="tp36">
            <div class="topic-header">
                <div class="topic-num">36</div>
                <div>
                    <div class="topic-title">Partition DP</div>
                    <div class="topic-meta">
                        <span class="tier-badge tier-T5">T5</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">Dynamic Programming</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">1D Partition DP</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">2D Partition DP</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">3D Partition DP</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">Convex Hull Trick</span>
                        <span class="topic-type">Divide &amp; Conquer DP</span>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="sec-title">Why This Topic Matters</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        Partition DP solves problems where a 1D sequence must be cut into contiguous segments, and the optimal answer is built by deciding WHERE to place each cut. The core invariant is: <strong>dp[i] = optimal value for the prefix a[0..i-1]</strong>, computed by scanning all possible last segments a[j..i-1] and taking the best over all valid cut points j. This pattern is distinct from Interval DP (which optimises the ORDER of operations) and from Knapsack (which selects non-contiguous items) — Partition DP always produces a sequential, non-overlapping, exhaustive division of the array. It dominates top-tier interviews because: (1) the recurrence <code>dp[i] = min/max over j &lt; i of (dp[j] + cost(j, i))</code> is a 3-line template that solves a vast class of problems; (2) the cost function <code>cost(j, i)</code> is what varies — sometimes a sum, sometimes a max, sometimes a string match, sometimes a painting cost — and recognising which is the only skill needed; and (3) the Stage 5 optimisation (Divide &amp; Conquer DP or Convex Hull Trick) converts O(n²) to O(n log n) and is a ICPC/IOI-essential technique.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        Partition DP is a <strong>cutting problem</strong>. You have a ribbon of length n. You must cut it into segments. Each segment [j..i-1] has a cost or score. You want to minimise the total cost (or maximise the total score) over all ways to cut. <code>dp[i]</code> = best total cost when you've made all cuts within the first i elements. For each i, you try every possible "last cut position" j and ask: <em>"What if the last segment is [j..i-1]?"</em><br><br>
                        The universal recurrence:<br>
                        <code>dp[i] = min over 0 ≤ j &lt; i of (dp[j] + cost(j, i))</code><br><br>
                        Everything in Partition DP is a variation of this formula. The ONLY thing that changes across problems is <code>cost(j, i)</code>.<br><br>
                        <strong>How this scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1:</strong> cost(j,i) is trivial (sum of elements in segment, fixed penalty per cut, or dictionary word match). O(n²) or O(n·m) where m = dictionary size.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 2:</strong> Same structure; ONE constraint changes — bounded number of cuts k (adds a second dimension), or the cost function requires a running max instead of a sum.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 3:</strong> State expands: dp[i][k] = optimal value for first i elements using exactly k segments. The recurrence iterates over j AND k simultaneously.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 4:</strong> Problem doesn't say "partition." The "sequence" must be identified: a bookcase where each shelf is a segment, a job schedule where each day-range is a segment, paint costs where colour groups are segments.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 5:</strong> O(n²) is too slow. The cost function is linear in j → apply Convex Hull Trick (O(n log n)). Or the optimal cut point j* for dp[i] is monotone in i → apply Divide &amp; Conquer DP (O(n log n)).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant / Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant:</strong> dp[i] = optimal value achievable for a partition of the prefix a[0..i-1] into any number of valid contiguous segments.<br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (strong induction on i):</strong><br>
                        <strong>Base case:</strong> dp[0] = 0 — empty prefix costs nothing; zero segments. ✓<br>
                        <strong>Inductive step:</strong> Assume dp[j] is correct for all j &lt; i. For prefix a[0..i-1], consider any optimal partition. There exists a last segment a[j..i-1] for some j ∈ [0,i). The rest of the partition covers a[0..j-1], contributing dp[j] (optimal by hypothesis). The last segment contributes cost(j,i). Total = dp[j] + cost(j,i).<br>
                        <strong>Minimality:</strong> The optimal last-segment choice minimises over all valid j: dp[i] = min(dp[j] + cost(j,i)). Since we try ALL j, the optimal j is included. ✓<br>
                        <strong>Correctness of dp[j]:</strong> Since dp[j] was computed correctly before dp[i] (j &lt; i, left-to-right fill), the induction holds. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Why this works for maximisation too:</strong> Replace min with max. The exchange argument is identical — any optimal partition has a "last segment"; fixing it and optimising the prefix is the same decomposition.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Sub-Variant</th><th>Stage</th><th>Complexity</th><th>Key Data Structure</th><th>New Idea</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>Word Break (feasibility)</td><td>1</td><td>O(n·m)</td><td>boolean dp array + hash set dictionary</td><td>dp[i] = boolean (can s[0..i-1] be partitioned into dictionary words?); cost(j,i) = is s[j..i-1] a word; trivial cost function</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>Word Break II (all solutions)</td><td>2</td><td>O(2ⁿ) worst case</td><td>backtracking seeded by dp feasibility table</td><td>Not just feasibility — enumerate ALL valid partitions; use dp table to prune infeasible cuts before backtracking</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>Palindrome Partitioning II (min cuts)</td><td>2</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>boolean palindrome table + 1D cut dp</td><td>cost(j,i) = 1 if s[j..i-1] is palindrome else ∞; two-phase: precompute palindrome table, then 1D partition DP</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>Partition Array for Maximum Sum</td><td>1</td><td>O(n·k)</td><td>1D dp with running max during j-scan</td><td>Score = segment_length × segment_max; running max tracked as j decreases; window bounded by k</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>Filling Bookcase Shelves</td><td>4</td><td>O(n·W)</td><td>1D dp with width accumulator + running max</td><td>Stage 4 disguise — books on shelves; "segment" = one shelf; cost = shelf height (max height in segment); width constraint gates valid j</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>Largest Sum of Averages</td><td>3</td><td>O(n²k)</td><td>2D dp[i][k] + prefix sums</td><td>Adds k as second dimension; dp[i][k] = max over j of dp[j][k-1] + avg(a[j..i-1]); prefix sums for O(1) average computation</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>Split Array Largest Sum</td><td>3</td><td>O(n²k) or O(n log sum)</td><td>2D dp[i][k] OR binary search + greedy</td><td>Objective is "minimise the maximum" (not minimise the sum); teaches minimax partition DP</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>Minimum Difficulty of a Job Schedule</td><td>3</td><td>O(n²d)</td><td>2D dp[i][d] + sliding max</td><td>Three dimensions: position, day-count, and the cost is MAX of segment (not sum); sliding window max per segment</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>Paint House III</td><td>3</td><td>O(n·k·m²)</td><td>3D dp[i][k][c]</td><td>Third dimension = color of last painted house; neighborhood count increments when color changes; three-state expansion</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>Decode Ways</td><td>1</td><td>O(n)</td><td>1D dp[i]</td><td>Counting partitions (not optimising); cost is binary (valid code or not); teaches COUNT variant</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>11</td><td>Word Break Count</td><td>2</td><td>O(n·m)</td><td>1D dp[i] + hash set</td><td>Count valid word-break partitions using dictionary; hash set for O(1) word check</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>12</td><td>Maximum Sum After K Partitions</td><td>3</td><td>O(nk)</td><td>2D dp[i][k]</td><td>Exactly k parts (not at most); initialise with -∞ for unreachable; boundary condition j ≥ k-1</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>13</td><td>Optimal partition with Convex Hull Trick</td><td>5</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>CHT / Li Chao tree</td><td>When cost(j,i) = a[j]*i + b[j] (linear in j), CHT reduces O(n²) inner loop to O(log n)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>14</td><td>Divide &amp; Conquer DP</td><td>5</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>Recursive D&amp;C with opt bounds</td><td>When j*(i) ≤ j*(i+1) (monotone optimal split), D&amp;C halves the search space at each recursion level; O(n log n) total</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Complexity Staircase</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
