                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution Across Stages</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 1: 1D Partition DP (Single Dimension)</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 — Word Break / Decode Ways:</strong><br>
                        <code>dp[i]</code> = boolean (can prefix of length i be partitioned?) or integer (count/cost for prefix of length i)<br>
                        Recurrence: <code>dp[i] = OR(dp[j] AND valid(j,i))</code> for boolean; <code>dp[i] = SUM(dp[j] for valid j)</code> for count; <code>dp[i] = MIN(dp[j] + cost(j,i))</code> for optimisation<br>
                        Base: <code>dp[0] = True</code> (or 1 for count, 0 for min-cost)<br>
                        Fill: left to right; dp[i] uses all dp[j] for j &lt; i<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up left-to-right — memoised top-down also works; bottom-up avoids recursion overhead for n ≤ 10⁵<br>
                        Space: O(n) — only the dp array needed<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 — Partition Array for Maximum Sum:</strong><br>
                        <code>dp[i]</code> = max sum partitioning a[0..i-1] with each segment length ≤ k<br>
                        Recurrence: <code>dp[i] = max(dp[j] + (i-j) * max(a[j..i-1]) for j in range(max(0,i-k), i))</code><br>
                        Running max: as j decreases from i-1 to i-k, maintain <code>cur_max = max(cur_max, a[j])</code>; avoids O(k) recompute per j<br>
                        Base: <code>dp[0] = 0</code><br>
                        Fill: left to right; inner loop runs at most k iterations → O(n·k)
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 2: 2D Partition DP (Position × Count)</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Largest Sum of Averages / Min Job Difficulty / Split Array:</strong><br>
                        <code>dp[i][k]</code> = optimal value for first i elements partitioned into exactly k segments<br>
                        Recurrence: <code>dp[i][k] = opt(dp[j][k-1] + cost(j, i) for j in range(k-1, i))</code><br>
                        j ≥ k-1 ensures prior k-1 segments had at least one element each<br>
                        Base: <code>dp[0][0] = 0</code>; <code>dp[i][k] = +∞</code> (or <code>-∞</code>) for k &gt; i (not enough elements)<br>
                        Cost functions:<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Sum of averages: cost(j,i) = (prefix[i] - prefix[j]) / (i-j) — O(1) with prefix sums<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Job difficulty: cost(j,i) = max(jobs[j..i-1]) — O(1) with sliding max during j-scan<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;Split array: cost(j,i) = max(a[j..i-1]) — same as job difficulty<br>
                        Preferred: Bottom-up, outer loop over k (1 to K), inner loop over i (k to n), innermost over j — fill order guarantees dp[j][k-1] is available when computing dp[i][k]<br>
                        Optimisation (Stage 5): If cost(j,i) satisfies the concave SMAWK condition, D&amp;C DP applies → O(n log n)
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 3: 3D Partition DP (Position × Count × Mode)</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3/4 — Paint House III / String Compression / Word Break with Budget:</strong><br>
                        <code>dp[i][k][c]</code> = optimal value for first i elements, k "groups/segments used", last-segment type/color c<br>
                        Recurrence: <code>dp[i][k][c] = opt(dp[j][k-1][c'] + cost(j,i,c) for all j &lt; i and c' compatible with c)</code><br>
                        Base: depends on problem; typically <code>dp[0][0][*] = 0</code>; all others +∞<br>
                        Key: the third dimension c GATES transitions — same color c as previous → don't increment k; different → increment k<br>
                        Preferred: Top-down memoisation — three-dimensional state with conditional third-dimension transitions is error-prone in bottom-up; memoisation handles order automatically
                    </div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Group 4: Optimised Partition DP (Stage 5)</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5a — Convex Hull Trick:</strong><br>
                        Applicable when: <code>dp[i] = min over j of (dp[j] + a[j]*i + b[j])</code> — cost is a linear function of the query variable i<br>
                        View each j as a line <code>y = a[j]*x + b[j]</code> where y = dp[j] + cost; query at x=i<br>
                        Maintain lower convex hull of lines; binary search for minimum → O(log n) per query<br>
                        Total: O(n log n); or O(n) if queries are monotone (deque-based CHT)<br>
                        Li Chao tree: alternative for non-monotone j or i; O(n log V) where V = value range<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5b — Divide &amp; Conquer DP:</strong><br>
                        Applicable when: opt[i] (optimal j for dp[i]) is monotone: opt[i] ≤ opt[i+1]<br>
                        Condition: cost function satisfies the quadrangle inequality: cost(a,c) + cost(b,d) ≤ cost(a,d) + cost(b,c) for a ≤ b ≤ c ≤ d<br>
                        Algorithm:<br>
                        <code>solve(lo, hi, opt_lo, opt_hi):<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;mid = (lo + hi) // 2<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;scan j from opt_lo to min(opt_hi, mid-1); find opt_mid<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;dp[mid] = best value found<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;solve(lo, mid-1, opt_lo, opt_mid)<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;solve(mid+1, hi, opt_mid, opt_hi)</code><br>
                        Total: O(n log n) — each level of recursion scans O(n) j values total; O(log n) levels
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        "partition / split / divide array into [k] contiguous parts" → Stage 3 2D partition DP — dp[i][k]; cost = function of last segment<br>
                        "minimum number of [cuts / splits] to make each segment satisfy property P" → Stage 1/2 1D partition DP — dp[i] = min cuts; cost(j,i) = ∞ if P not satisfied<br>

                        "fill shelves / schedule jobs / assign tasks to days" → Stage 4 disguised partition DP — identify what a "segment" is; cost = max or sum per segment<br>
                        "word break / can string be decoded as [words / codes]" → Stage 1 feasibility partition DP — dp[i] boolean; hash set for O(1) segment validity<br>
                        "maximum score from partitioning where score = f(segment)" → Stage 1/2 optimisation partition DP — dp[i] = max(dp[j] + f(s[j:i]))<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        Input is a 1D sequence; output is a scalar (min cost, max score, count); answer requires dividing the sequence into non-overlapping contiguous parts → Partition DP; O(n²) base; dp[i] with inner j-loop<br>
                        Problem has an explicit "k parts" or "d days" constraint — answer depends on BOTH position AND count → 2D partition DP dp[i][k]; O(n²k)<br>
                        Third dimension appears when the "type" or "color" of the last segment affects future segment costs → 3D dp[i][k][c]<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        n ≤ 1000 and k ≤ 100 → O(n²k) feasible; standard 2D partition DP<br>
                        n ≤ 10⁵ with O(n²) TLE → check if cost function is linear in j (CHT) or if opt is monotone (D&amp;C)<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        "partition array into two subsets with minimum difference" → NOT contiguous partition DP → 0/1 Knapsack dp[s]; elements need not be contiguous<br>
                        "burst balloons / remove elements with cost depending on neighbours" → NOT partition DP → Interval DP ("last one standing"); cost has cross-segment dependencies<br>
                        "minimum cost to merge non-adjacent segments" → NOT 1D partition DP → Interval DP (arbitrary split order); the "non-adjacent" or "arbitrary order" property breaks partition DP's left-to-right structure
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Q1:</strong> Does the problem ask for optimal value (min/max/count) of a partition of a 1D sequence into CONTIGUOUS, NON-OVERLAPPING segments covering all elements?<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ NO: Not partition DP. Check knapsack (non-contiguous), interval DP (arbitrary order), or greedy.<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ YES: Continue.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q2:</strong> What does cost(j, i) depend on?<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ Segment content (sum, max, avg, dict lookup, palindrome check): → Standard partition DP. O(n²). Go to Q3.<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ Cross-segment interaction (cost of segment [j,i] depends on what's in [0,j-1] or [i,n-1]): → NOT partition DP. Use interval DP or state machine DP.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q3:</strong> Is there a BOUND on the number of segments (exactly k or at most k)?<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ YES: Add k as second dimension. dp[i][k]. O(n²k). Go to Q4.<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ NO: 1D dp[i]. O(n²). Go to Q5.<br><br>
                        <strong>Q4:</strong> Does the cost or transition also depend on the TYPE/COLOR/MODE of the last segment?<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ YES: Third dimension. dp[i][k][c]. O(n²·k·C). Top-down recommended.<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ NO: Standard 2D. dp[i][k].<br><br>
                        <strong>Q5:</strong> Is n &gt; 5000 and O(n²) TLEs?<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ Is cost(j,i) LINEAR in j? → YES: Convex Hull Trick. O(n log n).<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ Is the optimal j* monotone (opt[i] ≤ opt[i+1])? → YES: Divide &amp; Conquer DP. O(n log n).<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ Is the window of valid j fixed (e.g., |j-i| ≤ k)? → YES: Sliding window max/deque DP. O(n·k) → O(n).<br>
                        &nbsp;&nbsp;→ None apply: O(n²) may be unavoidable. Check if n ≤ 5000.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage identification:</strong><br>
                        Q2 (simple cost) + Q3 (no k) → Stage 1. O(n²) or better.<br>
                        Q2 + Q3 (k bound) → Stage 3. O(n²k).<br>
                        Q4 (color/type) → Stage 3. O(n²·k·C). Use top-down.<br>
                        Problem disguised (shelves/jobs/paint) → Stage 4. Same complexity.<br>
                        Q5 (CHT or D&amp;C) → Stage 5. O(n log n).<br>
                        If O(n²) TLEs: check linearity of cost (CHT) or opt monotonicity (D&amp;C).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique BREAKS</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Cost function has cross-segment dependencies:</strong> Partition DP requires that cost(j,i) depends ONLY on the segment a[j..i-1], never on segments outside it. If the cost of a segment changes based on what's already been computed, the subproblem is not self-contained. Fix: expand the state to include the relevant property of the adjacent segment as a dimension (making it a state machine DP or 3D partition DP).<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Counting ALL partitions without dp pruning (Word Break II):</strong> Enumerating all valid partitions by backtracking without first building the feasibility dp table leads to exponential time on strings where many prefixes are reachable but the full string is not. Fix: always run the O(n²) boolean dp pass first; only DFS from positions where dp[pos] = True.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Wrong boundary for the j-loop in k-segment DP:</strong> In dp[i][k], the inner j-loop must start at j = k-1 (not j = 0). Starting at j = 0 allows segments where previous k-1 groups don't have enough elements — dp[j][k-1] would be -∞ or invalid. Additionally, dp[i][k] is only valid for i ≥ k (need at least k elements for k segments). Fix: always enforce j ≥ k-1 in the inner loop and initialise dp[i][k] = +∞ for i &lt; k.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Applying CHT when cost is not linear in j:</strong> CHT requires cost(j,i) = a(j)*i + b(j) — strictly linear in the query variable i. If the cost involves max/min of segment (not sum), it is NOT linear → CHT doesn't apply. Use D&amp;C DP if opt is monotone, or accept O(n²). Silently applying CHT to a non-linear cost gives wrong answers.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] D&amp;C DP when opt is NOT monotone:</strong> If the cost function does not satisfy the quadrangle inequality, opt[i] is not monotone and D&amp;C DP gives wrong answers. Fix: always verify opt monotonicity on small cases before applying D&amp;C DP. If in doubt, verify the quadrangle inequality algebraically.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 4] Treating "Burst Balloons" / "Remove Boxes" as partition DP:</strong> These problems have costs that depend on what's adjacent to the current segment — which changes as elements are removed. Partition DP assumes each segment's cost is fixed once the endpoints are known. Fix: use Interval DP with the "last one standing" framing.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 — Word Break: Optimal Substructure</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[i] = OR(dp[j] AND s[j:i] in dictionary for j in 0..i-1) correctly determines if s[0..i-1] can be word-broken.<br>
                        Optimal substructure: If s[0..i-1] can be word-broken, there exists a LAST word s[j..i-1] in the dictionary, and s[0..j-1] can also be word-broken (dp[j] = True).<br>
                        Completeness: We try ALL j ∈ [0,i); therefore the correct last-word split point is always considered.<br>
                        Base case: dp[0] = True — empty string is trivially word-breakable (zero words).<br>
                        Induction: dp[i] uses only dp[j] for j &lt; i (computed before i in left-to-right order). ✓ □<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Largest Sum of Averages: Correctness of 2D DP</strong><br>
                        Claim: dp[i][k] = max(dp[j][k-1] + sum(a[j..i-1])/(i-j) for j in k-1..i-1) = max sum of k group averages for a[0..i-1].<br>
                        Invariant: dp[i][k] = max sum of k group averages for ANY k-partition of a[0..i-1].<br>
                        Base: dp[i][1] = avg(a[0..i-1]) = average of the single group. ✓<br>
                        Induction on k: For k groups, the LAST group is a[j..i-1] for some j. Its average is sum(a[j..i-1])/(i-j). The first k-1 groups cover a[0..j-1], contributing dp[j][k-1] (optimal by induction). Since we maximise over all valid j (j ≥ k-1 ensures k-1 groups have ≥ 1 element each), we find the true optimum. ✓<br>
                        Prefix sums: sum(a[j..i-1]) = prefix[i] - prefix[j] in O(1); does not affect correctness, only efficiency. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5 — Divide &amp; Conquer DP: Correctness of Pruned Search</strong><br>
                        Claim: If opt[lo] ≤ opt[mid] ≤ opt[hi] (monotone optimal split), the D&amp;C search finds the true optimal j for every i.<br>
                        Monotonicity assumption: The cost function satisfies the quadrangle inequality, ensuring opt[i] is non-decreasing.<br>
                        D&amp;C invariant: When solve(lo, hi, opt_lo, opt_hi) is called, the true opt[i] for any i ∈ [lo,hi] lies in [opt_lo, opt_hi]. We scan only this range for i = mid.<br>
                        Left recursion: For i ∈ [lo, mid-1], opt[i] ≤ opt[mid], so the true opt lies in [opt_lo, opt_mid]. ✓<br>
                        Right recursion: For i ∈ [mid+1, hi], opt[i] ≥ opt[mid], so the true opt lies in [opt_mid, opt_hi]. ✓<br>
                        Work per level: At each recursion level, the sum of opt_hi - opt_lo across all calls = O(n). With O(log n) levels, total work = O(n log n). □
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">
                        <strong>Bug 1 — Word Break: using s[i:j] instead of s[j:i]</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: slice indices reversed<br>
                        if dp[j] and s[i:j] in word_set:   # BUG: i &gt; j always here<br>
                        # FIX:<br>
                        if dp[j] and s[j:i] in word_set:   # segment from j to i (exclusive)</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 2 — Decode Ways: not handling leading zero / single-digit zero</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG omission: "0" should NOT be decoded as a single digit<br>
                        if s[i-1] != '0':     # missing this guard<br>
                            dp[i] += dp[i-1]<br>
                        # FIX: always add this zero-guard for single-digit check</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 3 — Palindrome Partitioning II: initialising dp[i] = i instead of i-1</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: worst case is i-1 cuts (each char separate), not i cuts<br>
                        dp = list(range(n+1))   # dp[i] = i: BUG, off by 1<br>
                        # FIX:<br>
                        dp[0] = -1  # sentinel so dp[0]+1 = 0 cuts for valid palindrome at 0<br>
                        dp = [i-1 for i in range(n+1)]</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 4 — Partition Array for Max Sum: not resetting running max per i</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: cur_max carries over from previous i<br>
                        for i in range(1, n+1):<br>
                            for j in range(max(0, i-k), i):<br>
                                cur_max = max(cur_max, a[j])   # BUG: not reset<br>
                        # FIX: reset cur_max inside outer loop<br>
                        for i in range(1, n+1):<br>
                            cur_max = 0<br>
                            for j in range(i-1, max(-1, i-k-1), -1):<br>
                                cur_max = max(cur_max, a[j])<br>
                                dp[i] = max(dp[i], dp[j] + (i-j) * cur_max)</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 5 — 2D DP: j-loop starting at 0 instead of k-1</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: allows k-1 prior groups over 0 elements (infeasible)<br>
                        for j in range(0, i):   # BUG<br>
                        # FIX:<br>
                        for j in range(k-1, i):   # j must be at least k-1</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 6 — Min Job Difficulty: not checking i ≥ d</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: dp[i][d] computed even when i &lt; d<br>
                        for d in range(1, D+1):<br>
                            for i in range(1, n+1): ...   # BUG: no check for i &gt;= d<br>
                        # FIX:<br>
                        for d in range(1, D+1):<br>
                            for i in range(d, n+1):<br>
                                for j in range(d-1, i): ...</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 7 — Paint House III: overwriting pre-painted houses</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: ignores houses[i-1] != 0 constraint<br>
                        for c in range(1, m+1):<br>
                            dp[i][k][c] = min(...)   # BUG<br>
                        # FIX: if house is pre-painted, only update its actual color<br>
                        if houses[i-1] != 0:<br>
                            c = houses[i-1]<br>
                            dp[i][...][c] = ...</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 8 — Filling Bookcase Shelves: missing width constraint check</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: no width constraint<br>
                        for j in range(i-1, -1, -1):<br>
                            cur_max = max(cur_max, height[j])<br>
                            dp[i] = min(dp[i], dp[j] + cur_max)   # BUG<br>
                        # FIX: break when width exceeded<br>
                        for j in range(i-1, -1, -1):<br>
                            total_width += width[j]<br>
                            if total_width &gt; shelf_width: break<br>
                            cur_max = max(cur_max, height[j])<br>
                            dp[i] = min(dp[i], dp[j] + cur_max)</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 9 — D&amp;C DP: processing hi half before computing opt_mid</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: left half uses stale opt before opt_mid is found<br>
                        def solve(lo, hi, opt_lo, opt_hi):<br>
                            mid = (lo + hi) // 2<br>
                            solve(lo, mid-1, opt_lo, mid)    # BUG: opt_mid not computed yet<br>
                        # FIX: compute opt_mid FIRST<br>
                        def solve(lo, hi, opt_lo, opt_hi):<br>
                            mid = (lo + hi) // 2<br>
                            opt_mid = find_opt(mid, opt_lo, min(opt_hi, mid))<br>
                            solve(lo, mid-1, opt_lo, opt_mid)<br>
                            solve(mid+1, hi, opt_mid, opt_hi)</code><br><br>
                        <strong>Bug 10 — CHT: inserting lines non-monotonically into deque-CHT</strong><br>
                        <code># BUG: deque-CHT requires slopes to be monotone; arbitrary order breaks hull<br>
                        for j in range(n):<br>
                            hull.add_line(slope=a[j], intercept=dp[j])   # BUG if a[j] non-monotone<br>
                        # FIX: use Li Chao tree for arbitrary insertion order<br>
                        tree = LiChaoTree(x_range)<br>
                        for j in range(n):<br>
                            tree.add_line(a[j], dp[j])<br>
                            dp[i] = tree.query(i)</code>
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Confusing partition DP with knapsack DP:</strong> "Partition array into two equal-sum subsets" (LC 416) looks like a partition problem but is a 0/1 Knapsack because the subsets need not be contiguous. Partition DP ONLY applies when every element must belong to exactly one contiguous segment. The word "partition" in a problem title does NOT guarantee partition DP — check for contiguity.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 2] Palindrome Partitioning II: building O(n³) DP instead of O(n²) two-phase:</strong> Candidates attempt dp[i][j][k] (start, end, cuts) which is O(n³) in space and O(n⁴) in time. The correct model separates the palindrome table (O(n²) interval DP) from the cut DP (O(n) partition DP). The cut DP is 1D: dp[i] = min cuts for prefix of length i. NEVER combine these into a single 2D or 3D table.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] 2D partition DP: wrong initialisation of base cases:</strong> dp[0][0] = 0 and all other dp[0][k] = +∞ (or dp[i][0] = +∞ for i &gt; 0). A common mistake is initialising dp[i][1] = cost(0,i) manually instead of letting the recurrence handle it — this creates inconsistencies when k=1 is computed both manually and through the recurrence, sometimes double-counting or missing valid partitions.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] Applying D&amp;C DP without verifying opt monotonicity:</strong> The D&amp;C DP prunes the j-search range for each i. If opt[i] is NOT monotone, this pruning is INCORRECT — it will skip the true optimal j for some i and return wrong answers. Fix: verify the quadrangle inequality on paper (or empirically compute opt[] for small inputs and check monotonicity) before applying D&amp;C DP.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 3] Paint House III: incrementing neighborhood count incorrectly:</strong> The neighborhood count k increments when the current house's color DIFFERS from the previous house's color. A common mistake is incrementing k when the same color is used again (off-by-one in the "same color" check). The invariant is: k = number of maximal monochromatic runs so far; it increments exactly when a color TRANSITION happens.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 1] Word Break: O(n³) from naïve string hashing:</strong> s[j:i] in word_set is O(i-j) (string hashing). The total cost is O(n² · avg_word_length). For n=10⁴ and avg_word_length=10, this is 10⁹ operations. Fix: use a Trie to match words starting from each position in one O(n·max_word_length) pass.<br><br>
                        <strong>[Stage 5] CHT: using it when the cost function has MAX/MIN (not SUM/PRODUCT):</strong> CHT requires cost(j,i) = m(j)*i + b(j) — a linear function of i. Costs like max(a[j..i-1]) are NOT linear in i (they depend on all elements between j and i). Applying CHT to max-based costs gives wrong answers. Fix: for max-based costs, check if D&amp;C DP applies (via sliding window for monotone opt) or accept O(n²).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Stage</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>1</td><td>2</td><td>"Word Break: what if a word can be used at most c times?"</td><td>Add count[word] tracking; during the j-scan, check usage[s[j:i]] &lt; c; this adds a usage dictionary alongside dp; O(n·m·c)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>2</td><td>2</td><td>"Split Array Largest Sum: now minimise the SUM of squares of subarray sums (not max)."</td><td>Same 2D DP structure dp[i][k]; cost = sum(a[j..i-1])²; cost is a quadratic function of j — CHT applies since (Σa)² expands to 2*prefix[j]*prefix[i] - prefix[j]² which is linear in i; O(nk log n)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>3</td><td>3</td><td>"Minimum Job Difficulty: what if you must complete the jobs in ANY order (not fixed order)?"</td><td>Assign jobs optimally to days by sorting; on each day, assign the hardest remaining jobs; greedy: sort jobs DESC; each day takes the top ⌈n/d⌉ or ⌊n/d⌋ jobs; this changes the problem from partition DP to greedy scheduling</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>4</td><td>3</td><td>"Recover the actual partition (not just the optimal value) from the dp table."</td><td>Parent pointer array par[i] = j at which dp[i] was achieved; backtrack from n: cut at par[n], then par[par[n]], etc.; for 2D dp[i][k], par[i][k] = optimal j; O(n) reconstruction</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>5</td><td>4</td><td>"Filling Bookcase Shelves: books can be placed in any order (not fixed)."</td><td>Sort books by height descending; greedy fills each shelf with the tallest remaining books; or DP with sorted input — but sorting changes the problem from "contiguous partition" to "assignment"; may require a different DP formulation</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>6</td><td>4</td><td>"Palindrome Partitioning II: palindromes must have odd length only."</td><td>Only change the palindrome precomputation: is_palin[i][j] = (s[i]==s[j]) and is_palin[i+1][j-1] and (j-i+1) is odd; the 1D cut DP is unchanged; teaches that cost function modification is isolated from the DP structure</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>7</td><td>5</td><td>"Split Array into k parts minimise max sum, n = 10⁶. How?"</td><td>Binary search on answer + greedy feasibility check: O(n log(sum)); the partition DP is O(n²k) which TLEs; binary search: "can we partition into k parts with max sum ≤ mid?" answered greedily in O(n); total O(n log(sum))</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>8</td><td>5</td><td>"Prove when the Divide &amp; Conquer DP applies to Largest Sum of Averages."</td><td>Show that cost(j,i) = avg(a[j..i-1]) satisfies the concave version of the quadrangle inequality (opt is monotone for maximisation variant); increasing j* with increasing i means that adding more elements always prefers a later start for the last group</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>9</td><td>Beyond</td><td>"Partition DP across a distributed system — array is sharded across 10 machines."</td><td>Compute prefix sums on each shard locally; communicate only prefix sums to coordinator; coordinator runs partition DP with O(1) cost queries; for D&amp;C DP: each recursion level's work is O(n) — parallelise each level; O(n log n / machines) with synchronisation</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>10</td><td>Beyond</td><td>"Streaming partition DP: elements arrive online; answer must be updated after each element."</td><td>For unbounded k (no segment-count limit): Convex Hull Trick supports online line insertion (Li Chao tree); dp[i] updated in O(log n) per new element; for bounded k: requires a functional DP approach — maintain k layers of Li Chao trees</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>

                    <div class="sec-title">3-Phase Mastery Plan</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <strong>Phase 1 — Solve (strictly by Stage across all sub-variants):</strong><br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 — Establish the template in all three flavours:</strong><br>
                        S.No 1 (Word Break — boolean) → S.No 2 (Decode Ways — count) → S.No 3 (Extra Characters — minimise)<br>
                        After these three: write the universal recurrence dp[i] = f(dp[j] + cost(j,i)) from memory in all three modes (bool/count/optimise)<br>
                        Verify: can you identify cost(j,i) for any new problem in 30 seconds?<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — One constraint mutation:</strong><br>
                        S.No 4 (Palindrome Partitioning II — palindrome cost) → S.No 7 (Partition Array Max Sum — bounded window + running max) → S.No 5 (String Compression II)<br>
                        For each: identify the ONE change from the previous problem<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — Add the k dimension:</strong><br>
                        S.No 10 (Min Job Difficulty — cost=max) → S.No 11 (Largest Sum of Averages — cost=avg) → S.No 12 (Split Array — minimax)<br>
                        Write dp[i][k] for all three. The ONLY difference is the cost function.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 — Disguised problems:</strong><br>
                        S.No 14 (Bookcase Shelves) → S.No 17 (Paint House II) → S.No 19 (Paint House III)<br>
                        For each: state "sequence = ?, segment = ?, cost(j,i) = ?" before coding<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5 — Optimisations:</strong><br>
                        Binary search + greedy (Split Array LC 410) → Implement D&amp;C DP on Largest Sum of Averages → Implement CHT on a linear-cost partition problem<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 2 — Drill (speed and pattern recognition):</strong><br>
                        Stage 1: Word Break, Decode Ways, Extra Characters → under 8 minutes each<br>
                        Stage 3: Given a new "partition into k groups" problem — state dp[i][k] definition and recurrence verbally in under 60 seconds before coding<br><br>
                        <strong>Cost function flash drill — identify cost(j,i) in 10 seconds:</strong><br>
                        Bookcase Shelves → max(height[j..i-1]) constrained by sum(width[j..i-1]) ≤ W<br>
                        Largest Sum of Averages → sum(a[j..i-1]) / (i-j)<br>
                        Paint House III → cost[i-1][c] + neighborhood increment if color changed<br>
                        Palindrome Partitioning II → 1 if is_palindrome(s[j..i-1]) else ∞<br><br>
                        <strong>Optimisation trigger drill:</strong> Given n = 10⁵ and the cost function — identify in 30 seconds whether CHT or D&amp;C applies or neither<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 3 — Validate (unseen sources):</strong><br>
                        Stage 1/2: LeetCode weekly contest problems tagged "dynamic programming" from last 3 months not in this guide<br>
                        Stage 3: USACO Gold "Landscaping" / "Painting the Barn" — partitioned resource allocation<br>
                        Stage 4: Codeforces Div 2 D problems with 1D sequences and "assign to k groups" constraints<br>
                        Stage 5: AtCoder DP Contest problems J (Sushi), L (Deque) for D&amp;C DP variants
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Graduation Test</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Test 1 — CF 1603D: Critical Points (Stage 3 + Stage 4)</strong><br>
                        Primary stage: Stage 4<br>
                        Combination: Stage 4 (recognise that "segments between critical points" form a partition; the "critical point" structure is the hidden sequence) + Stage 3 (two-dimension DP over critical points and segment count; cost = precomputed segment properties)<br>
                        Why it certifies mastery: The sequence to partition is not given directly — critical points must be extracted first (Stage 4 reduction). The DP then requires a 2D partition recurrence (Stage 3). Neither stage alone solves the problem.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 2 — LC 1531: String Compression II (Stage 3 + Stage 4 + Stage 5)</strong><br>
                        Primary stage: Stage 3<br>
                        Combination: Stage 4 (disguised as a compression problem; must recognise that each "run of characters" = one segment; deletions reduce run counts) + Stage 3 (three-dimensional state: position, deletions used, last character group) + Stage 5 (naïve O(n³) can be optimised; memoisation makes it feasible for n≤100 but larger n needs pruning)<br>
                        Why it certifies mastery: The segment = "run of same character" identification is non-obvious (Stage 4). The three-dimension state expansion is required (Stage 3). The RLE cost function is neither a simple sum nor a max — it's a logarithmic step function — making it a unique cost variant not reducible to standard templates.<br><br>
                        <strong>Test 3 — USACO Gold 2019 February: Landscaping (Stage 4 + Stage 5)</strong><br>
                        Primary stage: Stage 5<br>
                        Combination: Stage 4 (partition rows of a field into groups to minimise cost; the "segment" = a group of consecutive rows assigned the same landscaping type; cost depends on transition costs between segment types) + Stage 5 (naïve O(n²·T) where T = types; opt monotonicity holds → D&amp;C DP; O(n·T·log n))<br>
                        Why it certifies mastery: The partition structure is hidden inside a 2D grid problem (Stage 4 — must reduce rows to a 1D sequence). The D&amp;C DP is required for large n (Stage 5). Correctly identifying AND implementing both layers cold within 45 minutes certifies full mastery of the Partition DP staircase.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp37">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">37</div>
                    <div>
                        <div class="topic-title">Game Theory &amp; Minimax</div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T5">T5</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Dynamic Programming</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Game Theory</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Minimax DP</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Sprague-Grundy</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Nim &amp; Variants</span>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="sec-title">Why This Topic Matters</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        Game Theory &amp; Minimax DP solves problems where two rational players alternate making decisions with opposing objectives, and the question is either who wins under perfect play, what score can the first player guarantee, or what is the optimal strategy. The core invariant is: every reachable game position is either a W-position (the player to move wins with perfect play) or an L-position (the player to move loses regardless of their moves), and this labelling propagates deterministically from terminal positions backwards through the game graph. This topic dominates competitive programming and top-tier interviews because it is a forcing structure — once you understand the W/L labelling invariant, every variant (score-difference games, Nim, Sprague-Grundy, bitmask games, graph games) becomes a coating on the same skeleton. The hard problems require identifying WHAT the game state is and HOW the game graph is structured, not inventing a new algorithm. Sprague-Grundy theory — which unifies all impartial games through XOR of Grundy values — is the single most powerful reduction in combinatorial game theory and converts multi-pile exponential problems into O(n) one-liners.
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        Every game position is a node in a directed graph. Terminal nodes (no moves) are coloured LOSS for the player to move. Propagate backwards: colour a node WIN if it has at least one edge to a LOSS node; colour it LOSS if ALL its edges lead to WIN nodes. Your entire job is to compute this colouring for the starting position. Everything else — score differences, Grundy values, Nim equivalences — is a refinement of this single colouring rule.<br><br>
                        <strong>Universal W/L recurrence:</strong><br>
                        dp[pos] = L if no moves exist; W if ∃ move to an L-position; L if all moves lead to W-positions.<br><br>
                        <strong>How this mental model scales through the 5 stages:</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 — Simplest form:</strong> The game graph is a line (pile sizes 0, 1, 2, …n). Terminal = pile 0. Colour left to right. dp[n] = W or L.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 — What changes:</strong> The winning/losing condition flips (misère), or the move options become asymmetric (divisors, perfect squares). The colouring rule is identical — only the terminal definition or the edge set changes.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 — What expands:</strong> The game state requires two or more dimensions. dp[i][j] = score-difference for interval games (both ends available), or dp[i][M] when the move-budget M is itself a state variable.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 — What is hidden:</strong> The game is disguised. The "game positions" are bitmasks of chosen numbers, node-pairs in a graph, or pile configurations after reductions. The Sprague-Grundy theorem maps any impartial game to an equivalent Nim pile via mex — the reduction IS the hard part.<br>
                        <strong>Stage 5 — What is optimised:</strong> The Grundy sequence for a take-away game is eventually periodic. Instead of computing O(n·|S|) for n up to 10¹⁸, detect the period in O(P·|S|) and answer any query in O(1).
                    </div>

                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant / Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant (W/L labelling completeness):</strong> In any finite, acyclic, two-player, zero-sum, perfect-information game, every position receives exactly one label: W or L.<br><br>
                        <strong>Proof sketch (strong induction on game-graph depth):</strong><br>
                        Base case (depth 0): Positions with no legal moves — the player to move cannot act and loses. Label = L. ✓<br>
                        Inductive step: Assume all positions at depth &lt; d are correctly labelled. For a position P at depth d:<br>
                        If any successor S has label L: the current player moves to S, leaving the opponent in a losing state. Label P = W. ✓<br>
                        If ALL successors have label W: every move leaves the opponent in a winning state. Label P = L. ✓<br>
                        Uniqueness: P cannot be both W and L — the two cases are mutually exclusive and exhaustive (some successor is L, or none is L). ✓<br>
                        Finiteness guarantees termination: The game is acyclic (a finite DAG), so every branch reaches a terminal in finite steps. The induction bottoms out. □<br><br>
                        <strong>Score-difference correctness sketch:</strong> Define dp[i][j] = (current player's score) − (opponent's score) for sub-game on interval [i,j]. The recurrence dp[i][j] = max(a[i] − dp[i+1][j], a[j] − dp[i][j-1]) is correct because: after the current player takes a[i] and the game state moves to [i+1,j], the NEW current player (the original opponent) achieves dp[i+1][j] advantage over the NEW opponent (the original player). So the original player's advantage is a[i] − dp[i+1][j]. The subtraction is the perspective flip.<br><br>
                        <strong>Sprague-Grundy theorem sketch:</strong> Define G(P) = mex&#123;G(P') : P' reachable from P&#125;. Then P is an L-position iff G(P) = 0, and for a sum of independent games, G(combined) = XOR(G(components)). The first claim follows directly from the W/L induction: G(P) = 0 iff mex&#123;...&#125; = 0 iff 0 is NOT in the reachable Grundy values iff every successor has Grundy value ≥ 1 iff every successor is a W-position (G ≥ 1 → W) iff P is an L-position. The XOR composition follows from Bouton's theorem on multi-pile Nim, extended to all impartial games via Grundy equivalence.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Sub-Variant</th><th>Stage</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>New Idea</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Single-pile take-away (fixed move set S)</td><td>Stage 1</td><td>O(n·|S|)</td><td>boolean dp array</td><td>THE baseline — W/L colouring from terminal dp[0]=L; dp[n] = any(not dp[n-s] for s in S); sequence is eventually periodic</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Take-away with divisor moves</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>O(n log n)</td><td>boolean dp</td><td>Move set is STATE-DEPENDENT (divisors of n, not a fixed set); moves recomputed per state</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Take-away with perfect-square moves</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>O(n√n)</td><td>boolean dp</td><td>Move set grows with n; inner loop is O(√n) per state</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Misère take-away</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>O(n·|S|)</td><td>boolean dp with flipped terminal</td><td>dp[0] = W (cannot move = WIN, because opponent took the last stone); same recurrence, ONE base-case flip</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Score-difference (interval game, take from ends)</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>2D interval DP</td><td>Tracks SCORE DIFFERENCE not just W/L; dp[i][j] = max(a[i]−dp[i+1][j], a[j]−dp[i][j-1]); fill by interval length</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Score-difference (suffix game, take from front)</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>O(n)</td><td>1D dp on suffix</td><td>Consumption is always left-to-right (not both ends); 1D dp replaces 2D; O(n) with rolling window</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Minimax guaranteed cost (Guess Number)</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>2D interval DP</td><td>Adversary maximises cost; we minimise worst-case; max inside min is the adversarial structure</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Stone Game II (variable M parameter)</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>dp[i][M] + suffix prefix sums</td><td>The MOVE BUDGET M is itself a state dimension; M updates as max(M, X) after each move</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Stone Game IV (perfect-square removal)</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>O(n√n)</td><td>W/L dp with square moves</td><td>Combines square-move set (S.No 3) with a W/L (not score-diff) query; foundational bridge</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Can I Win (bitmask game state)</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>O(2ⁿ·n)</td><td>bitmask dp</td><td>Game state is a BITMASK of used integers; first time exponential state space appears</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Nim (multi-pile, Sprague-Grundy)</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(n)</td><td>XOR of pile sizes</td><td>Multi-pile game; Grundy value of pile n = n; XOR = combined Grundy; L iff XOR = 0</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Generalised Grundy computation (arbitrary move set)</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(n·|S|)</td><td>grundy[n] = mex&#123;grundy[n-s]&#125;</td><td>mex replaces any; Grundy value encodes the full game spectrum (not just W/L); reveals Nim-equivalence</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Staircase Nim</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(n)</td><td>XOR of ODD-indexed pile sizes only</td><td>Not all piles contribute to XOR; odd-index reduction is the non-obvious insight</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Chalkboard XOR Game</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(n)</td><td>XOR property + parity; no DP needed</td><td>Initial XOR = 0 OR n is even → first player wins; proof via parity and XOR structure</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Cat and Mouse (graph game with DRAW)</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>O(n³)</td><td>reverse-BFS propagation; three-outcome DP</td><td>Cyclic game graph introduces DRAW as a third outcome; standard bottom-up DP fails on cycles</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Flip Game II / string state game</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(2ⁿ) memoised</td><td>game state = string hash</td><td>Game state is an arbitrary string; exponential without memoisation; string hash as cache key</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Sprague-Grundy sum of independent games</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(Σ Gᵢ)</td><td>XOR of component Grundy values</td><td>Multiple INDEPENDENT subgames played simultaneously; combined Grundy = XOR; identifying independent components IS the insight</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Period detection in Grundy sequences</td><td>Stage 5</td><td>O(P·|S|) + O(1) queries</td><td>cycle detection on Grundy array</td><td>Grundy sequences for fixed-move-set take-away games are eventually periodic; period detection enables O(1) queries for n up to 10¹⁸</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Wythoff's Game (two-pile, can remove equal from both)</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(n)</td><td>golden-ratio formula; no DP needed</td><td>L-positions follow Beatty sequence: (⌊φ·k⌋, ⌊φ²·k⌋) for k = 0,1,2,…; closed-form bypasses DP entirely</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Partisan game (asymmetric moves)</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>O(n²)</td><td>dp[pos][turn] — turn dimension required</td><td>Left/Right players have DIFFERENT legal moves; Sprague-Grundy doesn't apply; turn is a required state dimension</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>

