                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>Linguistic Triggers:</strong><br>
                        &bull; "for each node, find the [max/min/count] in its subtree" &rarr; Stage 1 bottom-up; dp[v] = f(dp[children]); O(n)<br>
                        &bull; "select subset of nodes, no two adjacent, maximise total value" &rarr; Stage 2 MIS tree DP; dp[v][0/1]; O(n)<br>
                        &bull; "find the answer for every possible root" &rarr; Stage 2 rerooting DP; two-pass DFS; O(n)<br>
                        &bull; "select exactly K nodes/edges from the tree maximising [objective]" &rarr; Stage 3 tree knapsack; dp[v][k]; O(n&sup2;)<br>
                        &bull; "count paths with sum / XOR / property P in a tree" &rarr; Stage 3 prefix-sum hashmap on DFS OR centroid decomp; O(n) or O(n log n)<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural Triggers:</strong><br>
                        &bull; Input is a parent array parent[i]; answer for each node depends on its subtree &rarr; rooted tree DP; post-order; O(n)<br>
                        &bull; Answer requires combining TWO arms at a node (diameter, max path sum) &rarr; top-2 arm tracking; global updated at bend; return single arm<br>
                        &bull; Multiple queries on subtrees of a static tree &rarr; Euler tour linearisation + BIT/segment tree; O(log n) per query<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint Triggers:</strong><br>
                        &bull; n &le; 10&sup5; and "select k nodes from tree" &rarr; O(n&sup2;) tree knapsack may TLE; consider small-to-large for O(n log n)<br>
                        &bull; Multiple queries each specifying k "key" nodes on large tree &rarr; virtual tree per query; O(k log n) compressed tree<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        &bull; "find shortest paths between every pair" &rarr; NOT tree DP &rarr; LCA + binary lifting for single-pair O(log n); BFS from each node O(n&sup2;)<br>
                        &bull; "minimum cost to connect all nodes" &rarr; NOT tree DP &rarr; MST (Kruskal/Prim); tree DP assumes tree is GIVEN<br>
                        &bull; "number of BSTs with n nodes" &rarr; NOT actual tree DP &rarr; 1D Catalan number DP; no tree traversed
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0;font-size:.78rem"><code>Q1: Is the input an explicit tree (n nodes, n-1 edges)?
  YES: Continue to Q2.
  NO:  Implicit tree? (BST insertion? Interval containment? Dependency DAG? Parent array?)
       If YES: extract the tree (Stage 4), then proceed.
       If NO: not a tree DP problem.

Q2: Does the answer at each node depend ONLY on its subtree?
  YES: Pure bottom-up tree DP. Stage 1. O(n).
       dp[v] = scalar. Recurrence: dp[v] = f(dp[c], val[v]).
  NO:  Continue.

Q3: Does the answer change if the root changes?
  YES: Rerooting DP. Stage 2. O(n).
       First pass: bottom-up (subtree aggregates + sizes).
       Second pass: top-down (contribution from above).
  NO:  Continue.

Q4: Is there a BINARY CHOICE at each node?
    (Include/exclude, covered/not covered, camera/no camera)
  YES: Two-state or three-state tree DP. dp[v][s]. Stage 2-3.
       2 states: dp[v][0/1].  3+ states: draw state machine FIRST.
  NO:  Continue.

Q5: Is there a BUDGET (select exactly K nodes/edges)?
  YES: Tree knapsack. dp[v][k]. Stage 3. O(n^2) naive.
       Merge children iteratively; O(n^2) by pairs-at-LCA proof.
       If n > 10^4: look for Stage 5 optimisation.
  NO:  Continue.

Q6: Does the answer involve PATHS (not just subtrees)?
  Q6a: Sum/XOR from root to node?
       -> Top-down DFS + prefix hashmap. Stage 3. O(n).
  Q6b: Max/min over ALL paths?
       -> Top-2 arms at each node; global at bend node. Stage 2.
  Q6c: COUNT of paths with property?
       -> Centroid decomposition. Stage 4. O(n log n).
  NO:  Continue.

Q7: Is naive O(n^2) too slow?
  -> Knapsack merge -> small-to-large (DSU on tree). O(n log n). Stage 5.
  -> Query per node -> Euler tour + BIT. O(n log n). Stage 5.
  -> Sparse key-node queries -> Virtual tree. O(k log n)/query. Stage 5.</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique Breaks</div>
                    <div class="warn-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 1] Applying bottom-up tree DP when the answer depends on traversal direction:</strong> For "maximum path from any node to any node," a single bottom-up pass misses paths through the root's parent. Fix: two-pass rerooting (Stage 2).<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 2] Rerooting with incorrect O(1) transition:</strong> Many candidates write ans[v] = ans[parent] + n &minus; 2&times;sz[parent] (wrong). Fix: always derive by considering which nodes gain/lose distance when re-rooting from parent to v.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 2] Top-2 arms: using the same child for both "up" and "down" arm:</strong> When v IS the best-arm child of parent, the up-contribution must use the second-best arm. Fix: precompute best1[parent] and best2[parent] by index.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 3] Claiming O(n&sup2;) per node for tree knapsack instead of O(n&sup2;) globally:</strong> Correct analysis via pairs-at-LCA gives O(n&sup2;) globally. Each pair (u, w) contributes O(1) at exactly their LCA.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 3] Path DP: forgetting to BACKTRACK hashmap on DFS return:</strong> Missing hashmap[prefix] &minus;= 1 after processing children causes paths from unrelated subtrees to be counted.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 4] Applying tree DP when input contains cycles:</strong> Post-order invariant breaks for graphs. Fix: verify input is acyclic before applying.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 5] Small-to-large when merge is NOT associative/commutative:</strong> For aggregates like median, merging doesn't directly work. Fix: check associativity before applying.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 &mdash; Tree Diameter via Post-Order DFS</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> diameter = max over all nodes v of (top1_arm[v] + top2_arm[v]).<br>
                        <em>Proof:</em> Every path has a unique bend node (its LCA). At bend node v: path = arm into one child + arm into another = top1 + top2. Post-order DFS visits every node once as a potential bend. Since every path bends at exactly one node, the global maximum is the true diameter. &#9633;<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 &mdash; Rerooting DP Correctness (Sum of Distances)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> ans[v] = ans[parent(v)] + n &minus; 2&times;sz[v].<br>
                        <em>Proof:</em> Re-rooting from p to v: sz[v] nodes get 1 closer; n &minus; sz[v] nodes get 1 farther. Change = (n &minus; sz[v]) &minus; sz[v] = n &minus; 2&times;sz[v]. ans[root] is correct from first pass; each re-root derives from a correct parent; by induction all ans[v] are correct. &#9633;<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5 &mdash; Tree Knapsack Total Complexity O(n&sup2;)</strong><br>
                        <em>Claim:</em> Merge cost O(|accumulated| &times; |child|) totals O(n&sup2;) across all merges.<br>
                        <em>Proof:</em> For any pair (u, w), they contribute to exactly ONE merge at their LCA. There are at most C(n,2) pairs. Total cost = &sum; (size_A &times; size_B) = &sum; 1 over all pairs &le; C(n,2) = O(n&sup2;). &#9633;
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">
                        <strong>Bug 1 &mdash; Diameter: returning sum of both arms to parent</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>return l + r + node.val   # BUG: parent receives full diameter
return max(l, r) + node.val  # FIX: single best arm</code></pre><br>
                        <strong>Bug 2 &mdash; MIS: dp[v][0] not allowing children to be either state</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>dp[v][0] = sum(dp[c][0] for c in ch)                # BUG
dp[v][0] = sum(max(dp[c][0], dp[c][1]) for c in ch) # FIX</code></pre><br>
                        <strong>Bug 3 &mdash; Rerooting: using parent's subtree size</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>ans[v] = ans[parent] + n - 2 * sz[parent]  # BUG
ans[v] = ans[parent] + n - 2 * sz[v]       # FIX</code></pre><br>
                        <strong>Bug 4 &mdash; Top-2 arms: using same child for both arms</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code># FIX: precompute best1_child and best2_child per parent
if best1_child[p] == v:
    up[v] = max(up[p], down[best2_child[p]]) + 1
else:
    up[v] = max(up[p], down[best1_child[p]]) + 1</code></pre><br>
                        <strong>Bug 5 &mdash; Three-state camera: null treated as "covered"</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>if not node: return (0, 0, 0)               # BUG
if not node: return (0, float('inf'), 0)    # FIX: null can't have camera</code></pre><br>
                        <strong>Bug 6 &mdash; Prefix hashmap path count: missing backtrack</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>hashmap[prefix] = hashmap.get(prefix, 0) + 1
for child in node.children:
    dfs(child, prefix + child.val)
# BUG: missing backtrack
hashmap[prefix] -= 1  # FIX</code></pre><br>
                        <strong>Bug 7 &mdash; Tree knapsack: full n+1 sized arrays per node</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>dp = [[0] * (n+1) for _ in range(n+1)]  # BUG: O(n^2) space
# FIX: dp[v] has size sz[v]+1; discard child DPs after merge</code></pre><br>
                        <strong>Bug 8 &mdash; Small-to-large: iterating the LARGER set</strong><br>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>for elem in large: small.add(elem)          # BUG: O(n) moves
if len(a) < len(b): a, b = b, a            # FIX: ensure a is larger
for elem in b: a.add(elem)                 # FIX: iterate smaller</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 1] Treating the tree as a linear array and applying 1D DP:</strong> BFS level-order DP loses the parent-child relationship. In tree DP the "index" is a node, and transitions go children &rarr; parent.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 2] Forgetting top-2 arms optimisation in rerooting:</strong> O(n) scan over siblings gives O(n&sup2;) total. Precompute best1[v] and best2[v] by index for O(1) per child.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 3] Space is also O(n&sup2;) if child DPs aren't discarded:</strong> Time is O(n&sup2;) by pairs-at-LCA, but keeping all arrays makes space O(n&sup2;). Discard child DP after merge; space = O(n).<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 4] Applying tree DP to implicit tree without verifying structure:</strong> Verify the extraction with a small example before coding DP.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 2] Rerooting: recomputing subtree sizes in second pass:</strong> Subtree sizes are defined relative to the original root. The second DFS reads stored values; never recomputes structure.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 5] Confusing DSU on tree with Union-Find DSU:</strong> "DSU on tree" = small-to-large merging. Union-Find = path-compressed connected components. Completely different algorithms with the same acronym.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 3] Not initialising count[0] = 1 before DFS for path hashmap:</strong> count[0] = 1 represents the "empty prefix." Missing this causes root-starting paths to be skipped.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Stage Push</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer Direction</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">1</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>"Your House Robber III solution uses dp[v][0/1]. What if you could rob at most K consecutive non-adjacent nodes on any root-to-leaf path?"</td><td>Add run-length dimension: dp[v][s][r] where r = consecutive selections ending at v; transitions check r &le; K before allowing s=1; still O(n &times; K)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">2</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>"What if nodes in House Robber III have negative values? Does the algorithm change?"</td><td>No structural change; dp[v][0] naturally yields 0 contribution when skipping negative nodes; max() handles omitting negative-value nodes; no third "skip" state needed</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">3</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>"Extend Sum of Distances to: for each node v, find the sum of SQUARED distances to all other nodes."</td><td>Compute cnt[v] and sumD[v] bottom-up; rerooting: ansQ[v] = ansQ[par] + 2&middot;ans[par] + (n &minus; 2&middot;sz[v]); derive by expanding (d+1)&sup2; and (d&minus;1)&sup2;; requires ans[v] already computed</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">4</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>"How do you count paths with sum = K in a weighted tree where edge weights can be NEGATIVE?"</td><td>Algorithm is IDENTICAL; negative weights do NOT break correctness because hashmap keys are exact prefix sums; what changes: prefix sums are no longer monotone, so two-pointer fails &mdash; hashmap handles this perfectly</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">5</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>"You need to run House Robber DP 10&sup5; times on the same tree, each query marks one node as 'forced included'. Can you avoid re-running?"</td><td>Precompute dp[v][0/1] bottom-up and up_dp[v][0/1] top-down; combine in O(1) per query; reduces 10&sup5; &times; O(n) to O(n log n) preprocessing + O(log n) per query</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">6</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>"Given a tree with node colours, query (u, v, c): count nodes of colour c on the path from u to v. How for 10&sup5; queries?"</td><td>Offline: sort queries by colour; Euler tour + BIT tracks colour contributions; path(u,v) = prefix(u) + prefix(v) &minus; 2&times;prefix(LCA) &minus; val(LCA); O((n + q) log n)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">7</td><td>Stage 5</td><td>"Your tree knapsack is O(n&sup2;). How do you bring it to O(n log&sup2; n)?"</td><td>Small-to-large set merging: each element moves O(log n) times &times; O(log n) per insertion = O(n log&sup2; n); alternatively for path-graph (degenerate tree), 1D knapsack solvable in O(n log n) with divide-and-conquer; for general trees: merge at each centroid takes O(sz log sz)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">8</td><td>Stage 5</td><td>"10&sup5; queries each specify k &le; 20 key nodes. For each query, run a tree DP counting only nodes reachable from key nodes. How to avoid O(n) per query?"</td><td>Virtual tree: build compressed tree on k key nodes in O(k log n) using Euler tour order + pairwise LCA; O(k) nodes; run tree DP in O(k); total O(q &times; k log n) instead of O(q &times; n)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">9</td><td>Beyond Stage 5</td><td>"The tree is DYNAMIC &mdash; edges can be added or removed; after each update you need the new diameter. How do you maintain this in sub-O(n) per update?"</td><td>Link-Cut Tree (LCT): each path query is O(log n); maintain diameter using two "farthest node from root" queries after each structural update; O(log&sup2; n) per update amortised</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">10</td><td>Beyond Stage 5</td><td>"You have a distributed system where each server holds one subtree of a large tree with n = 10&sup9; nodes. How would you compute the tree diameter across servers?"</td><td>Each server computes local diameter AND two deepest arms from its subtree root; combine across servers: diameter = max(local diameters, arm1[server_A] + arm1[server_B] + 1 for all adjacent server pairs); O(servers &minus; 1) messages</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>
                    <div class="sec-title">3-Phase Mastery Plan</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>Phase 1 &mdash; Solve (strictly by Stage):</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 &mdash; Establish the post-order invariant:</strong><br>
                        Solve in this exact order: S.No 2 (Path Sum III), S.No 1 (Diameter), S.No 4 (Distribute Coins), S.No 5 (Longest ZigZag).<br>
                        After these four: given ANY single-pass tree DP problem, you must be able to state the return signature (val1, val2, ...) and global update formula before touching code. Time target: 10 min each.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 &mdash; Add binary choice and rerooting:</strong><br>
                        Solve in order: S.No 3 (House Robber III), S.No 6 (Longest Path Different Adjacent Values), S.No 9 (Sum of Distances), S.No 10 (Count Possible Roots), S.No 11 (Max&ndash;Min Price Difference).<br>
                        Drill: for rerooting problems, always write the formula derivation (which nodes gain/lose distance) on paper before coding.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 &mdash; State expansion and knapsack:</strong><br>
                        Solve in order: S.No 8 (Binary Tree Cameras), S.No 18 (CF 161D Distance in Tree), S.No 29 (USACO Delegation), S.No 13 (Subtree Label Count).<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 &mdash; Implicit trees and hidden reductions:</strong><br>
                        Solve in order: S.No 14 (Count Nodes Highest Score), S.No 21 (Reorder Array &rarr; Same BST), S.No 22 (Number of Good Paths), S.No 20 (Count Valid Paths &mdash; Centroid).<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5 &mdash; Optimisation:</strong><br>
                        Solve in order: S.No 26 (Lomsat Gelral CF 600E), S.No 32 (Smallest Missing Value), S.No 27 (USACO Sprinklers 2), S.No 31 (AtCoder Virtual Tree).<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 2 &mdash; Drill:</strong><br>
                        &bull; 10-min drill (Stage 1): Write DFS signature and global update rule for: height, diameter, max path sum, count paths sum K &mdash; without referencing any solution.<br>
                        &bull; Formula drill (Stage 2): Cover the problem; write the rerooting transition formula from scratch for: sum of distances, max arm difference, min height under rerooting. Verify on a 4-node star graph by hand.<br>
                        &bull; State machine drill (Stage 3): Draw the state transition diagram for binary tree cameras BEFORE coding. Verify: do null nodes produce state 0, 1, or 2? (Answer: null &rarr; special sentinel; leaf has state 0).<br>
                        &bull; Knapsack merge drill: Trace the tree knapsack merge for a 3-node path (root &rarr; child &rarr; grandchild) with budget k=2. Verify the pairs-at-LCA argument by listing all pairs and their LCA.<br>
                        &bull; Implicit tree drill (Stage 4): For S.No 21 and S.No 22: cover the code; state the tree-extraction step in one sentence before writing any DP.<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 3 &mdash; Validate (unseen problem sources):</strong><br>
                        &bull; Stage 1: USACO Silver 2020 Feb "Swapity Swapity Swap" &mdash; subtree tracking under repeated permutation<br>
