                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Graduation Test</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Problem 1 &mdash; "Balanced Forest Partition" (Stage 3 + Stage 4)</strong><br>
                        <em>Source:</em> IOI 2017 / Codeforces 901C<br>
                        <em>Stages tested:</em> Stage 4 (implicit tree) + Stage 3 (tree knapsack)<br>
                        <em>Summary:</em> Given a tree where each node has a value, determine if you can remove exactly one edge to create two components with equal sum. If not, determine if you can add one node (with a chosen value) to make such a partition possible after one edge cut.<br>
                        <em>Why it proves mastery:</em> A candidate who only knows Stage 1&ndash;2 computes total sum and checks each subtree &mdash; solves the basic version. The full problem requires recognising "achievable subtree sums" as a tree knapsack (Stage 3) AND that the added node can be placed anywhere (Stage 4 rerooting of the knapsack). No single stage is sufficient; all four must interoperate. Solving cold in 45 minutes certifies internalisation of both patterns.<br><br>
                        <strong>Problem 2 &mdash; "CF 1188E" Tree Isomorphism Counting (Stage 3 + Stage 5)</strong><br>
                        <em>Source:</em> Codeforces 1188E<br>
                        <em>Stages tested:</em> Stage 5 (small-to-large) + Stage 3 (multi-dimensional state DP)<br>
                        <em>Summary:</em> Given a tree with nodes coloured red or blue and edge weights, find the minimum weight set of edges to remove such that every resulting component has equal numbers of red and blue nodes.<br>
                        <em>Why it proves mastery:</em> Candidate must (1) recognise balance = (red &minus; blue) is the DP dimension, (2) derive correct merge: new_balance = balance_so_far + balance_child at cost 0 (keep) or (edge_weight &minus; dp[child]) (cut), and (3) apply small-to-large to reduce O(n&sup2;) to O(n log n). All three realisations must arrive in sequence under time pressure.<br><br>
                        <strong>Problem 3 &mdash; "Maximum XOR Path in Tree with K Updates" (Stage 4 + Stage 5)</strong><br>
                        <em>Source:</em> Custom adaptation of CF 571D + trie-on-tree<br>
                        <em>Stages tested:</em> Stage 4 (XOR path transformation) + Stage 5 (trie as per-centroid data structure)<br>
                        <em>Summary:</em> Given a weighted tree, answer q queries: "What is the maximum XOR of values on any path in the tree?" After each query, one edge weight is updated.<br>
                        <em>Why it proves mastery:</em> Three independent insights must all arrive: (1) XOR path = XOR of two root-to-node prefixes (Stage 4 reduction); (2) maximum XOR over all pairs = trie query (Stage 5 data structure); (3) updates require centroid decomposition to localise change to O(log n) centroids (Stage 5 decomposition). Missing any one makes the problem unsolvable. Solving cold certifies mastery of the full staircase.
                    </div>
                </div>
