            <div class="topic-card" id="tp42">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">42</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">Dynamic Programming &middot; Data Structure Optimised DP</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T3">Apex Pattern</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">BIT/Seg-Tree + DP &middot; Monotonic Deque &middot; CHT &middot; Li Chao &middot; D&amp;C DP &middot; Knuth &middot; SMAWK &middot; CDQ &middot; Aliens Trick</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">26 problems &middot; 5 stages &middot; O(n&sup2;)&rarr;O(n log n)/O(n)</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why This Topic Matters:</strong> DS-Optimised DP takes a provably correct but O(n&sup2;) or O(n&sup2;k) DP and reduces it to O(n log n)/O(n) by recognising the inner loop is a structured query (range max, sliding window, line query) that can be collapsed by a purpose-built data structure. Core invariant: the na&iuml;ve "best j" query has monotone or geometric structure. Apex of competitive DP because it requires three simultaneous skills: (1) write correct O(n&sup2;) DP, (2) recognise algebraic structure of the transition, (3) implement a non-trivial DS (CHT, Li Chao, monotonic deque, segment tree, BIT) inside the DP loop. Universal TLE signal for n ~ 10&#8309;.</div>
                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Two-step pattern:</strong> (1) write O(n&sup2;) as dp[i] = max/min over j &lt; i of: f(j) + g(i, j); (2) ask what query over j this is. Range max/min of dp[j] &rarr; segment tree/BIT; sliding window &rarr; monotonic deque; m(j)&times;x(i)+b(j) &rarr; CHT/Li Chao; optimal j monotone in i &rarr; D&amp;C DP/Knuth. Recurrence UNCHANGED; only inner loop replaced.<br><br>
                        <strong>5 Stages:</strong><br>
                        &bull; <strong>Stage 1:</strong> O(n&sup2;) DP already correct. Name the DS (range max, sliding window, line query) before implementing.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Stage 2:</strong> ONE query constraint changes (non-monotone queries; variable-width window). Forces full-version DS (Li Chao over deque CHT; segment tree over BIT).<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Stage 3:</strong> State gains 2nd dimension; inner query becomes 2D or per-layer DS.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Stage 4:</strong> Hidden &mdash; problem doesn&apos;t look like DP; candidate must transform into canonical form and recognise g&apos;s structure.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Stage 5:</strong> Even O(n log n) too slow; apply Aliens trick (WQS binary search), CDQ, SMAWK, fractional cascading.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariants / Proof Sketches</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant 1: CHT &mdash; Lines on a Hull.</strong> For dp[i] = min over j of: b[j]+m[j]&middot;x[i], the optimal j lies on the lower convex hull of lines &#123;y = m[j]x + b[j]&#125;. <em>Proof sketch:</em> any non-hull line is dominated for ALL x by some other line. Hull has &le; O(n) lines; queries O(log n) binary search or O(1) amortised if monotone. &#9633;<br><br>
                        <strong>Invariant 2: D&amp;C DP &mdash; Monotone Optimal Split.</strong> For dp[i][j] = min over k of: dp[i&minus;1][k] + cost(k+1, j), if opt(i, j&minus;1) &le; opt(i, j) &le; opt(i, j+1), total O(n log n) per layer. <em>Proof:</em> D&amp;C call on [l, r] with mid searches opt in [opt(l), opt(r)]; recursion depth O(log n); O(n) total per level. &#9633;<br><br>
                        <strong>Invariant 3: Knuth &mdash; Quadrangle Inequality.</strong> If cost[a][c]+cost[b][d] &le; cost[a][d]+cost[b][c] for a&le;b&le;c&le;d AND cost monotone, then opt[i][j&minus;1] &le; opt[i][j] &le; opt[i+1][j]. <em>Proof sketch:</em> QI implies cost "rewards" merging adjacent subintervals; convexity-like property forces opt sandwich. Each row&apos;s search is O(n); total O(n&sup2;). &#9633;<br><br>
                        <strong>Invariant 4: BIT/Seg-Tree DP &mdash; Range Query.</strong> For dp[i] = max over j&lt;i of: dp[j] with a[j]&lt;a[i], BIT indexed by VALUE supports O(log n) point updates and prefix max queries. Each op O(log n); n ops total. &#9633;
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>Group 1 &mdash; Seg-Tree/BIT + DP:</strong> LIS in O(n log n) (Stage 2); LIS counting with (length, count) tuple (Stage 3); 2D LIS O(n log&sup2; n) (Stage 3); max non-overlapping intervals (Stage 3).<br>
                        <strong>Group 2 &mdash; Monotonic Deque + DP:</strong> max subarray length &isin; [lo, hi] (Stage 1); jump DP bounded window (Stage 2); stock trading cooldown K (Stage 2); DAG shortest path bounded jump (Stage 3).<br>
                        <strong>Group 3 &mdash; Convex Hull Trick:</strong> classic (dp[j]+(x[i]&minus;x[j])&sup2;) with deque CHT (Stage 1); binary search CHT for non-monotone queries (Stage 2); Li Chao tree for non-monotone slopes (Stage 2); CHT on tree paths (Stage 4).<br>
                        <strong>Group 4 &mdash; D&amp;C DP:</strong> layered k-partition with monotone opt (Stage 3); sum-of-squared sizes (Stage 3); painter&apos;s partition generalised (Stage 3).<br>
                        <strong>Group 5 &mdash; Knuth (O(n&sup3;)&rarr;O(n&sup2;)):</strong> optimal BST; matrix chain multiplication; optimal polygon triangulation (all Stage 3 with QI verified).<br>
                        <strong>Group 6 &mdash; Seg-Tree + DP non-trivial:</strong> LIS with value updates (Stage 3, BIT insufficient); max weight closure (Stage 4); count distinct subsequences (Stage 3).<br>
                        <strong>Group 7 &mdash; SMAWK / totally monotone (advanced):</strong> DP with totally monotone cost matrix &rarr; SMAWK O(n); stronger than D&amp;C; reduces O(n log n) to O(n).<br>
                        <strong>Group 8 &mdash; Offline + DS (CDQ):</strong> 2D LIS O(n log&sup2; n) via CDQ; cross-layer inversion counting via merge sort + BIT.
                    </div>
