                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problem Statement</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>&#x1F527; K-Partition with Varying Costs (S.No 23)</strong><br>
                        <em>Statement:</em> Given array A of n integers (all A[i] &ge; 0), partition into exactly K contiguous subarrays. Cost of [l, r] = (sum A[l..r])&sup2; + w(r&minus;l+1). Minimise total. n &le; 2&times;10&#8309;, K &le; min(n, 200), w &le; 10&#8313;. TL: 2 seconds.<br>
                        <em>Stage:</em> Stage 4 (D&amp;C DP) + Stage 5 (CHT within each D&amp;C call).<br>
                        <em>Approach:</em> dp[k][i] = min cost partitioning A[1..i] into k subarrays. Transition: dp[k][i] = min over j of: dp[k&minus;1][j] + cost(j+1, i). Expand: (prefix[i]&minus;prefix[j])&sup2; + w(i&minus;j) = prefix[i]&sup2; &minus; 2 prefix[i] prefix[j] + prefix[j]&sup2; + wi &minus; wj. For each j, slope = &minus;2 prefix[j], query = prefix[i], intercept = dp[k&minus;1][j] + prefix[j]&sup2; &minus; wj &mdash; a CHT line. Prefix sums monotone (non-negative A) &rarr; deque CHT per D&amp;C call.<br>
                        <em>Insight:</em> D&amp;C outer (monotone opt) + CHT inner (linear structure). Total O(Kn log n) with better constant than pure D&amp;C.<br>
                        <em>Example:</em> A = [3, 4, 5, 7], K = 2, w = 1. [3][4,5,7] &rarr; (9+1)+(256+3) = 269. [3,4][5,7] &rarr; (49+2)+(144+2) = 197. [3,4,5][7] &rarr; (144+3)+(49+1) = 197. Optimal = 197.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>Linguistic:</strong><br>
                        &bull; "Min/max cost with property on contiguous subarray length &le; K" &rarr; sliding window + monotonic deque O(n)<br>
                        &bull; "Partition array into K groups minimising total cost" &rarr; D&amp;C DP if cost satisfies opt monotonicity; O(kn log n)<br>
                        &bull; "Merge adjacent elements with cost = f(combined range)" &rarr; Knuth; verify QI; O(n&sup2;)<br>
                        &bull; "LIS / longest non-decreasing subsequence" &rarr; BIT or patience sort; O(n log n)<br>
                        &bull; "Min cost with transition dp[j] + slope(j)&times;query(i)" &rarr; CHT; check slope &amp; query monotonicity<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural:</strong><br>
                        &bull; O(n&sup2;) TLE with n ~ 10&#8309; AND inner = max/min over j of dp[j] + f(i, j) &rarr; DS optimisation mandatory<br>
                        &bull; Optimal split opt(i) non-decreasing in i (check 3&ndash;4 examples) &rarr; D&amp;C DP or Knuth<br>
                        &bull; 2D interval dp[i][j] O(n&sup3;) &rarr; Knuth if QI<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint:</strong> n &le; 10&#8309; &amp; O(n&sup2;) = 10&#185;&#8304; &rarr; DS opt mandatory; n &le; 5000 &amp; O(n&sup3;) &rarr; Knuth&apos;s O(n&sup2;).<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        &bull; "Max subarray sum (no length constraint)" &rarr; Kadane&apos;s, NOT deque<br>
                        &bull; "Find K-th LIS" &rarr; BIT counting + binary search descent, not pure BIT DP<br>
                        &bull; "LIS with product constraint" &rarr; product doesn&apos;t decompose into slope&times;query
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0;font-size:.78rem"><code>Q1: O(n&sup2;) or O(n&sup3;) DP correct but too slow (n &gt; 10&sup3;)?
Q2: Shape of inner transition: dp[i] = max/min over j of: [expr]?
  Q2a: j in SLIDING WINDOW of fixed size K?
       &rarr; Monotonic DEQUE. O(n). Stage 1. STOP.
  Q2b: j in PREFIX [0, f(i)]?              &rarr; Continue to Q3.
  Q2c: j in ARBITRARY SUBRANGE [g(i), h(i)]?
       &rarr; Segment tree + range max. O(n log n).

Q3: Transition = dp[i] = min over j of: m(j)*x(i) + b(j)?
  YES: CHT. Continue to Q4.
  NO:  Continue to Q5.

Q4: Slopes m(j) monotone?
  YES + queries monotone:      Deque CHT.         O(n).
  YES + queries NON-monotone:  Binary search CHT. O(n log n).
  NO (slopes non-monotone):    Li Chao tree.      O(n log V).

Q5: 2D dp[t][i] with k layers, opt(t, i) monotone in i?
  YES: Divide &amp; Conquer DP. O(kn log n).
       Verify opt monotonicity on 3&ndash;4 manual examples.

Q6: Interval dp[i][j]? Cost satisfies QI?
  YES: Knuth. O(n&sup2;) from O(n&sup3;).
       Verify: cost[a][c]+cost[b][d] &le; cost[a][d]+cost[b][c].

Q7: Range max/min over dp[j] with VALUE constraint (a[j] &lt; a[i])?
  YES: BIT (prefix) or segment tree (range). O(n log n).</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique Breaks</div>
                    <div class="warn-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 1] Deque on VALUE-bounded (not index-bounded) window:</strong> Deque can&apos;t maintain &mdash; elements enter front/back arbitrarily. Fix: BIT or seg tree on compressed values.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 2] Deque CHT with non-monotone queries:</strong> Front pop assumes x[i] &ge; x[i&minus;1]. Fix: keep deque for insertion; BINARY SEARCH for queries. O(n log n).<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 3] D&amp;C DP without verifying opt monotonicity:</strong> Wrong subrange passed to recursion &rarr; silently wrong. Fix: verify on small example. If fails, use Li Chao or different formulation.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 3] Knuth without QI:</strong> opt sandwich doesn&apos;t hold &rarr; wrong answers. Fix: verify on 2&times;2 submatrix. If any (a,b,c,d) fails, Knuth inapplicable.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 4] CHT when slope and query share a variable:</strong> dp[j] + (a[i]&minus;a[j])&sup2; with unsorted a[] &rarr; both slope and query non-monotone. Fix: Li Chao OR sort if DP allows.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 5] Static Li Chao with unbounded slopes:</strong> Out-of-range access. Fix: expand range OR DYNAMIC Li Chao (balanced BST, O(n log&sup2; n)).<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 2] BIT LIS: update before query:</strong> a[i] becomes its own predecessor. Fix: always QUERY first, UPDATE after.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 &mdash; Monotonic Deque Window Max:</strong> <em>Invariant:</em> at start of step i, deque contains subset of [i&minus;K, i&minus;1] in increasing index, DECREASING dp. <em>Maintenance:</em> (1) pop expired from front; (2) pop dominated from back; push current. <em>Correctness:</em> any back-popped element is permanently dominated &mdash; current has &ge; dp AND lasts longer. Front = max. &#9633;<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 &mdash; CHT:</strong> Each j defines line L_j. L_k dominated iff above lower envelope for all x. Lower envelope = lower convex hull, piecewise-linear, O(n) lines. Any non-hull line discardable. Hull maintained by intersection test. Monotone queries &rarr; deque front advances monotonically, O(1) amortised. &#9633;<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 &mdash; D&amp;C DP:</strong> Induct on recursion depth. Base mid: brute-force scan [opt_lo, min(opt_hi, mid&minus;1)] is correct. Left subcall: i &lt; mid &rArr; opt(i) &le; opt(mid) by monotonicity &rArr; [opt_lo, opt(mid)] suffices. Right subcall: symmetric. Total per level O(n); O(log n) levels &rArr; O(n log n). &#9633;
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">
                        <strong>Bug 1 &mdash; BIT LIS: update before query</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>BIT.update(a[i], 1); dp[i] = 1 + BIT.query(a[i])  # BUG
# FIX:
dp[i] = 1 + BIT.query(a[i] - 1); BIT.update(a[i], dp[i])</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 2 &mdash; Deque: expired popped from back</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>while deque and deque[0] &lt; i - K: deque.popleft()  # FIX: FRONT</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 3 &mdash; CHT intersection: wrong strictness</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>return (b3-b1)*(m1-m2) &gt; (b2-b1)*(m1-m3)  # FIX: strict &gt;</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 4 &mdash; Min CHT vs Max CHT:</strong> flip inequality sign for upper hull (max).<br>
                        <strong>Bug 5 &mdash; D&amp;C: wrong arg order</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>solve(l, mid-1, opt_lo, opt_mid)   # left: [opt_lo, opt_mid]
solve(mid+1, r, opt_mid, opt_hi)   # right: [opt_mid, opt_hi]</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 6 &mdash; Knuth fill order: must be by INCREASING interval length d = j&minus;i.</strong><br>
                        <strong>Bug 7 &mdash; Li Chao empty tree:</strong> initialise with sentinel (slope=0, intercept=+inf).<br>
                        <strong>Bug 8 &mdash; CHT equal slopes: division by zero.</strong> Handle BEFORE intersection: if same slope, keep line with better intercept.<br>
                        <strong>Bug 9 &mdash; BIT tuple DP: on equal length, SUM counts (not max).</strong><br>
                        <strong>Bug 10 &mdash; Segment tree DP: propagate lazy BEFORE recursing into children.</strong>
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        &bull; <strong>Not expanding cost before optimising:</strong> Before any DS, expand cost(i, j) into pure-i terms + pure-j terms + PRODUCT f(i)&times;g(j). Only then does CHT/deque applicability become visible.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Using max CHT pop condition for min problem:</strong> Min &rarr; lower hull; max &rarr; upper hull. Inequality flips. Never copy without flipping.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Knuth without QI verification:</strong> Not every interval DP satisfies QI. Verify numerically on a 5-element example before applying.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>D&amp;C: swapping opt bounds:</strong> Single most common D&amp;C DP bug. Left half = [opt_lo, opt_mid]; right = [opt_mid, opt_hi]. Draw the rectangle on paper first.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>CHT on trees without undo on backtrack:</strong> Standard deque CHT has no mid-deque deletion. Need stack-based undo CHT OR rebuild per DFS path.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Confusing opt monotonicity with QI:</strong> QI &rArr; opt monotonicity (Knuth works &rArr; D&amp;C works). Opt monotonicity does NOT &rArr; QI (D&amp;C may work, Knuth may not). Verify independently.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Patience sort when counting LIS required:</strong> Patience gives length only. Counting needs BIT/seg tree tuple DP. Match tool to question.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Stage Push</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">1</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>"LIS uses BIT. What if values change online?"</td><td>BIT offline insufficient. Switch to seg tree on values with point updates. For middle-of-sequence updates, dp[k] for k&gt;j may need recompute. Alternatively offline batch via CDQ D&amp;C sorted by time.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">2</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>"Sliding window DP. What if window is VALUE-bounded (a[i]&minus;a[j] &le; K)?"</td><td>Deque cannot maintain value-bounded window. Fix: BIT indexed by value, query [a[i]&minus;K, a[i]&minus;1]. Index-bounded &rarr; deque; value-bounded &rarr; BIT/seg tree.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">3</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>"Extend D&amp;C k-partition to CIRCULAR array."</td><td>"Break the circle": run D&amp;C on doubled array a[1..2n] with exactly k groups spanning exactly n elements. OR fix first-element of a group; enumerate n choices; but costs O(kn&sup2; log n).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">4</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>"CHT is 1D. What if 2D: dp[i][j] = min over k of dp[i&minus;1][k] + cost(k, j) where cost is CHT-applicable per row?"</td><td>Apply CHT independently per row (fixed i). Build fresh hull using dp[i&minus;1][k] values. Monotone j per row &rarr; deque CHT O(n) per row &rarr; O(kn). Non-monotone &rarr; binary search O(n log n) per row &rarr; O(kn log n).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">5</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>"Weighted DAG, dp[v] = max over u&rarr;v of dp[u] + w(u, v) = f(u)&middot;g(v). Optimise."</td><td>CHT on DAG in topological order. Line y = f(u)&middot;t + dp[u]; query t = g(v). Monotone g(v) &rarr; deque CHT O(V+E log V). Non-monotone &rarr; Li Chao O((V+E) log G).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">6</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>"n buildings, mailbox placement minimising sum of distances to medians."</td><td>Interval DP with cost(l, r) = sum |a[i] &minus; median|. Precompute cost in O(n&sup2;). Verify QI (Monge cost). Knuth &rarr; O(n&sup2;). K mailboxes &rarr; D&amp;C per layer &rarr; O(kn log n).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">7</td><td>Stage 5</td><td>"CHT O(n log n) with binary search. Can you do O(n) with non-monotone queries?"</td><td>If offline: sort queries, apply deque CHT, permute answers &mdash; total O(n log n) sort. True O(n) online requires SMAWK (stronger condition: totally monotone cost matrix). SMAWK finds all row optima in O(n) via reduce+interpolate recursion.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">8</td><td>Stage 5</td><td>"D&amp;C DP O(kn log n). For k up to n, this is O(n&sup2; log n). Can you do O(n log&sup2; n) for all k?"</td><td>Aliens trick (WQS binary search). Key: f(k) = optimal cost with k groups is CONVEX in k. Binary search on penalty &lambda; per group; solve unconstrained problem (each group pays &lambda;) in O(n log n); find &lambda; where k*(&lambda;) = k. Total O(n log&sup2; n).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">9</td><td>Beyond</td><td>"Streaming LIS, n up to 10&#8313;, memory O(&radic;n)."</td><td>Patience sorting maintains LIS stack up to LIS length. With O(&radic;n) memory: sliding window over &radic;n blocks; local patience stacks per block; merge step. Exact O(&radic;n) streaming LIS is open research; approximations exist.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">10</td><td>Beyond</td><td>"Array distributed across D machines. Compute LIS length globally."</td><td>Each machine computes local patience stack (&le; n/D entries). Global merge of D sorted arrays in O((n/D) D log D) = O(n log D). Combined boundary &rarr; global LIS. Total O(n log(n/D)/D + n log D). Optimal D = &radic;(log n) &rarr; O(n &radic;(log n)).</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>
                    <div class="sec-title">3-Phase Mastery Plan</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>Phase 1 &mdash; Solve (by stage, across all sub-variants):</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1 &mdash; Build each DS from scratch, no libs:</strong> S.No 4 (LC 239 sliding window) &rarr; S.No 1 (LC 300 LIS via BIT from scratch) &rarr; S.No 2 (LC 1696 deque + DP).<br>
                        Rule: after each problem state aloud: "the inner scan max over j &isin; [lo, hi] of dp[j] was replaced by ___" &mdash; fill in the DS name.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2:</strong> S.No 5 (LC 1425 zero floor) &rarr; S.No 3 (LC 2407 BIT&rarr;seg tree) &rarr; S.No 7 (LC 673 tuple BIT) &rarr; S.No 8 (LC 1235 binary search + seg tree).<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3 &mdash; CHT (algebraic derivation BEFORE code):</strong> For each CHT problem, write before coding: (1) expand cost(i, j) fully; (2) identify slope(j), query(i), intercept(j); (3) check slope + query monotonicity; (4) choose deque / binary search / Li Chao. Order: S.No 9 (CF 311E deque CHT) &rarr; S.No 11 (CF 660F binary search) &rarr; S.No 12 (CF 319C Li Chao from scratch).<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 &mdash; D&amp;C &amp; Knuth (VERIFY before coding):</strong> For each: write O(n&sup2;)/O(n&sup3;) recurrence; verify opt monotonicity on n=4 manually; for Knuth additionally verify QI on 3&times;3. Order: S.No 14 (CF 321E) &rarr; S.No 15 (CF 868F QI proof) &rarr; S.No 17 (LC 1000 Knuth + K-way) &rarr; S.No 23 (Custom D&amp;C + CHT combined).<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 2 &mdash; Drill:</strong><br>
                        &bull; <strong>DS-from-scratch drill:</strong> BIT (point-update, prefix-max) in 5 min; monotonic deque (push/pop front/pop back/front) in 3 min; Li Chao tree (add_line, query) in 15 min. If any exceeds target, drill daily for a week.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Cost-expansion drill (Stage 3):</strong> for 10 recurrences, expand cost in under 3 min and identify slope(j), query(i), intercept(j). Examples: dp[j]+(a[i]&minus;a[j])&sup2; &rarr; expand; dp[j]+max(a[i], b[j]) &rarr; NOT CHT (max not linear).<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Opt monotonicity drill (Stage 4):</strong> for given cost, determine in under 2 min whether opt is monotone. Examples: cost = (r&minus;l+1)&sup2; &rarr; YES; cost = max(a[l..r]) &rarr; NO (fails QI).<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Pattern identification drill:</strong> from transition formula alone, identify technique: dp[j] + (w[i]&minus;w[j])&sup2; &rarr; CHT; dp[i&minus;1][k] + cost(k, j) with k layers &rarr; D&amp;C per layer; dp[i][k] + dp[k][j] + w[i..j] &rarr; Knuth; max over j &isin; [i&minus;K, i&minus;1] of dp[j] + a[i] &rarr; monotonic deque.<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 3 &mdash; Validate (unseen):</strong><br>
                        &bull; Stage 1: CSES "Sliding Median" (two deques or policy-based tree)<br>
                        &bull; Stage 2: USACO Gold 2021 Feb &mdash; Modern Art 3 (seg tree DP on painting intervals)<br>
                        &bull; Stage 3: AtCoder ABC 289 G &mdash; Shopping in AtCoder (CHT with non-obvious cost)<br>
                        &bull; Stage 4: CF 1603E &mdash; Escape from Tarkov (D&amp;C DP + monotone-opt proof)<br>
                        &bull; Stage 5: ICPC WF 2019 &mdash; Hobson&apos;s Trains (interval DP + QI on geometric cost + Knuth)
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Graduation Test</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Problem 1 &mdash; LC 1235 Maximum Profit in Job Scheduling (Stage 2 + Stage 3)</strong><br>
                        <em>Stages:</em> Stage 2 (BIT/seg tree on coord-compressed end times) + Stage 3 (binary search for latest non-overlapping + sorting transformation).<br>
                        <em>Summary:</em> Jobs with start, end, profit. Maximise profit with no overlaps.<br>
                        <em>Why it proves mastery:</em> Deque-only candidate tries sliding window (wrong &mdash; jobs not contiguous). BIT-only candidate queries wrong range. No-sorting candidate gets wrong transitions. All three (sort by end, binary search for latest compatible, BIT prefix max) must work together in 45 min.<br><br>
                        <strong>Problem 2 &mdash; CF 868F Yet Another Minimization Problem (Stage 3 + Stage 4)</strong><br>
                        <em>Stages:</em> Stage 4 (recognise D&amp;C applies; verify opt monotonicity for squared-sum cost) + Stage 3 (correct D&amp;C bounds).<br>
                        <em>Summary:</em> Partition array into K groups minimising sum of squared sums.<br>
                        <em>Why it proves mastery:</em> Four gates: (1) write O(kn&sup2;) DP; (2) identify k-partition with specific cost; (3) prove opt monotonicity for (sum)&sup2; cost algebraically; (4) implement D&amp;C correctly. Missing any gate fails. Stage 5 reflex: for very large K, apply Aliens trick to reduce to O(n log&sup2; n).<br><br>
                        <strong>Problem 3 &mdash; CF 1603E (Stage 4 + Stage 5: Aliens on D&amp;C DP)</strong><br>
                        <em>Stages:</em> Stage 5 (Aliens / WQS binary search on convex-in-k function) + Stage 4 (inner D&amp;C DP per &lambda; evaluation).<br>
                        <em>Why it proves mastery:</em> Aliens trick is the hardest single optimisation in competitive DP &mdash; requires convexity of f(k), parametric search on &lambda;, inner D&amp;C DP, reconstruction of k. Tests the candidate&apos;s ability to COMPOSE optimisations, not just apply them individually. Combined complexity O(n log n log C).
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="topic-card" id="tp43">
                <div class="topic-header">
                    <div class="topic-num">43</div>
                    <div style="flex:1">
                        <div style="display:flex;align-items:center;gap:.5rem;flex-wrap:wrap">
                            <div class="topic-title">Dynamic Programming &middot; Profile DP / Broken Profile DP</div>
                            <span class="tier-badge tier-T3">Apex Pattern</span>
                            <span class="topic-type">Column-by-Column &middot; Broken Profile &middot; k-ary Profile &middot; Two-Column Profile &middot; Plug DP &middot; Transfer Matrix + Matrix Exp</span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="topic-meta">25 problems &middot; 5 stages &middot; O(m&middot;4&#8319;)&rarr;O(nm&middot;2&#8319;)&rarr;O(8&#8319; log m) with matrix exp</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="topic-body">
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>Why This Topic Matters:</strong> Profile DP (a.k.a. Broken Profile / Plug DP) solves a precise and powerful class: counting or optimising tilings, colourings, and placements on a 2D grid where ONE dimension is small (&le; 14) and the other can be arbitrarily large. The core invariant is the <em>profile</em> &mdash; an n-bit bitmask encoding the "boundary state" between already-processed and not-yet-processed cells. By processing cells in row-major order and updating only the profile at each step, the entire O(2&#8319; &middot; m) state space is managed with zero redundancy. Invisible to candidates who only know standard 2D DP &mdash; the bitmask profile is the non-obvious key. Also the foundation for <strong>Plug DP</strong> (contour DP) which handles arbitrary polyomino placements and Hamiltonian path counting on grids.</div>
                    <div class="sec-title">The Mental Model</div>
                    <div class="info-box"><strong>"Building a wall one brick at a time."</strong> Process cells left-to-right, top-to-bottom. At any moment, the boundary between "done" and "todo" is a jagged vertical line &mdash; the <em>broken profile</em>. An n-bit bitmask captures this boundary: bit i = 1 means row i in the current column is already occupied (by a tile that started in the previous column); bit i = 0 means row i is free. Every transition places exactly one tile, advances the frontier by one cell, and updates the bitmask.<br><br>
                        <strong>5 Stages:</strong><br>
                        &bull; <strong>Stage 1 &mdash; Simplest form:</strong> Profile is one column wide. Tile = 1&times;2 domino (H or V). State = dp[col][mask] where mask = which rows of column col are pre-filled. Column-by-column processing.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Stage 2 &mdash; What changes:</strong> ONE constraint changes &mdash; larger tiles (1&times;3, L-tromino), forbidden cells, or non-rectangular grid. Bitmask width unchanged; transition rules and validity checks change.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Stage 3 &mdash; What expands:</strong> Profile gains a SECOND bitmask (two-column lookahead), OR state includes a counter (tiles &le; K), OR two properties per cell (colour + occupancy). State = dp[col][mask1][mask2] or dp[col][mask][count].<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Stage 4 &mdash; What is hidden:</strong> Problem does NOT say "tiling." It asks about colourings, independent sets, Hamiltonian paths, or max-weight placements. Candidate must MODEL the grid as a profile DP problem &mdash; this modelling IS the difficulty.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Stage 5 &mdash; What is optimised:</strong> Even O(2&#8319; &middot; m &middot; 2&#8319;) too slow (n=10, m=10&#8310;). Precompute transition as a transfer matrix; matrix exponentiation reduces O(m &middot; 4&#8319;) to O(4&#8319; &middot; n&sup2; log m). Or use broken profile cell-by-cell to reduce from 4&#8319; to 2&#8319;.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Core Invariant / Proof Sketch</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Invariant 1: The Profile Sufficiency Lemma.</strong> For a grid tiling problem, the n-bit bitmask of which rows in the current frontier column are pre-occupied is SUFFICIENT to determine the count of valid completions of the remaining grid &mdash; regardless of HOW those pre-occupations were created.<br>
                        <em>Proof sketch:</em> Process cells in row-major order. At cell (r, c), the only info needed from the already-processed region is whether (r, c) itself and (r&minus;1, c) are pre-occupied &mdash; both encoded in the bitmask. Since tiles extend at most one column right or one row down, the profile captures ALL future constraints created by past placements. Therefore dp[c][mask] is well-defined and complete. &#9633;<br><br>
                        <strong>Invariant 2: Broken Profile Cell-by-Cell.</strong> Processing cell by cell instead of column-by-column reduces states touched per cell from O(4&#8319;) to O(2&#8319;).<br>
                        <em>Proof sketch:</em> Column-by-column state = (prev_col_mask, next_col_mask) = O(4&#8319;) pairs per column. Cell-by-cell state = single n-bit mask. Placing a tile at (r, c) changes AT MOST ONE bit (flip bit r). The "broken" profile has bits 0..r&minus;1 referring to column c (processed rows) and bits r..n&minus;1 referring to column c&minus;1 (not-yet-processed). Each transition modifies 1&ndash;2 bits &mdash; O(1) per transition. Total O(n &middot; m &middot; 2&#8319;) vs O(m &middot; 4&#8319;). &#9633;
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Sub-Variants to Master</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>Group 1 &mdash; Classical Tiling (column-by-column):</strong> domino tiling n&times;m (Stage 1, O(m &middot; 4&#8319;)); domino + tromino (Stage 2); 1&times;3 horizontal tile with two-column lookahead (Stage 2, O(m &middot; 8&#8319;)).<br>
                        <strong>Group 2 &mdash; Broken Profile (cell-by-cell):</strong> domino tiling via broken profile (Stage 2, O(nm &middot; 2&#8319;)); forbidden cells (Stage 2); minimum uncovered cells (Stage 3 &mdash; switches from counting to minimisation).<br>
                        <strong>Group 3 &mdash; Colouring &amp; Independent Set:</strong> k-colourings with adjacency constraint (Stage 2, O(m &middot; k&#8319;)); max independent set on grid (Stage 3); max-weight IS on grid (Stage 3).<br>
                        <strong>Group 4 &mdash; Multi-State / Two-Row:</strong> tilings with two tile types + constraint (Stage 3); min tiles to cover (Stage 3); 1&times;2 + 2&times;2 mixed (Stage 3, two-column profile).<br>
                        <strong>Group 5 &mdash; Plug DP (Hamiltonian paths/cycles):</strong> count Hamiltonian paths/cycles on n&times;m grid (Stage 4, O(nm &middot; Catalan(n/2)&sup2;)); TSP on grid (Stage 5).<br>
                        <strong>Group 6 &mdash; Transfer Matrix + Matrix Exp:</strong> tilings with m up to 10&#8313; (Stage 5, O(4&#8319; &middot; n&sup2; log m)); periodic colouring with huge m (Stage 5).<br>
                        <strong>Group 7 &mdash; Hidden Profile DP:</strong> max sum non-adjacent cells n&times;m, n &le; 14 (Stage 4); Sudoku configurations (Stage 4); paint n&times;3 with 3 colours (Stage 4).
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Complexity Staircase</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>Sub-Variant</th><th>Time</th><th>Space</th><th>What Changed</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td>Column-by-column domino tiling</td><td>O(m &middot; 4&#8319;)</td><td>O(2&#8319;)</td><td>Baseline: profile = prev-col mask; enumerate next-col masks</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Broken profile cell-by-cell</td><td>O(nm &middot; 2&#8319;)</td><td>O(2&#8319;)</td><td>Each step flips one bit; halves exponent</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Forbidden cells</td><td>O(nm &middot; 2&#8319;)</td><td>O(2&#8319;)</td><td>Per-cell validity check; constant factor increase</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Minimisation variant</td><td>O(nm &middot; 2&#8319;)</td><td>O(2&#8319;)</td><td>DP stores min cost instead of count</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Two-mask / two-col profile</td><td>O(m &middot; 8&#8319;)</td><td>O(4&#8319;)</td><td>Tiles span 2 columns; profile width doubles</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Max weight IS on grid</td><td>O(m &middot; 2&#8319;)</td><td>O(2&#8319;)</td><td>Counting &rarr; weight max; per-mask weight precomputed</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Plug DP (Hamiltonian paths)</td><td>O(nm &middot; C(n))</td><td>O(nm &middot; C(n))</td><td>Profile encodes plug connectivity; C(n) = Catalan</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>Matrix exponentiation (large m)</td><td>O(8&#8319; log m)</td><td>O(4&#8319;)</td><td>Transfer matrix exponentiated; replaces O(m) with O(log m)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>SMAWK / optimal tiling</td><td>O(n &middot; 2&#8319;)</td><td>O(2&#8319;)</td><td>Totally monotone profile transition matrix</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>
                    <div class="sec-title">State Evolution for Each Sub-Variant Group</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>Group 1: Column-by-Column Profile DP (domino tiling)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0;font-size:.78rem"><code>State: dp[col][mask] = ways to fully tile columns 0..col-1
       with `mask` = pre-fill of column col from horizontal dominoes

Recurrence: to compute dp[col+1][mask_next]:
  for each mask_in with dp[col][mask_in] &gt; 0:
    DFS-fill column col placing vertical dominoes within col,
    and horizontal dominoes extending to col+1 (setting bits in mask_next)
    dp[col+1][mask_next] += dp[col][mask_in]

Base:     dp[0][0] = 1
Terminal: answer = dp[m][0]
Time:     O(m &middot; 4&#8319;)
Optim:    Precompute valid (mask_in, mask_out) pairs ONCE outside main loop</code></pre>
                        <strong>Group 2: Broken Profile Cell-by-Cell</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0;font-size:.78rem"><code>State: dp[r*m + c][mask] = tilings with cells before (r,c) processed

At cell (r, c):
  if mask bit r = 1 (pre-filled):        dp[next][mask XOR (1&lt;&lt;r)] += dp[cell][mask]
  else (free):
    if r+1 &lt; n AND bit r+1 is 0 (vertical domino):
      dp[next][mask OR (1&lt;&lt;(r+1))] += dp[cell][mask]
    if c+1 &lt; m (horizontal domino, pre-fills (r, c+1)):
      dp[next][mask OR (1&lt;&lt;r)] += dp[cell][mask]

Base:     dp[0][0] = 1
Terminal: dp[n*m][0]
Time:     O(n &middot; m &middot; 2&#8319;)</code></pre>
                        <strong>Group 3: k-ary Row Profile (colouring)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0;font-size:.78rem"><code>colour_mask = base-k encoding of colour assignments to n cells in a row
State space: k&#8319; per row (n=3, k=3: 27 states)

Precompute:
  valid_rows = [mask : no_adjacent_same_colour(mask)]
  valid_trans = &#123;(m1, m2) : m1, m2 valid AND no column has same colour&#125;

Recurrence: dp[r+1][m2] += dp[r][m1] for (m1, m2) in valid_trans
Time: O(m &middot; |valid_rows|&sup2;) &mdash; feasible for n=3 k=3 (27&sup2; = 729)</code></pre>
                        <strong>Group 6: Transfer Matrix + Matrix Exponentiation (large m)</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0;font-size:.78rem"><code>T[mask_in][mask_out] = ways to fill ONE column from mask_in to mask_out
  (precomputed via the column-fill DFS)

Answer = (T^m)[0][0]
Time:   O((2&#8319;)&sup3; &middot; log m) = O(8&#8319; log m)

For n=6: 64&times;64 matrix, 60 squarings &asymp; 15M ops &mdash; feasible
For n=10: 1024&times;1024, 60 squarings &asymp; 6.4&times;10&#8313; &mdash; too slow
         (use vector &times; matrix iteration instead of full matrix mul)</code></pre>
                    </div>
