                    <div class="sec-title">Custom Problems</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>&#x1F527; Custom 1 &mdash; L-Tromino Tiling Count (S.No 9)</strong><br>
                        <em>Statement:</em> n&times;m grid (2 &le; n &le; 6, 1 &le; m &le; 10&#8309;). Count tilings using only L-trominoes (4 rotations). Answer mod 10&#8313;+7.<br>
                        <em>Stage:</em> Stage 3 (two-column profile because L-trominoes span 2 rows &times; 2 columns).<br>
                        <em>Approach:</em> State = (mask_left, mask_right). mask_left = pre-fills in column c from trominoes in column c&minus;1; mask_right = pre-fills into column c+1. State space O(4&#8319;); for n=6: 4096. DFS fills one column completely from (mask_left=all-ones) generating mask_right_out. Transfer matrix T[mask_right_in][mask_right_out] = number of ways. For large m: matrix exponentiation O(4&#8319; &middot; n&sup2; log m).<br>
                        <em>Example:</em> n=2, m=4. Answer: 4 (by enumeration).<br><br>
                        <strong>&#x1F527; Custom 2 &mdash; Striped Grid Tiling (S.No 19)</strong><br>
                        <em>Statement:</em> Count tilings of n&times;m grid (n &le; 8, m &le; 10&#185;&#8312;) using only HORIZONTAL 1&times;2 dominoes such that each ROW has an even number of dominoes. Answer mod 10&#8313;+7.<br>
                        <em>Stage:</em> Stage 5 (transfer matrix + matrix exponentiation; m up to 10&#185;&#8312;).<br>
                        <em>Approach:</em> Profile = n-bit mask of pre-fills in current column. For each row the two cells (row, c), (row, c+1) are either both in the same domino or neither is. Valid transitions: T[mask][~mask] = 1 for all masks (every uncovered row gets a rightward domino). Answer = (T&#8319;&#8319;)&#8320;&#8320;.<br>
                        <em>Complexity:</em> O(2&#8319; &middot; 2&#8319; &middot; log m) &mdash; for n=8: 256 &times; 256 &times; 60 &asymp; 4M ops.<br>
                        <em>Example:</em> n=2, m=4: only valid tiling is all horizontal dominoes paired; answer = 1.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Pattern Recognition Triggers</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>Linguistic:</strong><br>
                        &bull; "Count the number of ways to tile/fill/cover an n&times;m grid..." &rarr; Stage 1&ndash;2 Profile DP immediately; n &le; 14 is profile width; O(m &middot; 2&#8319;) or O(nm &middot; 2&#8319;) broken profile<br>
                        &bull; "Fill a grid such that no two adjacent cells have same colour/state..." &rarr; Stage 2 Row-profile DP; each row = profile; valid profiles + adjacent compatibility<br>
                        &bull; "n &le; 10 rows, m up to 10&#8313; columns..." &rarr; Stage 5 Transfer matrix + matrix exp immediately<br>
                        &bull; "Count Hamiltonian paths/cycles on n&times;m grid (n &le; 8)..." &rarr; Stage 4 Plug DP; connectivity profile NOT occupancy; Catalan states<br>
                        &bull; "Max/min score over placements with local adjacency..." &rarr; Stage 3 profile DP optimisation; DP stores max/min; precompute pairwise interaction scores<br><br>
                        <strong>Structural:</strong> grid with min(rows, cols) &le; 14 AND counting/optimising configurations; local-only validity (each cell depends on immediate neighbours) &rArr; profile sufficiency holds.<br><br>
                        <strong>Constraint triggers:</strong> n &le; 6&ndash;8, m &le; 10&#8313; &rArr; matrix exp on 2&#8319; &times; 2&#8319; transfer matrix; n &le; 10&ndash;12, m &le; 10&#8309; &rArr; broken profile direct; n &le; 4&ndash;5 with k = 3&ndash;4 states &rArr; ternary/quaternary profile.<br><br>
                        <strong>Anti-Triggers:</strong><br>
                        &bull; "Shortest path from top-left to bottom-right" &rarr; NOT profile DP &rarr; BFS/Dijkstra or dp[i][j]<br>
                        &bull; "Largest connected component in grid" &rarr; NOT profile DP &rarr; BFS/DFS or Union-Find<br>
                        &bull; "Minimum operations to make all cells equal" &rarr; greedy or BFS; no inter-cell dependency requiring profile
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Decision Framework</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0;font-size:.78rem"><code>Q1: COUNTING or OPTIMISING configurations on 2D grid with LOCAL constraints?
  YES: Proceed.    NO: Not profile DP. Use BFS / standard grid DP / greedy.

Q2: min(rows, cols) &le; 14 (binary) / &le; 8 (ternary) / &le; 6 (k=4&ndash;5)?
  YES: Profile DP applies.    NO: infeasible &mdash; consider FKT or closed form.

Q3: Validity = OCCUPANCY only, or CONNECTIVITY required?
  OCCUPANCY: standard profile DP.
  CONNECTIVITY (Hamiltonian paths/cycles, single component):
    PLUG DP; state = non-crossing matching of plugs; O(Catalan(n)). Stage 4.

Q4: States per cell?
  2 states:                single bitmask &rarr; Stage 1&ndash;2.  O(nm &middot; 2&#8319;).
  k &gt; 2 states:            k-ary profile &rarr; Stage 2.      O(m &middot; k&#8319;).
  Tiles span 2+ columns:   two-column profile &rarr; Stage 3. O(m &middot; 4&#8319;).

Q5: m &gt; 10&#8310;?
  YES: Transfer matrix + matrix exp &rarr; Stage 5. O(8&#8319; log m).
  NO:  Direct DP &rarr; Stage 1&ndash;3.

Q6: Column-by-column or cell-by-cell?
  Col-by-col:  O(m &middot; 4&#8319;); simpler; precompute valid (in, out) pairs.
  Cell-by-cell (broken): O(nm &middot; 2&#8319;); lower exponent; each step flips 1&ndash;2 bits.
  Prefer broken when n &gt; 8.

Troubleshooting (slower than expected):
  1. Precomputed valid (mask_in, mask_out) pairs? Or DFS inside inner loop?
  2. Broken profile (2&#8319;) vs column (4&#8319;)?
  3. Matrix exp for large m?
  4. Pruned invalid single-row masks before DP?</code></pre>
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">When This Technique Breaks</div>
                    <div class="warn-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 1] Both dimensions large (n = m = 100):</strong> 2&#185;&#8304;&#8304; states &mdash; infeasible. Fix: closed-form (e.g., FKT / Kasteleyn eigenvalue product for domino tilings), generating functions, or permanent computation.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 2] Single-column profile when tiles span multiple columns:</strong> 1&times;3 horizontal or L-trominoes cross TWO columns; single-column bitmask misses future pre-fills. Silent wrong answers. Fix: TWO-COLUMN profile; state = two bitmasks; state space 2&#8319; &rarr; 4&#8319;.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 3] Broken profile cell-by-cell with tiles wider than 2 cells:</strong> works for 1&times;2 (each tile changes &le; 2 bits); fails for 1&times;3 or 2&times;3 which span more frontier positions. Fix: extend profile width to cover max tile span.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 4] Simple occupancy profile for Hamiltonian path counting:</strong> occupancy bitmask cannot distinguish ONE connected path from TWO disconnected segments. Fix: PLUG DP with CONNECTIVITY profile (non-crossing matching of 2n plugs; Catalan states).<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 5] Transfer matrix includes invalid transitions:</strong> if T[mask_in][mask_out]=1 for an incomplete column fill, matrix exp counts invalid tilings. Fix: during DFS fill, verify every row of the column is covered EXACTLY ONCE before adding to T.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 3] Off-by-one in broken profile bit indexing:</strong> mixing "this column, row already processed" vs "next column, not yet processed" positions in the bitmask. Fix: explicit comment on which bits = current column (0..r&minus;1) vs next column (r..n&minus;1).
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Proof of Correctness Skeleton</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Stage 1 &mdash; Column DP (domino tiling):</strong> <em>State completeness:</em> dp[c][mask] = valid partial tilings of columns 0..c&minus;1 with mask = pre-fills of column c. <em>Transition correctness:</em> DFS over column-c fill enumerates all valid combinations; setting bits in mask_next records crossing dominoes. <em>No double-counting:</em> each tiling maps to unique (column, mask) sequence. <em>Terminal:</em> dp[m][0] = all tilings with no leftover pre-fill. &#9633;<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2 &mdash; Broken Profile Cell-by-Cell:</strong> <em>Equivalence:</em> at transition (r&minus;1, c) &rarr; (r, c), mask encodes pre-fills of column c rows 0..r&minus;1 (processed) plus column c&minus;1 rows r..n&minus;1 (yet to be processed) &mdash; equivalent to column DP state (prev_mask, partial_next_mask). <em>Per-cell transitions modify 1&ndash;2 bits;</em> memoisation valid by profile sufficiency. &#9633;<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5 &mdash; Matrix Exponentiation:</strong> <em>Matrix interpretation:</em> T[mask_in][mask_out] = ways to fill one column from mask_in to mask_out (by column DP). <em>Multiplication:</em> (T&sup2;)[i][k] = &sum; T[i][j] T[j][k] = ways to fill 2 columns. <em>Induction on k:</em> (T&#8319;)[i][f] = ways to fill k columns. <em>Answer:</em> (T&#8319;&#8319;)[0][0]. &#9633;
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Implementation Pitfalls (Code-Level)</div>
                    <div class="warn-box">
                        <strong>Bug 1 &mdash; Inverted row-to-bit mapping (MSB vs LSB):</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// BUG: bit n-1 = row 0 (inverted)
int bit = 1 &lt;&lt; (n - 1 - r);
// FIX: bit i = row i (LSB = row 0)
int bit = 1 &lt;&lt; r;</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 2 &mdash; Vertical domino without bounds check:</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>if (r + 1 &lt; n &amp;&amp; !(mask &amp; (1&lt;&lt;r)) &amp;&amp; !(mask &amp; (1&lt;&lt;(r+1))))
    // FIX: always check r+1 &lt; n first</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 3 &mdash; Initialising dp[mask]=1 for ALL masks:</strong> only dp[0][0]=1; all other masks mean &quot;impossible pre-fill&quot; at column 0.<br>
                        <strong>Bug 4 &mdash; In-place update (read and write same dp array):</strong> use two arrays dp and dp_next; swap after each column.<br>
                        <strong>Bug 5 &mdash; Two-column profile: wrong carryover role:</strong> explicitly separate mask_left (incoming to current column) from mask_right (carryover to next).<br>
                        <strong>Bug 6 &mdash; Broken profile: advancing column before mask update:</strong> always update mask FIRST (reflect current cell&apos;s placement), THEN advance position.<br>
                        <strong>Bug 7 &mdash; k-ary profile: using power-of-2 shifts for base-k:</strong>
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0"><code>// BUG: binary shift for ternary profile
int colour = (mask &gt;&gt; row) &amp; 1;
// FIX: base-k extraction
int colour = (mask / pow_k[row]) % k;</code></pre>
                        <strong>Bug 8 &mdash; Matrix multiply: transposed indexing:</strong> C[i][j] += A[i][k] * B[k][j] &mdash; NOT B[j][k].<br>
                        <strong>Bug 9 &mdash; Identity matrix initialised as all-zeros:</strong> set identity[i][i] = 1 explicitly.<br>
                        <strong>Bug 10 &mdash; DFS fill called inside main DP loop:</strong> precompute valid_transitions[mask_in] ONCE before the main loop; inner loop is O(1) lookup.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Red Flags / Common Mistakes</div>
                    <div class="warn-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        &bull; <strong>Standard 2D DP dp[i][j] for profile DP problems:</strong> dp[i][j] captures ONE cell&apos;s state; profile DP requires the ENTIRE ROW/COLUMN BOUNDARY state. Ask: "does (i, j) depend on neighbours in a way a scalar can&apos;t summarise?" If yes, bitmask the full boundary.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Wrong profile width for multi-column tiles:</strong> profile width = (max tile column span) &minus; 1. 1&times;2 dominoes &rarr; 1 bit wide; 1&times;3 or L-trominoes &rarr; 2 bits wide (two-column profile). Sketch the widest tile and count columns.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Recomputing valid transitions inside the main loop:</strong> DFS column-fill should run ONCE producing valid_transitions[mask_in]; main loop iterates pre-computed entries in O(1) per transition.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Occupancy bitmask for Hamiltonian paths:</strong> two topologically distinct plug configs can share an occupancy bitmask. Use PLUG DP with PAIRING encoding; O(Catalan(n)) connectivity states instead of O(2&#8319;).<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Missing matrix exp when m is large:</strong> m &gt; 10&#8310; &rArr; O(m &middot; 4&#8319;) TLE. Immediately think "transfer matrix + matrix exp"; cost O(8&#8319; log m).<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Broken profile: advancing before mask updates:</strong> mask must ALWAYS represent the CURRENT cell&apos;s frontier. Update then advance; never batch both operations into one step.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Both dimensions large (n = m = 20):</strong> 2&sup2;&#8304; = 1M states, 2&sup2;&#8304;&sup2; = 10&#185;&sup2; transitions &mdash; infeasible. Always check min(n, m) &le; 14 before choosing profile DP.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Interviewer Follow-Up Questions</div>
                    <div class="tbl-wrap"><table>
                        <thead><tr><th>#</th><th>Stage Push</th><th>Question</th><th>Intended Answer</th></tr></thead>
                        <tbody>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">1</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>"n&times;m grid with 1&times;2 dominoes, some cells pre-BLOCKED. How does profile DP adapt?"</td><td>Blocked cells force their profile bit to be permanently skipped. In broken profile DFS at (r, c): if blocked AND bit r = 0 &rarr; invalid (should be pre-set to 1); if blocked AND bit r = 1 &rarr; just advance without placing a tile. Number of valid configs decreases.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">2</td><td>Stage 2</td><td>"Replace 1&times;2 dominoes with only 1&times;3 trominoes. Complexity?"</td><td>Horizontal 1&times;3 trominoes span 3 columns &rarr; TWO-column profile (2n bits); state dp[col][mask_c][mask_c+1]. Vertical trominoes span 3 rows &rarr; check 3 consecutive bits. DFS fills col c using vertical + horizontal trominoes. O(m &middot; 4&#8319;).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">3</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>"Mix 1&times;2 dominoes AND 2&times;2 squares. How?"</td><td>2&times;2 spans 2 rows + 2 columns &rarr; two-column profile (mask_c, mask_c+1). 2&times;2 placement requires rows r, r+1 both 0 in BOTH mask_c and mask_c+1; sets both bits in mask_c+1. Horizontal 1&times;2 sets one bit; vertical sets two in mask_c.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">4</td><td>Stage 3</td><td>"k colours on n&times;m grid (n &le; 8, k &le; 5). State space?"</td><td>k&#8319; states per row/col; for n=8, k=5: 390,625. Precompute valid single-row masks (no adjacent same colour) and valid adjacent-row transitions (no same colour per column). O(m &middot; |valid_pairs|).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">5</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>"Count INDEPENDENT SETS of size EXACTLY K on n&times;m grid."</td><td>Add counter to state: dp[col][mask][count]; count &isin; 0..K. Transition adds popcount(mask) to count. State space O(m &middot; 2&#8319; &middot; K). For large K: generating function / polynomial in K per profile state.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">6</td><td>Stage 4</td><td>"Count Hamiltonian paths on 4&times;n grid, n up to 10&#8309;."</td><td>Canonical Plug DP. Profile = non-crossing matching of 8 plugs per boundary. Catalan(4)=14 connectivity states per side. O(n &middot; 14&sup2;) per cell; feasible with matrix exp on transfer matrix over plug states.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">7</td><td>Stage 5</td><td>"n=10, m=10&#8313;. O(m &middot; 2&#8319;) = 10&#185;&sup3; too slow."</td><td>Build transfer matrix T[2&#8319; &times; 2&#8319;]; matrix exp T&#8319;&#8319;. Precompute T: O(4&#8319; &middot; n). Mat exp: O((2&#8319;)&sup3; log m). For n=10: 10&#8313; per mul &times; 30 = 3&times;10&#185;&#8304; &mdash; borderline. Use vector&times;matrix iteration (O(4&#8319;) per step) if m has special structure; or reduce n by folding.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">8</td><td>Stage 5</td><td>"Compute transfer matrix T more efficiently than O(n &middot; 4&#8319;)?"</td><td>For each mask_in, DFS-generate valid mask_out incrementally (one row at a time, O(1) branch per row). Total O(2&#8319;) per starting mask &rarr; O(n &middot; 4&#8319;) overall (same asymptotic, much better constant).</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">9</td><td>Beyond</td><td>"n=m=10&#8310;. Count domino tilings. Research-level."</td><td>FKT algorithm: closed-form product over eigenvalues of grid graph&apos;s Kasteleyn adjacency. # tilings = &prod; (4cos&sup2;(&pi;j/(n+1)) + 4cos&sup2;(&pi;k/(m+1))) over appropriate j, k ranges. O(nm) multiplications with multi-precision for exact count.</td></tr>
                        <tr><td class="num-cell">10</td><td>Beyond</td><td>"Online: grid revealed cell by cell. Output current partial tiling count after each reveal."</td><td>Broken profile cell-by-cell is naturally streaming-compatible &mdash; each cell processes independently of future cells. Update DP vector in O(2&#8319;) per reveal. Total O(nm &middot; 2&#8319;), memory O(2&#8319;).</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table></div>
                    <div class="sec-title">3-Phase Mastery Plan</div>
                    <div class="info-box" style="line-height:1.75">
                        <strong>Phase 1 &mdash; Solve (by stage, across all sub-variants):</strong><br>
                        <strong>Stage 1:</strong> S.No 1 (LC 790 &mdash; write 4-state column DP explicitly; label each state; verify 2&times;3 by hand) &rarr; S.No 2 (Parquet; generalise to n-bit bitmask; write column DFS; verify transitions for n=3 manually). <em>Rule:</em> after S.No 2, draw transition graph for n=2 (4 masks); verify 2&times;2 count = 2.<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 2:</strong> S.No 3 (Broken Profile; re-implement S.No 2 cell-by-cell; verify identical answers on small grids) &rarr; S.No 4 (LC 1931; precompute valid single-row masks AND valid pairs BEFORE coding DP) &rarr; S.No 6 (CF 318C; add forbidden cells; verify 3&times;3 with one forbidden).<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 3:</strong> S.No 5 (LC 1659 ternary profile; precompute all happiness interaction scores) &rarr; S.No 8 (LC 1411; 27 row masks + 27&times;27 pairs) &rarr; S.No 9 (Custom L-Tromino two-column DFS, verify all 4 rotations) &rarr; S.No 10 (COCI Selotejp 2&times;2 tile).<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 4 &mdash; Identification before implementation:</strong> for each S.No 12&ndash;16, write BEFORE coding: "This IS profile DP because ___. The profile represents ___. State space = ___." Order: S.No 12 (LC 464 bitmask over integers) &rarr; S.No 13 (LC 473 buckets = columns) &rarr; S.No 14 (LC 3276 row-availability) &rarr; S.No 11 (CF 11D Plug DP, 2 hours allowed).<br><br>
                        <strong>Stage 5:</strong> S.No 18 (ABC 215 H; verify T&sup1; = single-column transitions; T&sup2; matches two-column DP) &rarr; S.No 19 (Custom Striped; derive T[mask][~mask]=1 analytically before coding).<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 2 &mdash; Drills:</strong><br>
                        &bull; <strong>10-min drill:</strong> write complete column-fill DFS for 1&times;2 dominoes in &lt; 8 min; test n=4.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Profile design drill:</strong> for any problem, write in 2 min &mdash; (1) what the bitmask represents, (2) width, (3) state space, (4) transition type. Do 5 problems before coding any.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Transition precomputation drill:</strong> DFS generating all valid (mask_in, mask_out) pairs in &lt; 10 min; target &lt; 5 min with practice.<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Matrix exp drill:</strong> implement T&#8319; in &lt; 10 min; verify on identity (gives identity) and Fibonacci matrix [[1,1],[1,0]].<br>
                        &bull; <strong>Recognition drill:</strong> given only constraints, identify (a) standard profile DP, (b) two-column, (c) plug DP, or (d) profile + matrix exp in &lt; 30 seconds.<br><br>
                        <strong>Phase 3 &mdash; Validate (unseen):</strong><br>
                        &bull; Stage 1: CSES "Counting Tilings" (n &le; 10, m &le; 10&#8310;) &mdash; broken profile + matrix exp on first attempt<br>
                        &bull; Stage 2: CF 417D "Lossy Compression" &mdash; profile DP on coloured grid segments<br>
                        &bull; Stage 3: AtCoder DP Contest "Matching" &mdash; bitmask DP on bipartite graph<br>
                        &bull; Stage 4: IOI 2008 "Linear Garden" &mdash; Hamiltonian path on thin grid (plug DP)<br>
                        &bull; Stage 5: CF 1103E "Panoramic Facade" &mdash; profile DP + matrix exp, m up to 10&#185;&sup2;
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Graduation Test</div>
                    <div class="core-box">
                        <strong>Problem 1 &mdash; LC 1931 Painting a Grid With Three Different Colors (Stage 2 + Stage 3)</strong><br>
                        <em>Stages:</em> Stage 2 (ternary row profile, 3&#8319; states; intra-row + inter-row validity) + Stage 3 (precompute valid single-row masks AND valid adjacent-row pairs before DP).<br>
                        <em>Why it proves mastery:</em> Binary-only candidate cannot handle ternary. Candidate without precomputation TLE (3&sup2;&#8319; per step). Solving in 45 min shows: (1) binary&rarr;k-ary generalisation, (2) precomputation discipline, (3) efficient DP implementation.<br><br>
                        <strong>Problem 2 &mdash; LC 1659 Maximize Grid Happiness (Stage 3 + Stage 4)</strong><br>
                        <em>Stages:</em> Stage 4 (recognise profile DP from an optimisation/placement problem with n &le; 5) + Stage 3 (ternary profile, 3 cell states, precompute pairwise interaction scores).<br>
                        <em>Why it proves mastery:</em> Problem is presented as placement/optimisation &mdash; profile DP is completely hidden. Recognising "n &le; 5 = ternary profile, 243 states" within 5 minutes is the Stage 4 recognition reflex. Ternary-profile implementation under pressure tests generalisation from binary to k-ary.<br><br>
                        <strong>Problem 3 &mdash; CF 11D A Simple Task (Stage 4 + Stage 5: Plug DP)</strong><br>
                        <em>Stages:</em> Stage 4 (recognise connectivity profile required; occupancy bitmask INSUFFICIENT) + Stage 5 (Catalan-number connectivity state encoding, plug transitions, cycle closure).<br>
                        <em>Why it proves mastery:</em> Simple occupancy DP gives WRONG answers silently. Identifying that connectivity encoding is required AND implementing plug transitions (merge on connect, split on new segment, detect cycle closure at last cell) within 45 min is the gold standard for Profile / Plug DP mastery. Stage 5 implementation bookkeeping (canonical form of connectivity state) is the final differentiator.
                    </div>
                    <div class="sec-title">Quick Reference Summary</div>
                    <div class="info-box">
                        <pre style="white-space:pre-wrap;margin:.4rem 0;font-size:.78rem"><code>PROFILE DP SIGNAL:  min(rows, cols) &le; 14, counting/optimising grid configs
STATE:              dp[col][mask] or dp[cell][mask]
PROFILE:            n-bit bitmask = frontier occupancy of small dimension

VARIANT           | TIME          | WHEN
Col-by-col        | O(m &middot; 4&#8319;)   | n &le; 7,   m &le; 10&#8310;
Broken profile    | O(nm &middot; 2&#8319;)  | n &le; 10,  m &le; 10&#8309;
k-ary profile     | O(m &middot; k&#8319;)   | k colours, n &le; 8
Two-col profile   | O(m &middot; 8&#8319;)   | tiles span 2 cols
Matrix exp        | O(8&#8319; log m)  | m &gt; 10&#8310;
Plug DP           | O(nm &middot; C(n))  | Hamiltonian paths/cycles

GOLDEN RULES:
  - PRECOMPUTE valid (mask_in, mask_out) pairs BEFORE main loop
  - VERIFY every row covered EXACTLY ONCE in column-fill DFS
  - TRAP: both dims large &rarr; FKT / formula, NOT profile DP
  - TRAP: connectivity needed &rarr; Plug DP, NOT occupancy bitmask
  - ORIENT grid so n = min(rows, cols) before writing bitmask</code></pre>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>
    </div>

